{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea", "text_new": "{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 pandemic in North Korea}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case = \n| location = [[North Korea]]\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| arrival_date =\n| image = \n| caption = \n| recovery_cases = \n| deaths =\n| confirmed_cases = 0\n| suspected_cases =\n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\n{{Politics of North Korea|width=22.0em}}\n\nThere are no officially confirmed cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[North Korea]], although South Korean sources state that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the pandemic]] is steadily affecting the country. The virus is more likely to have come into North Korea from [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]], where the virus originated, than from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]]. The [[China\u2013North Korea border|Chinese-North Korean border]] restrictions are more relaxed than the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone|heavily militarized border]] between North and South Korea. However, suspected COVID-19 cases in the two Chinese provinces ([[Liaoning]] and [[Jilin]]) bordering North Korea have been low.<ref name=\"Who Knows\">{{Cite web |title=Who Knows How Many Virus Cases North Korea Has. It Says Zero |last1=Wainer |first1=David |last2=Lee |first2=Jihye |work=Bloomberg.com |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-16/north-korea-s-official-virus-tally-zero-experts-aren-t-so-sure }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nNorth Korea is an impoverished country with a [[Healthcare in North Korea|weak healthcare system]] and [[Sanctions against North Korea|is subject to sanctions]], rendering it vulnerable in the event of an outbreak.<ref>{{cite news |title=South Korea says detected North Korea missile fire 'inapproriate' amid coronavirus |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/21/north-korea-fired-suspected-short-range-missiles-south-korea-says.html |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/> There is concern that widespread malnutrition could exacerbate the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> North Korean public health official Pak Myong-su said that if the disease spread in North Korea, \"a serious disaster could not be avoided\".<ref name=\"Mainichi 2 April\"/>\n\nDiplomatically and economically isolated,<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> the country borders China, the starting point of the pandemic, which is North Korea's closest ally, most important trading partner, and a source of tourists.<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/><ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\">{{cite news |last1=Sang-Hun |first1=Choe |title=North Korea Claims No Coronavirus Cases. Can It Be Trusted? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/world/asia/north-korea-coronavirus.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korea's government is secretive and the media are tightly controlled, making it hard for outside observers to determine what is really going on in the country.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/>\n\nHistorically, North Korea has restricted travel in the face of epidemics abroad, for instance during the [[2014 Ebola epidemic]].<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/> Moreover, the country has had success in disease eradication in the past; it reportedly eliminated [[measles]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patel |first1=Minal K. |title=Progress Toward Regional Measles Elimination \u2014 Worldwide, 2000\u20132018 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/68/wr/mm6848a1.htm |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |date=2019 |language=en-us |doi=10.15585/mmwr.mm6848a1}}</ref><ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> [[Government of North Korea|North Korea's government]] is highly [[totalitarian]] and maintains strict control over the country and its society, which experts anticipated could help in enforcing disease control measures such as [[social distancing]].<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Why North Korea's healthcare sector is better equipped than many believe |url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/why-north-koreas-healthcare-sector-is-better-equipped-than-many-believe/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=NK News - North Korea News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> North Korea also has a large number of doctors, though they are less skilled and equipped than their Western counterparts, and a high level of public hygiene.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why North Korea's healthcare sector is better equipped than many believe |url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/why-north-koreas-healthcare-sector-is-better-equipped-than-many-believe/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=NK News - North Korea News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\n[[File:Masikryong-Hotel-and-Lift.jpg|200px|thumb|left|[[Masikryong Ski Resort]], a popular ski resort in North Korea. Due to the outbreak of the virus, ski resorts and spas in North Korea have been closed.]]\n\nNorth Korea was one of the first countries to close borders due to COVID-19.<ref name=\"Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way\"/> The government has implemented widespread travel restrictions,<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\">{{cite news |last1=Shinkman |first1=Paul D. |title=North Korea Opens Borders to Aid Amid Coronavirus Threat |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world-report/articles/2020-03-13/north-korea-opens-borders-to-aid-amid-coronavirus-threat |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> including closing the border to foreign tourists in late January 2020<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\">{{cite news |title=North Korea Bars Foreign Tourists Amid Virus Threat, Groups Say |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-22/north-korea-bars-foreign-tourists-amid-virus-threat-groups-say |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=22 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and then suspending flights and banning travel in and out of the country.<ref name=\"Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way\">{{cite news |title=Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way |url=https://www.38north.org/2020/02/eimaabrahamian022020/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=38 North |date=20 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Though many parts of the border were closed, the bridge between [[Dandong]] and [[Sinuiju]] remained open and allowed supplies to be delivered.<ref name=\"Russia Delivers\">{{cite news |title=Russia Delivers Coronavirus Test Kits to North Korea |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world-report/articles/2020-03-12/russia-delivers-coronavirus-test-kits-to-north-korea |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> In late February, the North Korean government said that it would keep the border closed until a cure was found.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\"/>\n\nThe possibility of a COVID-19 outbreak in North Korea is a concern to international organizations and observers due to the country's poverty and low-quality healthcare infrastructure. Outside organizations have provided aid to help the country fight the virus: the Russian government provided [[COVID-19 testing|test kits]],<ref name=\"Russia Delivers\"/> the [[World Health Organization]] announced plans to send supplies despite the lack of confirmed cases, and the [[International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies]], [[U.S. State Department]], and South Korean government all indicated willingness to help.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> The U.S. government worked with the United Nations to make exceptions to sanctions, though they were also criticized for slowing down the process for providing aid.<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\"/> [[Doctors Without Borders]] said in late March that supplies of diagnostic equipment and [[personal protective equipment]] were stranded on the Chinese border.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/two-foreigners-left-under-quarantine-in-north-korea-state-media/?t=1585324059464|title=Only two foreigners remain under quarantine in North Korea, state media says|first=Jeongmin|last=Kim|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn early February, the [[North Korean government]] took severe measures to block the spread of the coronavirus. ''[[Rodong Sinmun]]'', the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] newspaper, reported that the customs officials at [[Nampho]] port were performing disinfection activities, including placing imported goods in quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://kcnawatch.org/newstream/1583703072-617647256/\uac80\uc0ac\uac80\uc5ed\uc744-\uc0ac\uc18c\ud55c-\ube48\ud2c8\ub3c4-\uc5c6\uac8c/ |script-title=ko:\uac80\uc0ac\uac80\uc5ed\uc744 \uc0ac\uc18c\ud55c \ube48\ud2c8\ub3c4 \uc5c6\uac8c |language=ko |date=2020-03-09 |accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref> All international flights and railway services were suspended in early February, and connections by sea and road were largely closed over the following weeks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February, wearing face masks was obligatory and visiting public places such as restaurants was forbidden. Ski resorts and spas were closed and military parades, marathons, and other public events were cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchools were closed throughout the country; university students in Pyongyang from elsewhere in the country were confined to their dormitories.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joo |first1=Jeong Tae |title=Sources: N. Korea extends school closures until April 15 |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-north-korea-extends-school-closures-until-april-15/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Daily NK |date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"N Korea closes schools\">{{cite news |last1=Joo |first1=Jeong Tae |title=N. Korea closes schools throughout the country for one month |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-closes-schools-throughout-country-one-month/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Daily NK |date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korean citizens returning from other countries were subjected to a 40-day isolation period to which was added a 30-day \u201cmedical observation\u201d period. According to North Korean media, nearly 7,000 North Koreans were subjected to these rules on 1 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the North Korean government, 10,000 people had been quarantined by the end of March.<ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\"/> From 12 February, the 14-day quarantine on all foreigners (including their local staff) was extended to 30 days.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Diplomats and other foreigners were evacuated to [[Vladivostok]] in March.<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\"/><ref name=\"Russia Delivers\"/> By 27 March, according to North Korean media, there were only two foreigners in quarantine and 2280 North Koreans were under \"medical observation\" in areas such as [[South Phyongan]] province and [[North Phyongan]] province, [[Ryanggang]] province, and the city of [[Rason]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/two-foreigners-left-under-quarantine-in-north-korea-state-media/?t=1585324059464|title=Only two foreigners remain under quarantine in North Korea, state media says|first=Jeongmin|last=Kim|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe North Korean military fired five missiles on two occasions in early March 2020, which may be \"an effort to ensure the country remains on the agenda for other nations amid the virus outbreak\".<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> More missile tests followed in late March, along with an announcement that the [[Supreme People's Assembly]] would meet in early April. Foreign observers said the government was trying to show confidence in their handling of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Missile tests and meetings: North Korea signals confidence in face of coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-northkorea-analysi/missile-tests-and-meetings-north-korea-signals-confidence-in-face-of-coronavirus-idUSKBN21A0O7 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The South Korean military called the provocation \"extremely inappropriate\" in light of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea Fires Missile Into East Sea |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-28/north-korea-fires-missile-into-east-sea-s-korea-military-says |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2020, North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-un]] ordered the construction of new hospitals.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/kim-jong-un-north-korea-hospital-coronavirus |title = Kim Jong Un orders workers to build new hospitals as North Korea continues to claim no coronavirus cases |work=[[Fox News]] |date = 2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nKim Jong-un sent a letter to South Korean president [[Moon Jae-in]] as a show of support amidst the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|outbreak in South Korea]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Top U.S. Commander 'Fairly Certain' North Korea Has Virus Cases |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-14/top-u-s-commander-fairly-certain-north-korea-has-virus-cases |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=14 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Donald Trump]] wrote a letter to [[Kim Jong-un]] to express his willingness to work with him on dealing with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea says Trump wrote Kim, offered coronavirus cooperation |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-northkorea-idUSKBN2180YX |work=Reuters |date=2020-03-21}}</ref> North Korean state media has reported on the severity of the outbreak in other countries.<ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\"/>\n\nOn 31 March 2020, the ''[[Asia Times]]'' reported that North Korea's measures against the pandemic seemed largely successful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/03/north-koreas-silent-struggle-against-covid-19/|title=North Korea's silent struggle against Covid-19|first=Gabriela|last=Bernal|publisher=Asian Times|date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Edwin Salvador, WHO's representative in North Korea, reported that as of 2 April, 709 people had been tested, with no confirmed cases, and 509 people were in quarantine.<ref>{{cite new|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-northkorea/north-korea-testing-quarantining-for-covid-19-still-says-no-cases-who-representative-idUSKBN21P3C2|title=North Korea testing, quarantining for COVID-19, still says no cases: WHO representative|first=Stephanie|last=Nebehay|publisher=Reuters|date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, Kim Jong-un presided over a meeting of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Politburo]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]. The meeting adopted a joint resolution by the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]], [[State Affairs Commission of North Korea|State Affairs Commission]] and the [[Cabinet of North Korea|Cabinet]], \u201cOn more thoroughly taking national measures for protecting the life and safety of our people from the worldwide epidemic disease\u201d. The resolution called to take strict national countermeasures to thoroughly check the inroads of the virus due to the steady spread of the epidemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/04/kim-jong-un-guides-saturdays-politburo-meeting-ahead-of-spa-state-media/|title=North Korea's Politburo discusses \"danger\" from COVID-19, promotes officials|first=Gabriela|last=Bernal|publisher=Asian Times|date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nAlthough South Korean media shared news hinting at the spread of the COVID-19 epidemic to North Korea, the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] denied the veracity of such claims. On 18 February, ''Rodong Sinmun'' quoted a public health official reiterating the country had had \"no confirmed case of the new coronavirus so far\". The WHO prioritised aid for North Korea, including the shipment of protective equipment and supplies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/who-says-no-signs-of-coronavirus-cases-in-north-korea.html|title=World Health Organization says there are 'no indications' of coronavirus cases in North Korea|publisher=CNBC|date=19 February 2020|access-date=19 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219100113/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/who-says-no-signs-of-coronavirus-cases-in-north-korea.html|archive-date=19 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Military===\nIn early March, the North Korean government continued to deny that they had any cases of [[COVID-19]]. However, according to [[South Korea]]n media outlet ''[[Daily NK]]'', 180 soldiers had died. There was no estimate of those merely infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3074377/coronavirus-nearly-200-north-korea-soldiers-die-outbreak|title=Coronavirus: nearly 200 North Korea soldiers 'die from outbreak government refuses to acknowledge'|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February and March, U.S. officials observed a decrease in military activity in North Korea, believed to be a sign that there are COVID-19 cases in the country.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> General [[Robert B. Abrams]] observed that the North Korean military had \"been on lockdown for about 30 days\" and \"didn\u2019t fly an airplane for 24 days\".<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/>\n\n===Political===\nThe underground network that assists [[North Korean defectors|defectors in escaping North Korea]] has been almost unable to operate amidst strict controls implemented to stop the virus, with defection attempts being suspended.<ref name=\"Group of North Korean women and children\">{{cite news |title=Group of North Korean women and children escape coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.ft.com/content/253d5ff0-63e9-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=www.ft.com |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Defection rates had been declining already, probably due to increased security under the administrations of [[Kim Jong-un]] in North Korea and [[Xi Jinping]] in China.<ref name=\"Group of North Korean women and children\"/>\n\n===Economic===\nOn 26 March, the New York Times reported satellite imagery shared by the [[Royal United Services Institute]], which showed that the illicit trafficking of coal and other goods stopped, with the commercial vessels now idling in their home ports.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/video/coronavirus-north-korea.html</ref> This trafficking is prohibited under United Nations sanctions, and is believed to be mostly with China. The change happened after North Korea sought to seal itself off starting 22 January. These sales normally provide a revenue stream that has historically contributed to its nuclear and ballistic missile programs. It may also cause a possible drop in fuel and fertilizer imports, which would affect North Korea's agriculture sector, right at the beginning of the farming season. Analysts said it was reasonable to assume damage has been done to North Korean agriculture, industry and the overall economy.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Timeline==\n===January 2020===\nFrom 23 January, North Korea banned [[Tourism in North Korea|foreign tourists]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/north-korea-to-temporarily-ban-tourists-over-wuhan-virus-fears-says-tour-company|title=North Korea to temporarily ban tourists over Wuhan virus fears, says tour company|last=hermesauto|date=21 January 2020|website=The Straits Times|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January, suspected cases in [[Sinuiju]] were quarantined.{{update inline|date=February 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-quarantines-suspected-coronavirus-cases-sinuiju/|title=N. Korea quarantines suspected coronavirus cases in Sinuiju|website=Daily NK|date=28 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130223216/https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-quarantines-suspected-coronavirus-cases-sinuiju/|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January, North Korea's news agency [[KCNA]] declared a \"state emergency\" and reported the establishment of anti-epidemic headquarters around the country.<ref name=\"20200206cnn\">{{cite news |last1=Berlinger |first1=Joshua |last2=Seo |first2=Yoonjung |title=All of its neighbors have it, so why hasn't North Korea reported any coronavirus cases? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/06/asia/north-korea-wuhan-coronavirus-infection-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207093221/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/06/asia/north-korea-wuhan-coronavirus-infection-intl-hnk/index.html |archive-date=7 February 2020 |accessdate=7 February 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 2 February, KCNA reported that all the people who had entered the country after 13 January were placed under \"medical supervision\".<ref name=\"20200206cnn\"/>\n\nOn 7 February, South Korean media outlet ''[[Daily NK]]'' claimed that five North Koreans in [[Sinuiju]] on the Chinese border died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-five-north-koreans-died-coronavirus-infections/|title=Sources: Five N. Koreans died from coronavirus infections|author=Jang Seul Gi|website=Daily NK|date=7 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208082046/https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-five-north-koreans-died-coronavirus-infections/|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Within the same day, ''[[The Korea Times]]'' reported that a North Korean female living in the capital [[Pyongyang]] was infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news/section/3/141479/Coronavirus-spreads-to-North-Korea,-woman-infected|title=Coronavirus spreads to North Korea, woman infected|website=The Standard|location=Hong Kong|date=7 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208082206/https://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news/section/3/141479/Coronavirus-spreads-to-North-Korea,-woman-infected|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite no confirmation by North Korean authorities on the claims, the country has implemented stricter measures to combat the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pyongyangtimes.com.kp/?bbs=33091|title=Nation steps up fight against novel CoV|website=The Pyongyang Times|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rodong.rep.kp/en/index.php?strPageID=SF01_02_01&newsID=2020-02-08-0001|title=Work to Curb the Inflow of Infectious Disease Pushed ahead with|website=Rodong Sinmun|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchools were closed starting on 20 February.<ref name=\"N Korea closes schools\"/>\n\nOn 29 February, [[Kim Jong-un]] called for stronger measures to be taken to prevent COVID-19 from spreading to North Korea.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/kim-warns-consequences-virus-spreads-korea-200229061648473.html | title=Kim warns of 'serious consequences' if virus spreads to N Korea |work=al Jazeera}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\nOn 14 March 2020, North Korea state media reported there were no confirmed cases in its territory.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kim |first1=Stella |last2=Hagen |first2=Isobel |date=March 14, 2020 |title=North Korea claims it has no coronavirus cases |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/live-blog/coronavirus-updates-live-house-approves-coronavirus-aid-bill-n1158821/ncrd1158881#liveBlogHeader |work=NBC News |access-date=March 14, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2020, [[Kim Jong-un]] ordered the construction of new hospitals in North Korea. North Korean state media also reported that groundbreaking on a new hospital was underway the day prior on Tuesday 17 March. Kim Jong-un reportedly told a newspaper linked to the ruling [[Workers' Party of Korea]] that the construction of new hospitals were being done for general improvement of the nation's healthcare system without mentioning COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/kim-jong-un-north-korea-hospital-coronavirus |title = Kim Jong Un orders workers to build new hospitals as North Korea continues to claim no coronavirus cases |work=[[Fox News]] |date = 2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, North Korean media stated that more than 2,590 people had been released from quarantine in [[North Pyongan]] and [[South Pyongan]] provinces. All but three quarantined foreigners had been released.<ref name=\"aa.com.tr 21\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19: North Korea releases quarantined people |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19-north-korea-releases-quarantined-people/1773332 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 1 April 2020, North Korean public health official Pak Myong-su repeated the claim that North Korea has no cases of the virus.<ref name=\"Mainichi 2 April\">{{cite news |title=N. Korea has no infected people with new coronavirus: expert |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200402/p2g/00m/0in/025000c |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Mainichi Daily News |date=2 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On 23 April 2020, it was reported that the country has taken 740 coronavirus tests, and all of them came back negative.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Norman |first1=Greg |title=North Korea claims 740 coronavirus tests came back negative, thousands released from quarantine |url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/north-korea-claims-740-coronavirus-tests-come-back-negative |website=Fox News |accessdate=24 April 2020 |date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Health in North Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Medicine|North Korea|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|North Korea]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|North Korea]]\n[[Category:2020 in North Korea|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in North Korea]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 pandemic in North Korea}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case = \n| location = [[North Korea]]\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| arrival_date =\n| image = \n| caption = \n| recovery_cases = \n| deaths =\n| confirmed_cases = 0\n| suspected_cases =\n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\n{{Politics of North Korea|width=22.0em}}\n\nThere are no officially confirmed cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[North Korea]], although South Korean sources state that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the pandemic]] is steadily affecting the country. The virus is more likely to have come into North Korea from [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]], where the virus originated, than from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]]. The [[China\u2013North Korea border|Chinese-North Korean border]] restrictions are more relaxed than the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone|heavily militarized border]] between North and South Korea. However, suspected COVID-19 cases in the two Chinese provinces ([[Liaoning]] and [[Jilin]]) bordering North Korea have been low.<ref name=\"Who Knows\">{{Cite web |title=Who Knows How Many Virus Cases North Korea Has. It Says Zero |last1=Wainer |first1=David |last2=Lee |first2=Jihye |work=Bloomberg.com |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-16/north-korea-s-official-virus-tally-zero-experts-aren-t-so-sure }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nNorth Korea is an impoverished country with a [[Healthcare in North Korea|weak healthcare system]] and [[Sanctions against North Korea|is subject to sanctions]], rendering it vulnerable in the event of an outbreak.<ref>{{cite news |title=South Korea says detected North Korea missile fire 'inapproriate' amid coronavirus |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/21/north-korea-fired-suspected-short-range-missiles-south-korea-says.html |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/> There is concern that widespread malnutrition could exacerbate the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> North Korean public health official Pak Myong-su said that if the disease spread in North Korea, \"a serious disaster could not be avoided\".<ref name=\"Mainichi 2 April\"/>\n\nDiplomatically and economically isolated,<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> the country borders China, the starting point of the pandemic, which is North Korea's closest ally, most important trading partner, and a source of tourists.<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/><ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\">{{cite news |last1=Sang-Hun |first1=Choe |title=North Korea Claims No Coronavirus Cases. Can It Be Trusted? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/world/asia/north-korea-coronavirus.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korea's government is secretive and the media are tightly controlled, making it hard for outside observers to determine what is really going on in the country.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/>\n\nHistorically, North Korea has restricted travel in the face of epidemics abroad, for instance during the [[2014 Ebola epidemic]].<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/> Moreover, the country has had success in disease eradication in the past; it reportedly eliminated [[measles]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patel |first1=Minal K. |title=Progress Toward Regional Measles Elimination \u2014 Worldwide, 2000\u20132018 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/68/wr/mm6848a1.htm |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |date=2019 |language=en-us |doi=10.15585/mmwr.mm6848a1}}</ref><ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> [[Government of North Korea|North Korea's government]] is highly [[totalitarian]] and maintains strict control over the country and its society, which experts anticipated could help in enforcing disease control measures such as [[social distancing]].<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Why North Korea's healthcare sector is better equipped than many believe |url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/why-north-koreas-healthcare-sector-is-better-equipped-than-many-believe/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=NK News - North Korea News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> North Korea also has a large number of doctors, though they are less skilled and equipped than their Western counterparts, and a high level of public hygiene.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why North Korea's healthcare sector is better equipped than many believe |url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/why-north-koreas-healthcare-sector-is-better-equipped-than-many-believe/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=NK News - North Korea News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\n[[File:Masikryong-Hotel-and-Lift.jpg|200px|thumb|left|[[Masikryong Ski Resort]], a popular ski resort in North Korea. Due to the outbreak of the virus, ski resorts and spas in North Korea have been closed.]]\n\nNorth Korea was one of the first countries to close borders due to COVID-19.<ref name=\"Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way\"/> The government has implemented widespread travel restrictions,<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\">{{cite news |last1=Shinkman |first1=Paul D. |title=North Korea Opens Borders to Aid Amid Coronavirus Threat |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world-report/articles/2020-03-13/north-korea-opens-borders-to-aid-amid-coronavirus-threat |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> including closing the border to foreign tourists in late January 2020<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\">{{cite news |title=North Korea Bars Foreign Tourists Amid Virus Threat, Groups Say |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-22/north-korea-bars-foreign-tourists-amid-virus-threat-groups-say |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=22 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and then suspending flights and banning travel in and out of the country.<ref name=\"Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way\">{{cite news |title=Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way |url=https://www.38north.org/2020/02/eimaabrahamian022020/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=38 North |date=20 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Though many parts of the border were closed, the bridge between [[Dandong]] and [[Sinuiju]] remained open and allowed supplies to be delivered.<ref name=\"Russia Delivers\">{{cite news |title=Russia Delivers Coronavirus Test Kits to North Korea |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world-report/articles/2020-03-12/russia-delivers-coronavirus-test-kits-to-north-korea |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> In late February, the North Korean government said that it would keep the border closed until a cure was found.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\"/>\n\nThe possibility of a COVID-19 outbreak in North Korea is a concern to international organizations and observers due to the country's poverty and low-quality healthcare infrastructure. Outside organizations have provided aid to help the country fight the virus: the Russian government provided [[COVID-19 testing|test kits]],<ref name=\"Russia Delivers\"/> the [[World Health Organization]] announced plans to send supplies despite the lack of confirmed cases, and the [[International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies]], [[U.S. State Department]], and South Korean government all indicated willingness to help.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> The U.S. government worked with the United Nations to make exceptions to sanctions, though they were also criticized for slowing down the process for providing aid.<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\"/> [[Doctors Without Borders]] said in late March that supplies of diagnostic equipment and [[personal protective equipment]] were stranded on the Chinese border.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/two-foreigners-left-under-quarantine-in-north-korea-state-media/?t=1585324059464|title=Only two foreigners remain under quarantine in North Korea, state media says|first=Jeongmin|last=Kim|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn early February, the [[North Korean government]] took severe measures to block the spread of the coronavirus. ''[[Rodong Sinmun]]'', the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] newspaper, reported that the customs officials at [[Nampho]] port were performing disinfection activities, including placing imported goods in quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://kcnawatch.org/newstream/1583703072-617647256/\uac80\uc0ac\uac80\uc5ed\uc744-\uc0ac\uc18c\ud55c-\ube48\ud2c8\ub3c4-\uc5c6\uac8c/ |script-title=ko:\uac80\uc0ac\uac80\uc5ed\uc744 \uc0ac\uc18c\ud55c \ube48\ud2c8\ub3c4 \uc5c6\uac8c |language=ko |date=2020-03-09 |accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref> All international flights and railway services were suspended in early February, and connections by sea and road were largely closed over the following weeks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February, wearing face masks was obligatory and visiting public places such as restaurants was forbidden. Ski resorts and spas were closed and military parades, marathons, and other public events were cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchools were closed throughout the country; university students in Pyongyang from elsewhere in the country were confined to their dormitories.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joo |first1=Jeong Tae |title=Sources: N. Korea extends school closures until April 15 |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-north-korea-extends-school-closures-until-april-15/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Daily NK |date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"N Korea closes schools\">{{cite news |last1=Joo |first1=Jeong Tae |title=N. Korea closes schools throughout the country for one month |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-closes-schools-throughout-country-one-month/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Daily NK |date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korean citizens returning from other countries were subjected to a 40-day isolation period to which was added a 30-day \u201cmedical observation\u201d period. According to North Korean media, nearly 7,000 North Koreans were subjected to these rules on 1 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the North Korean government, 10,000 people had been quarantined by the end of March.<ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\"/> From 12 February, the 14-day quarantine on all foreigners (including their local staff) was extended to 30 days.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Diplomats and other foreigners were evacuated to [[Vladivostok]] in March.<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\"/><ref name=\"Russia Delivers\"/> By 27 March, according to North Korean media, there were only two foreigners in quarantine and 2280 North Koreans were under \"medical observation\" in areas such as [[South Phyongan]] province and [[North Phyongan]] province, [[Ryanggang]] province, and the city of [[Rason]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/two-foreigners-left-under-quarantine-in-north-korea-state-media/?t=1585324059464|title=Only two foreigners remain under quarantine in North Korea, state media says|first=Jeongmin|last=Kim|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe North Korean military fired five missiles on two occasions in early March 2020, which may be \"an effort to ensure the country remains on the agenda for other nations amid the virus outbreak\".<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> More missile tests followed in late March, along with an announcement that the [[Supreme People's Assembly]] would meet in early April. Foreign observers said the government was trying to show confidence in their handling of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Missile tests and meetings: North Korea signals confidence in face of coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-northkorea-analysi/missile-tests-and-meetings-north-korea-signals-confidence-in-face-of-coronavirus-idUSKBN21A0O7 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The South Korean military called the provocation \"extremely inappropriate\" in light of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea Fires Missile Into East Sea |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-28/north-korea-fires-missile-into-east-sea-s-korea-military-says |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2020, North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-un]] ordered the construction of new hospitals.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/kim-jong-un-north-korea-hospital-coronavirus |title = Kim Jong Un orders workers to build new hospitals as North Korea continues to claim no coronavirus cases |work=[[Fox News]] |date = 2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nKim Jong-un sent a letter to South Korean president [[Moon Jae-in]] as a show of support amidst the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|outbreak in South Korea]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Top U.S. Commander 'Fairly Certain' North Korea Has Virus Cases |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-14/top-u-s-commander-fairly-certain-north-korea-has-virus-cases |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=14 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Donald Trump]] wrote a letter to [[Kim Jong-un]] to express his willingness to work with him on dealing with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea says Trump wrote Kim, offered coronavirus cooperation |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-northkorea-idUSKBN2180YX |work=Reuters |date=2020-03-21}}</ref> North Korean state media has reported on the severity of the outbreak in other countries.<ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\"/>\n\nOn 31 March 2020, the ''[[Asia Times]]'' reported that North Korea's measures against the pandemic seemed largely successful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/03/north-koreas-silent-struggle-against-covid-19/|title=North Korea's silent struggle against Covid-19|first=Gabriela|last=Bernal|publisher=Asian Times|date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Edwin Salvador, WHO's representative in North Korea, reported that as of 2 April, 709 people had been tested, with no confirmed cases, and 509 people were in quarantine.<ref>{{cite new|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-northkorea/north-korea-testing-quarantining-for-covid-19-still-says-no-cases-who-representative-idUSKBN21P3C2|title=North Korea testing, quarantining for COVID-19, still says no cases: WHO representative|first=Stephanie|last=Nebehay|publisher=Reuters|date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, Kim Jong-un presided over a meeting of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Politburo]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]. The meeting adopted a joint resolution by the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]], [[State Affairs Commission of North Korea|State Affairs Commission]] and the [[Cabinet of North Korea|Cabinet]], \u201cOn more thoroughly taking national measures for protecting the life and safety of our people from the worldwide epidemic disease\u201d. The resolution called to take strict national countermeasures to thoroughly check the inroads of the virus due to the steady spread of the epidemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/04/kim-jong-un-guides-saturdays-politburo-meeting-ahead-of-spa-state-media/|title=North Korea's Politburo discusses \"danger\" from COVID-19, promotes officials|first=Gabriela|last=Bernal|publisher=Asian Times|date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nAlthough South Korean media shared news hinting at the spread of the COVID-19 epidemic to North Korea, the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] denied the veracity of such claims. On 18 February, ''Rodong Sinmun'' quoted a public health official reiterating the country had had \"no confirmed case of the new coronavirus so far\". The WHO prioritised aid for North Korea, including the shipment of protective equipment and supplies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/who-says-no-signs-of-coronavirus-cases-in-north-korea.html|title=World Health Organization says there are 'no indications' of coronavirus cases in North Korea|publisher=CNBC|date=19 February 2020|access-date=19 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219100113/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/who-says-no-signs-of-coronavirus-cases-in-north-korea.html|archive-date=19 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Military===\nIn early March, the North Korean government continued to deny that they had any cases of [[COVID-19]]. However, according to [[South Korea]]n media outlet ''[[Daily NK]]'', 180 soldiers had died. There was no estimate of those merely infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3074377/coronavirus-nearly-200-north-korea-soldiers-die-outbreak|title=Coronavirus: nearly 200 North Korea soldiers 'die from outbreak government refuses to acknowledge'|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February and March, U.S. officials observed a decrease in military activity in North Korea, believed to be a sign that there are COVID-19 cases in the country.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> General [[Robert B. Abrams]] observed that the North Korean military had \"been on lockdown for about 30 days\" and \"didn\u2019t fly an airplane for 24 days\".<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/>\n\n===Political===\nThe underground network that assists [[North Korean defectors|defectors in escaping North Korea]] has been almost unable to operate amidst strict controls implemented to stop the virus, with defection attempts being suspended.<ref name=\"Group of North Korean women and children\">{{cite news |title=Group of North Korean women and children escape coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.ft.com/content/253d5ff0-63e9-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=www.ft.com |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Defection rates had been declining already, probably due to increased security under the administrations of [[Kim Jong-un]] in North Korea and [[Xi Jinping]] in China.<ref name=\"Group of North Korean women and children\"/>\n\n===Economic===\nOn 26 March, the New York Times reported satellite imagery shared by the [[Royal United Services Institute]], which showed that the illicit trafficking of coal and other goods stopped, with the commercial vessels now idling in their home ports.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/video/coronavirus-north-korea.html</ref> This trafficking is prohibited under United Nations sanctions, and is believed to be mostly with China. The change happened after North Korea sought to seal itself off starting 22 January. These sales normally provide a revenue stream that has historically contributed to its nuclear and ballistic missile programs. It may also cause a possible drop in fuel and fertilizer imports, which would affect North Korea's agriculture sector, right at the beginning of the farming season. Analysts said it was reasonable to assume damage has been done to North Korean agriculture, industry and the overall economy.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Timeline==\n===January 2020===\nFrom 23 January, North Korea banned [[Tourism in North Korea|foreign tourists]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/north-korea-to-temporarily-ban-tourists-over-wuhan-virus-fears-says-tour-company|title=North Korea to temporarily ban tourists over Wuhan virus fears, says tour company|last=hermesauto|date=21 January 2020|website=The Straits Times|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January, suspected cases in [[Sinuiju]] were quarantined.{{update inline|date=February 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-quarantines-suspected-coronavirus-cases-sinuiju/|title=N. Korea quarantines suspected coronavirus cases in Sinuiju|website=Daily NK|date=28 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130223216/https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-quarantines-suspected-coronavirus-cases-sinuiju/|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January, North Korea's news agency [[KCNA]] declared a \"state emergency\" and reported the establishment of anti-epidemic headquarters around the country.<ref name=\"20200206cnn\">{{cite news |last1=Berlinger |first1=Joshua |last2=Seo |first2=Yoonjung |title=All of its neighbors have it, so why hasn't North Korea reported any coronavirus cases? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/06/asia/north-korea-wuhan-coronavirus-infection-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207093221/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/06/asia/north-korea-wuhan-coronavirus-infection-intl-hnk/index.html |archive-date=7 February 2020 |accessdate=7 February 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 2 February, KCNA reported that all the people who had entered the country after 13 January were placed under \"medical supervision\".<ref name=\"20200206cnn\"/>\n\nOn 7 February, South Korean media outlet ''[[Daily NK]]'' claimed that five North Koreans in [[Sinuiju]] on the Chinese border died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-five-north-koreans-died-coronavirus-infections/|title=Sources: Five N. Koreans died from coronavirus infections|author=Jang Seul Gi|website=Daily NK|date=7 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208082046/https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-five-north-koreans-died-coronavirus-infections/|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Within the same day, ''[[The Korea Times]]'' reported that a North Korean female living in the capital [[Pyongyang]] was infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news/section/3/141479/Coronavirus-spreads-to-North-Korea,-woman-infected|title=Coronavirus spreads to North Korea, woman infected|website=The Standard|location=Hong Kong|date=7 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208082206/https://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news/section/3/141479/Coronavirus-spreads-to-North-Korea,-woman-infected|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite no confirmation by North Korean authorities on the claims, the country has implemented stricter measures to combat the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pyongyangtimes.com.kp/?bbs=33091|title=Nation steps up fight against novel CoV|website=The Pyongyang Times|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rodong.rep.kp/en/index.php?strPageID=SF01_02_01&newsID=2020-02-08-0001|title=Work to Curb the Inflow of Infectious Disease Pushed ahead with|website=Rodong Sinmun|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchools were closed starting on 20 February.<ref name=\"N Korea closes schools\"/>\n\nOn 29 February, [[Kim Jong-un]] called for stronger measures to be taken to prevent COVID-19 from spreading to North Korea.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/kim-warns-consequences-virus-spreads-korea-200229061648473.html | title=Kim warns of 'serious consequences' if virus spreads to N Korea |work=al Jazeera}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\nOn 14 March 2020, North Korea state media reported there were no confirmed cases in its territory.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kim |first1=Stella |last2=Hagen |first2=Isobel |date=March 14, 2020 |title=North Korea claims it has no coronavirus cases |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/live-blog/coronavirus-updates-live-house-approves-coronavirus-aid-bill-n1158821/ncrd1158881#liveBlogHeader |work=NBC News |access-date=March 14, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2020, [[Kim Jong-un]] ordered the construction of new hospitals in North Korea. North Korean state media also reported that groundbreaking on a new hospital was underway the day prior on Tuesday 17 March. Kim Jong-un reportedly told a newspaper linked to the ruling [[Workers' Party of Korea]] that the construction of new hospitals were being done for general improvement of the nation's healthcare system without mentioning COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/kim-jong-un-north-korea-hospital-coronavirus |title = Kim Jong Un orders workers to build new hospitals as North Korea continues to claim no coronavirus cases |work=[[Fox News]] |date = 2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, North Korean media stated that more than 2,590 people had been released from quarantine in [[North Pyongan]] and [[South Pyongan]] provinces. All but three quarantined foreigners had been released.<ref name=\"aa.com.tr 21\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19: North Korea releases quarantined people |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19-north-korea-releases-quarantined-people/1773332 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 1 April 2020, North Korean public health official Pak Myong-su repeated the claim that North Korea has no cases of the virus.<ref name=\"Mainichi 2 April\">{{cite news |title=N. Korea has no infected people with new coronavirus: expert |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200402/p2g/00m/0in/025000c |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Mainichi Daily News |date=2 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Health in North Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Medicine|North Korea|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|North Korea]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|North Korea]]\n[[Category:2020 in North Korea|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in North Korea]]\n", "name_user": "Quidster4040", "label": "safe", "comment": "adding most recent update on COVID19 in North Korea", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_North_Korea"}
{"title_page": "Khans of Bollywood", "text_new": "{{short description|Bollywood actors with surname Khan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| total_width = 335\n| footer = [[Aamir Khan]] (left), [[Shah Rukh Khan]] (middle), and [[Salman Khan]] (right).\n| footer_align = center\n| image1 = Aamir Khan 2013.jpg\n| image2 = Shahrukh Khan CE.jpg\n| image3 = Salman khan at Chillar Party Meet.jpg\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| caption2 = \n}}\n\nThe term '''Khans of Bollywood''' refers to several male actors of [[Bollywood]], the [[Mumbai]]-based [[Hindi]] language [[Cinema of India|Indian film]] industry, whose surnames are [[Khan (surname)|Khan]]. Most commonly, this involves the '''Three Khans''': [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]], [[Salman Khan]] and [[Aamir Khan]]. The three are unrelated, but happen to share the same surname,<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2016/03/20/are-bollywoods-three-khans-the-last-of-the-movie-kings/|title=Are Bollywood's Three Khans The Last Of The Movie Kings?|last=Cain|first=Rob|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> were all born in 1965,<ref>{{cite news|title=Fab At 50: A Tale Of Three Khans|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/anand-vaishnav-/fab-at-fifty-yes-they-kha_b_7482408.html|work=[[Huffington Post]]|date=8 June 2015|language=en-IN}}</ref> and, due to their longevity and high popularity, are considered some of the most successful [[movie star]]s in the history of both Indian and world cinema. \n\nThe dominance of the three Khans at the Indian box office has been compared to that of the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] in [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]].<ref name=\"forbes\"/> Shah Rukh Khan frequently appears among the top three wealthiest actors in the world, while [[Aamir Khan]] has been the only Eastern actor to be ranked first in the world's [[List of highest paid film actors|highest-earning actors in films]], and Salman Khan has been the highest paid celebrity in [[South Asia]] several times. They have also earned critical acclaim, between them winning 6 [[National Film Awards]] and 26 [[Filmfare Awards]], as well as an [[Academy Award]] nomination for Aamir. They are also some of the most famous [[Muslims in India]],<ref name=\"desiblitz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.desiblitz.com/content/the-three-khans-of-bollywood|title=The Three Khans of Bollywood - DESIblitz|date=18 September 2012|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> some of the most famous Indians known overseas, and some of the world's biggest [[movie star]]s.<ref name=\"movie-star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/10/05/heres-why-aamir-khan-is-arguably-the-worlds-biggest-movie-star-part-2/|title=Why Aamir Khan Is Arguably The World's Biggest Movie Star, Part 2|last1=Cain|first1=Rob|date=5 October 2017|website=[[Forbes]]}}</ref> They have been reported by various sources to command high salary packages up to {{INRConvert|50|c|0}} per movie.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://sportrichlist.com/top10/highest-paid-bollywood-actors/ |title=Top 10 Highest Paid Bollywood Actors 2015 |publisher=Sportrichlist.com |date=21 November 2013 |accessdate=19 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202052604/http://sportrichlist.com/top10/highest-paid-bollywood-actors/ |archive-date=2 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sengar |first=Resham |url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/celebrity/take-home-salary-of-top-7-bollywood-stars_146256.html |title=Take home salary of top 7 Bollywood stars &#124; Zee News |publisher=Zeenews.india.com |date=12 November 2013 |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://listtoptens.com/top-10-highest-paid-bollywood-actors/ |title=Top 10 Highest Paid Bollywood Actors |publisher=Listtoptens.com |date= |accessdate=19 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014020246/http://listtoptens.com/top-10-highest-paid-bollywood-actors/ |archive-date=14 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The three Khans have had successful careers since the late 1980s,<ref name=\"desiblitz\" /> and have dominated the Indian box office since the 1990s,<ref>[http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/after-aamir-srk-salman-why-bollywoods-next-male-superstar-may-need-a-decade-to-rise-3049864.html After Aamir, SRK, Salman, why Bollywood's next male superstar may need a decade to rise], [[Firstpost]], 16 October 2016</ref> across three decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/aamir-khan-is-the-king-of-the-king-khans-moved-ahead-of-shah-rukh-salman-1723117|title=Why Aamir Khan Is The King Of Khans: Foreign Media|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> \n\nCombined, they have starred in eight of the top ten [[List of highest-grossing Bollywood films|highest-grossing Bollywood films ever]], half of the ten [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing Indian films]],<ref name=\"worldwide\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/worldwide-total-gross.php|title=Top Worldwide Grossers All Time|website=www.boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> and nearly every [[List of highest-grossing Indian films#Highest-grossing films by year|annual top-grossing Bollywood film]] between 1989 and 2017 (except for 1992{{ndash}}1993 and 2006).<ref name=\"worldwide\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=125&catName=MTk4MC0xOTg5|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014090332/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=125&catName=MTk4MC0xOTg5|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 October 2013|title=Boxofficeindia.com|date=14 October 2013|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"web.archive.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=126&catName=MTk5MC0xOTk5|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014072959/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=126&catName=MTk5MC0xOTk5|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 October 2013|title=Boxofficeindia.com|date=14 October 2013|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> They officially created the [[100 Crore Club]]:<ref name=\"rediff\"/> the first films to [[Gross revenue|gross]] {{INR}}100 crore [[List of highest-grossing films in India|domestically]] were Salman's ''[[Hum Aapke Hain Koun]]'' (1994) and Shah Rukh's ''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]'' (1995),<ref name=\"boxofficeindia\">{{cite web |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3826&nCat= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425231804/http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3826&nCat= |archivedate=25 April 2012 |title=The 100 Crore Worldwide Grossers: 34 Films Since 1994 |publisher=Box Office India |date= |accessdate=19 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"web.archive.org\"/> and Aamir Khan's ''[[Ghajini (2008 film)|Ghajini]]'' (2008) was the first to [[Net income|net]] {{INR}}100 crore.<ref name=\"rediff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/aamir-khans-10-biggest-hits/20141222.htm|title=Aamir Khan's 10 BIGGEST Hits|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> Aamir's ''[[Dangal (film)|Dangal]]'' (2016) created the [[Bollywood 1000 Crore Club]], owing to its overseas success in [[Greater China|Chinese markets]], and eventually created the [[1000 Crore Club|2000 Crore Club]], becoming the highest-grossing Indian film ever (worldwide and [[List of highest-grossing Indian films in overseas markets|overseas]]), and one of the [[List of highest-grossing films in China|highest-grossing films in China]] and India, with his earnings from the film estimated to be {{INRConvert|300|c}},<ref>[http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/dangals-china-success-may-have-brought-aamir-khan-a-neat-rs-100-crore-paycheque-3526673.html Dangal's China success may have brought [[Aamir Khan]] a neat Rs 100 crore paycheque], [[Firstpost]], 7 June 2017</ref> the [[List of highest paid film actors|highest payday]] for a non-Hollywood actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/06/06/aamir-khans-china-paycheck-for-dangal-could-exceed-rs-100-crore-15-mm/|title=Aamir Khan's China Paycheck For 'Dangal' Could Exceed Rs. 100 Crore / $15 MM|first=Rob|last=Cain|publisher=}}</ref> In 2014, Shah Rukh was the richest non-Hollywood actor and the second richest actor in the world, with an estimated [[net worth]] of US$600 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Shah-Rukh-Khan-second-richest-actor-10-richest-actors/articleshow/35431720.cms|title=Shah Rukh Khan second richest actor in the world - Times of India \u25ba|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> On the 2016 ''[[Forbes]]'' list of the 10 highest-paid actors in the world, Salman ranked sixth, with total earnings of US$33.5 million for the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/emjl45mmei/7-salman-khan/ |title=Salman Khan - In Photos: The World's Highest-Paid Actors 2015 |work=Forbes |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> On 2017's <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/599b0ba431358e60d7768f66/the-worlds-highest-paid-a/|title=The World's Highest-Paid Actors 2017|website=Forbes}}</ref> and 2018's <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/5b7b16ada7ea43757f2cb680/the-worlds-highest-paid-a/|title=9. Salman Khan|website=Forbes}}</ref> ''[[Forbes]]'' list of the 10 highest-paid actors in the world, Salman Khan ranked 9th both years, earning $37 million and $38.5 million in 2017 and 2018, respectively.\n\nIn addition to the three Khans, there have been other Khans in Bollywood. The most famous Khan prior to them was [[Dilip Kumar]], whose real name is Muhammad Yusuf Khan, for which he has been referred to as the \"First Khan\" of Bollywood. Kumar was one of the biggest Indian movie stars of the 1950s and 1960s.<ref name=\"indianexpress\"/> His 1960 film ''[[Mughal-e-Azam]]'' was the first Indian film with an adjusted gross over [[Bollywood 1000 Crore Club|{{INR}}1000 crore]],<ref name=\"gold\"/><ref name=\"gold3\"/> making it the highest-grossing Indian film for over five decades.<ref name=\"gold3\"/> The term \"fourth Khan\" is sometimes used to refer to either [[Saif Ali Khan]] or [[Irrfan Khan]]\n\n==Three Khans==\n\n===Shah Rukh Khan===\n[[File:Shahrukh interacts with media after KKR's maiden IPL title.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Shah Rukh Khan]] in 2012. He was the most successful Indian actor for most of the 1990s and 2000s.<ref name=\"movie-star\"/>]]\n\n{{Main|Shah Rukh Khan}}\nShah Rukh Khan (born Shahrukh Khan, 2 November 1965), popularly called as SRK, is sometimes referred to in the media as the \"Baadshah of Bollywood\", \"King of Bollywood\", \"King Khan\", \"King of Romance\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2012/12/68379/bollywood-demigod-khan-casts-spell-on-moroccans/|title=Bollywood 'Demigod' Khan Casts Spell on Moroccans|date=3 December 2012|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-shah-rukh-khan-as-popular-as-pope-german-media-1150157|title=Shah Rukh Khan as popular as Pope: German media|date=10 February 2008|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ranisingh/2015/12/26/shah-rukh-khan-the-biggest-movie-star-in-the-world/#2e7fa2f6567b|title=Shah Rukh Khan - The Biggest Movie Star In The World.|first=Rani|last=Singh|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2016/04/16/dont-worry-heres-proof-that-srk-is-still-absolutely-the-worlds-biggest-movie-star/#787f99fb34e3|title=Don't Worry, Here's Proof That Shah Rukh Khan Is Still The World's Biggest Movie Star|first=Rob|last=Cain|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/04/30/worlds-biggest-movie-star-gives-a-ted-talk-in-vancouver-but-no-one-knows-who-he-is-6606988/|title=World's biggest movie star gives TED talk but no one knows who he is|date=30 April 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclearlife.com/television/shah-rukh-khan-worlds-biggest-movie-star/|title=Meet Shah Rukh Khan, the World's Biggest Movie Star You've Never Heard Of|date=4 January 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/huntsville/index.ssf/2018/05/indian_movie_megastar_shah_ruk.html|title=Indian movie megastar Shah Rukh Khan filming in Alabama|publisher=|date=11 May 2018}}</ref> He is a self-made Superstar who entered Bollywood without any background and became successful. He is the most successful actor in Bollywood. He has appeared in several successful romantic love stories including ''[[Darr]]'', ''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]'', ''[[Dil to Pagal Hai]]'', ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'' and ''[[Veer Zaara]]'' among others. He is also a recipient of 8 Filmfare for 'Best Actor in a leading role awards' (tied with legendary [[Dilip Kumar]]) and won a total of 14 Filmfare awards. He has appeared in more than 80&nbsp;[[Bollywood]] films. Described by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' as perhaps \"The World's Biggest Movie Star\", Khan has a significant following in Asia and the [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Indian diaspora]] worldwide. He is one of the richest actors in the world, with an estimated net worth of {{US$|link=yes}}790 million, and his work in Bollywood has earned him [[List of awards and nominations received by Shah Rukh Khan|numerous accolades]], including 14&nbsp;[[Filmfare Awards]].\n\nKhan started his career with appearances in several television-series in the late 1980s. He made his Bollywood debut in 1992 with ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]''. Early in his career, Khan was recognised for portraying villainous roles in the films ''[[Darr]]'' (1993), ''[[Baazigar]]'' (1993) and ''[[Anjaam]]'' (1994). He then rose to prominence after starring in a series of romantic films, including ''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]'' (1995), ''[[Dil To Pagal Hai]]'' (1997), ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'' (1998) and ''[[Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham...]]'' (2001). He earned critical acclaim for his portrayals of an alcoholic in ''[[Devdas (2002 Hindi film)|Devdas]]'' (2002), a NASA scientist in ''[[Swades]]'' (2004), a hockey coach in ''[[Chak De! India]]'' (2007), a man with [[Asperger syndrome]] in ''[[My Name Is Khan]]'' (2010), a forty-year old bachelor in ''[[Chennai Express]]'' (2013), a dancer in the musical heist comedy movie ''[[Happy New Year (2014 film)|Happy New Year]]'' (2014), a deranged fan in the psychological thriller movie ''[[Fan (film)|Fan]]'' (2016) and a gangster in the crime thriller movie ''[[Raees (film)|Raees]]'' (2017).\n\nMany of his films display themes of Indian national identity and connections with diaspora communities, or gender, racial, social and religious differences and grievances. For his contributions to film, the Government of India honored him with the [[Padma Shri]], and the Government of France awarded him both the [[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]] and the [[Legion of Honour|L\u00e9gion d'honneur]].\n\nAlong with the awards, he has been awarded four honorary doctorates.\n\n=== Salman Khan ===\n[[File:Salmanrampwalk.png|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Salmanrampwalk.png|right|thumb|233x233px|[[Salman Khan]] ramp walk in 2011.<ref name=\"hindustantimes2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/SALMAN-KHAN-Hail-Bollywood-s-new-king/Article1-920785.aspx|title=SALMAN KHAN: Hail Bollywood's new king|date=28 August 2012|work=Hindustan Times|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826151520/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/SALMAN-KHAN-Hail-Bollywood-s-new-king/Article1-920785.aspx|archivedate=26 August 2013|accessdate=17 January 2013|df=}}</ref> He has been the most domestically successful Indian actor in the 2010s.<ref name=\"Groves2\">{{cite news|last1=Groves|first1=Don|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dongroves/2017/06/27/tubelight-may-be-a-setback-but-salman-khans-star-power-is-undimmed/|title='Tubelight' May Be A Setback But Salman Khan's Star Power Is Undimmed|date=27 June 2017|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>]]\n{{Main|Salman Khan}}\nAbdul Rashid Salim Salman Khan (born 27 December 1965)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_bollywood-wishes-salman-khan-on-his-46th-birthday_1630590|title=Bollywood wishes Salman Khan on his 46th birthday|date=27 December 2011|newspaper=[[DNA India]]|accessdate=27 April 2012|agency=Press Trust of India|place=[[New Delhi]]}}</ref> better known as Salman Khan (pronunciation : {{IPA-hns|s\u0259l\u02c8ma\u02d0n \u02c8xa\u02d0n|}};) is one of the biggest and the most economically viable actors of India. In recent years, every movie he has acted in as the main lead has commended over 100 Crores. Referred to in the media as \"The Tiger of Bollywood\", \"Blockbuster Khan\", \"Box-office King\", he is popularly called \"Bhaijaan\" and \"Sallu\" by his fans. Described by the [[CNN]] as one of the world's biggest stars,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/05/06/entertainment/salman-khan-feat/|title=Who is Salman Khan? One of the world's biggest stars - CNN.com|author=Lisa Respers France, CNN|date=6 May 2015|work=CNN|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref> he has a significant following in Asia and the Indian diaspora worldwide. He is cited in the media as one of the most popular, influential<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/list/ls051665794/|title=IMDb: The 25 Greatest Indian Actors Of All Time - a list by swarupbasak|work=IMDb|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref>  and commercially successful actors of [[Bollywood|Hindi cinema]].<ref name=\"hindustantimes2\" />\n\nKhan began his acting career with a supporting role in ''[[Biwi Ho To Aisi]]'' (1988) and achieved a breakthrough with a leading role in his next release {{mdash}} [[Sooraj Barjatya]]'s romance ''[[Maine Pyar Kiya]]'' (1989). Khan went on to establish himself in Bollywood in the 1990s with roles in several top-grossing productions, including the romantic drama ''[[Hum Aapke Hain Koun..!]]'' (1994), the action thriller ''[[Karan Arjun]]'' (1995), the comedy ''[[Biwi No.1]]'' (1999), and the family drama ''[[Hum Saath-Saath Hain]]'' (1999). For his role in [[Karan Johar]]'s romantic drama ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'' (1998), Khan was awarded the [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor]]. After a brief period of decline in the 2000s, He also starred in the critically acclaimed movie ''[[Tere Naam]]'' (2003). Khan achieved greater stardom in the 2010s by playing the lead role in several successful action films, including ''[[Dabangg]]'' (2010), ''[[Bodyguard (2011 Hindi film)|Bodyguard]]'' (2011), ''[[Ek Tha Tiger]]'' (2012), ''[[Kick (2014 film)|Kick]]'' (2014), ''[[Bajrangi Bhaijaan]]'' (2015) and ''[[Tiger Zinda Hai]]'' (2017) nine of the films he has acted in, have accumulated gross earnings of over {{INRConvert|1|b}},<ref name=\"GROSS2\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=4409&nCat=|title=Top All Time Worldwide Grossers Updated 11/5/2012|publisher=[[Box Office India]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007021530/http://boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=4409&nCat=|archivedate=7 October 2013|accessdate=11 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"world2\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3997&nCat=|title=Top Worldwide Grossers ALL TIME: 37 Films Hit 100 Crore|publisher=[[Box Office India]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205213224/http://boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3997&nCat=|archivedate=5 February 2012|accessdate=3 February 2012|df=}}</ref> and he has starred in the highest-grossing Bollywood films of nine separate years which is a [[Bollywood]] record.<ref>[http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=2043&nCat=box_office_news DABANGG Is 17th ALL TIME BLOCKBUSTER].  [[Box Office India]]. Retrieved 25 May 2011. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924023928/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=2043&nCat=box_office_news|date=24 September 2010}}</ref> For his contributions to film, the Government of India honored him with the 2008 - [[Rajiv Gandhi]] Award for Outstanding Achievement in Entertainment.\n\nSalman Khan was ranked 7th in [[Forbes]]'s first global list of the highest-paid actor in the world with  US$33.5 million, earning more than Hollywood actors like [[Dwayne The Rock Johnson]], [[Johnny Depp]], [[Brad Pitt]] and [[Leonardo DiCaprio]]\n\n=== [[Leonardo DiCaprio|Aamir Khan]] ===\n[[File:AamirKhan.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:AamirKhan.jpg|thumb|[[Aamir Khan]] at an event in 2008. He has been the most internationally successful Indian actor since the late 2000s.<ref name=\"movie-star2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/10/05/heres-why-aamir-khan-is-arguably-the-worlds-biggest-movie-star-part-2/|title=Why Aamir Khan Is Arguably The World's Biggest Movie Star, Part 2|last1=Cain|first1=Rob|date=5 October 2017|website=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>]]\n{{Main|Aamir Khan}}\n[[Aamir Khan]] (born Mohammed Aamir Hussain Khan on 14 March 1965) is one of the biggest and most commercially successful superstars of India.<ref name=\"koimoi.com2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-news/aamir-khan-is-the-worlds-biggest-superstar-says-a-trade-analyst/|title=Aamir Khan Is The Worlds Biggest Superstar Says A Trade Analyst!|date=29 March 2018}}</ref> [[Leonardo DiCaprio|He has a reputation of doing fewer movies but with great attention to detail, including content and quality. Through his successful career in]] [[Bollywood|Hindi films]], Khan has established himself as one of the most popular and influential actors of [[Cinema of India|Indian cinema]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2006/aug/17sd11.htm|title=Readers' Picks: Top Bollywood Actors|date=17 August 2006|publisher=Rediff|accessdate=26 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2006/aug/08sld11.htm|title=Powerlist: Top Bollywood Actors|date=8 August 2006|publisher=Rediff|accessdate=26 January 2010}}</ref> [[Leonardo DiCaprio|In addition to being highly popular in India, he is also highly popular overseas, particularly in]] [[China]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/dangal-wins-china-why-aamir-is-truly-the-alpha-khan-of-bollywood-1717537|title=Dangal Wins China: Why Aamir Is Truly The Alpha Khan Of Bollywood|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/06/11/how-to-become-a-foreign-movie-star-in-china-aamir-khans-5-point-formula-for-success/|title=How To Become A Foreign Movie Star In China: Aamir Khan's 5-Point Formula For Success|last=Cain|first=Rob|publisher=}}</ref> [[Leonardo DiCaprio|the second largest movie market.]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Jamkhandikar|first=Shilpa|url=https://reuters.com/article/india-bollywood-aamir-khan-dangal-interv-idUKKBN18R0RQ|title=Q&A: Aamir Khan on what it takes to crack China's box office|date=31 May 2017|newspaper=Reuters|publisher=}}</ref> [[Leonardo DiCaprio|He is \"arguably the world's biggest]] [[movie star]]\" according to Rob Cain,<ref name=\"movie-star2\" /> [[Leonardo DiCaprio|due to his immense popularity in the world's two]] [[List of countries and dependencies by population|most populous nations]], India and China.<ref name=\"movie-star2\" />\n\n[[Leonardo DiCaprio|He is the recipient of]] [[List of awards and nominations received by Aamir Khan|numerous awards]], including four [[National Film Awards]] and seven [[Filmfare Awards]], as well as an [[Academy Award]] nomination. He was honoured by the [[Government of India]] with the [[Padma Shri]] in 2003 and the [[Padma Bhushan]] in 2010.<ref name=\"Padma Awards2\">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf|title=Padma Awards|date=2015|publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf|archivedate=15 November 2014|accessdate=21 July 2015|df=}}</ref>\n\n[[Leonardo DiCaprio|Khan first appeared on screen as a child actor in his uncle]] [[Nasir Hussain]]'s film ''[[Yaadon Ki Baaraat]]'' (1973), the first Bollywood [[masala film]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/10/03/aamir-khans-secret-superstar-could-be-indias-next-\u20b91000-crore160m-box-office-hit/|title=Aamir Khan's 'Secret Superstar' Could Be India's Next \u20b91,000 Crore/$152M Box Office Hit|last1=Cain|first1=Rob|date=3 October 2017|website=[[Forbes]]}}</ref> [[Leonardo DiCaprio|His first feature film role came with the]] [[experimental film]] ''[[Holi (1984 film)|Holi]]'' (1984), and he began a full-time acting career with a leading role in the highly successful tragic romance ''[[Qayamat Se Qayamat Tak]]'' (1988). ''Qayamat Se Qayamat Tak'' was a milestone in the history of [[Hindi cinema]], setting the template for Bollywood musical romance films that defined Hindi cinema in the 1990s.<ref name=\"Ray2\">{{cite news|last=Ray|first=Kunal|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/Romancing-the-1980s/article16898867.ece|title=Romancing the 1980s|date=18 December 2016|work=[[The Hindu]]|language=en-IN}}</ref><ref name=\"Chintamani2\">{{cite book|last=Chintamani|first=Gautam|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Qayamat_Se_Qayamat_Tak_The_Film_That_Rev.html?id=BZYOvgAACAAJ|title=Qayamat Se Qayamat Tak: The Film That Revived Hindi Cinema|date=2016|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|isbn=9789352640980}}</ref> [[Leonardo DiCaprio|His performance in the film and in the thriller]] ''[[Raakh]]'' (1989) earned him a [[National Film Award \u2013 Special Jury Award (Feature Film)|Special Jury Award]] at the National Film Award ceremony. He established himself as a leading actor of Hindi cinema in the 1990s by appearing in several commercially successful films, including the romantic drama ''[[Dil (1990 film)|Dil]]'' (1990), the romance ''[[Raja Hindustani]]'' (1996), for which he won his first [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor]], and the drama ''[[Sarfarosh]]'' (1999).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2000/nov/30aamir.htm|title=I become the audience|author=Press Trust India|date=30 November 2000|publisher=[[Rediff]]|accessdate=26 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibosnetwork.com/asp/clsActorDisplay.asp?actor=Aamir+Khan&layout=filmography|title=The Aamir Khan Station|publisher=IBOS Network|accessdate=16 January 2009}}</ref> [[Leonardo DiCaprio|He was also noted for playing against type in the critically acclaimed]] [[Cinema of Canada|Canadian]]-Indian film ''[[Earth (1998 film)|Earth]]'' (1998).\n\n[[Leonardo DiCaprio|In 2001, Khan started a]] [[Aamir Khan Productions|production company]], whose first release, ''[[Lagaan]]'', was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]] and earned him a [[National Film Award for Best Popular Film Providing Wholesome Entertainment|National Film Award for Best Popular Film]] and two more Filmfare Awards (Best Actor and [[Filmfare Award for Best Film|Best Film]]). After a four-year absence from the screen, Khan continued to portray leading roles, most notably in the 2006 box-office hits ''[[Fanaa (film)|Fanaa]]'' and ''[[Rang De Basanti]]''. The following year, he made his directorial debut with ''[[Taare Zameen Par]]'', a major success that garnered him the Filmfare Awards for Best Film and [[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]]. Khan's greatest commercial successes came with the thriller ''[[Ghajini (2008 film)|Ghajini]]'' (2008), the comedy-drama ''[[3 Idiots]]'' (2009), the adventure film ''[[Dhoom 3]]'' (2013), the satire ''[[PK (film)|PK]]'' (2014) and wrestling-drama ''[[Dangal (film)|Dangal]]'' (2016) all of which held records for being the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing Indian film of all time]].<ref name=\"pk2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-pk-highest-grosser-ever-aamir-khan-to-enter-rs-300-crore-club-2049501|title='PK' highest grosser ever: Aamir Khan to enter Rs 300 crore club|date=4 January 2015|work=Daily News and Analysis|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref> [[Leonardo DiCaprio|After the success of Dangal the Question of Aamir Khan Being the Worlds Biggest Superstar]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/121018/is-aamir-khan-worlds-biggest-superstar-heres-what-you-need-to-kno.html|title=Is Aamir Khan World's biggest superstar? Here's what you need to know!|date=12 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movietalkies.com/news/whoa-aamir-khan-worlds-biggest-superstar/|title=Whoa! Aamir Khan Is 'World's Biggest Superstar'!|date=13 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"koimoi.com2\" /> [[Leonardo DiCaprio|has been posed]]\n\n==Other Khans==\n{{See also|Khan (surname)|Salim Khan family|List of Hindi film clans}}\n\n===Dilip Kumar (Muhammad Yusuf Khan) ===\n[[File:DilipKumar.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Dilip Kumar]] (Muhammad Yusuf Khan) in 2010. He was one of the biggest Indian movie stars of the 1950s and 1960s.<ref name=\"indianexpress\"/>]]\n{{Main|Dilip Kumar}}\n\n[[Dilip Kumar]], whose real name is Muhammad Yusuf Khan,<ref>Tanuja Chandra (3 March 2004) [http://sify.com/entertainment/movies/bollywood/celebcolumns/fullstory.php?id=13418077 Dilip Kumar: Silent Revolutionary] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040428030606/http://sify.com/entertainment/movies/bollywood/celebcolumns/fullstory.php?id=13418077 |date=28 April 2004 }} Sify Movies. Retrieved on 30 March 2009.</ref> has been retrospectively referred to as the \"First Khan\" of Bollywood.<ref name=\"indianexpress\">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/dilip-kumar-happy-birthday-turns-94-a-look-at-his-journey-india-first-method-actor-4420625/|title=Happy Birthday Dilip Kumar: As Dilip Kumar turns 94, a look at his titanic reputation as India's finest method actor|date=11 December 2016|publisher=}}</ref> He debuted in the 1940s, and became one of the biggest Indian [[movie star]]s of the 1950s and 1960s.<ref name=\"indianexpress\"/> He is credited with bringing realism to film acting in the [[Indian subcontinent]], and is considered one of the greatest and most influential actors of all time. He has been described as \"the ultimate [[method actor]]\" (natural actor) by [[Satyajit Ray]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Unmatched innings|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/magazine/article597902.ece|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208164035/http://www.thehindu.com/arts/magazine/article597902.ece|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 February 2012|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=24 January 2012|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref> Kumar was a pioneer of method acting, predating [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] method actors such as [[Marlon Brando]]. Kumar inspired future generations of Indian actors, from [[Amitabh Bachchan]] and [[Naseeruddin Shah]] to [[Shah Rukh Khan]] to [[Nawazuddin Siddiqui]].<ref>[https://www.thequint.com/entertainment/2015/12/11/before-brando-there-was-dilip-kumar Before Brando, There Was Dilip Kumar], The Quint, 11 December 2015</ref> In the 1950s, Dilip Kumar became the first actor to charge {{INRConvert|1|l|year=1953|lk=l}} per film.<ref>{{cite news|title=B-Town rewind: The tale of the first Bollywood crore|url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/b-town-rewind-the-tale-of-the-first-bollywood-crore/15162064|work=[[Mid Day]]|date=16 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nKumar is known for his roles in films such as the romantic ''[[Andaz (1949 film)|Andaz]]'' (1949), the swashbuckling ''[[Aan]]'' (1952), the dramatic ''[[Devdas (1955 film)|Devdas]]'' (1955), the comical ''[[Azaad (1955 film)|Azaad]]'' (1955) and ''[[Ram Aur Shyam]]'' (1967), the historical ''[[Mughal-e-Azam]]'' (1960), and the social ''[[Ganga Jamuna]]'' (1961). His biggest commercial success was portraying [[Prince Salim]] in [[K. Asif]]'s big-budget epic [[historical film]] ''Mughal-e-Azam'', which was the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing film]] in Indian film history for 15 years until it was surpassed by 1975's ''[[Sholay]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/Mughal-e-Azam-1960/article15939167.ece|title=Mughal-e-Azam (1960)|date=31 July 2009|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> If adjusted for inflation, ''Mughal-e-Azam'' was the highest-grossing Indian film for more than five decades, equivalent to over [[Bollywood 1000 Crore Club|{{INR}}1000 crore]] in 2011,<ref name=\"gold\">[http://www.boxofficeindia.co.in/worth-their-weight-in-gold/ Worth Their Weight In Gold] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915183938/http://boxofficeindia.co.in/worth-their-weight-in-gold |date=15 September 2017 }}, ''[[Box Office India]]'', 1 November 2011</ref><ref name=\"gold3\">[http://boxofficeindia.co.in/top-50-film-of-last-50-years/ Top 50 Film of Last 50 Years] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104181418/http://boxofficeindia.co.in/top-50-film-of-last-50-years/ |date=4 November 2011 }}, ''[[Box Office India]]'', 3 November 2011</ref> until it was surpassed by Aamir Khan's ''[[Dangal (film)|Dangal]]'' in 2017.\n\n===Saif Ali Khan===\n[[File:Saif Ali Khan snapped at Imperial Hotel, New Delhi 05.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Saif Ali Khan]] at [[New Delhi]], [[India]] in 2012]]\n{{Main|Saif Ali Khan}}\nSaif Ali Khan - sometimes referred to as the \"Fourth Khan\", also a [[film producer]], son of [[Mansoor Ali Khan Pataudi]], a former captain of the [[Indian national cricket team]], and actress [[Sharmila Tagore]].<ref name=sak>Deepa Gahlot (July 1998) [http://www.sabrang.com/cc/comold/august98/saif.htm \u2018Religion played a major role in my upbringing\u2019] [[Sabrang Communications]]. Retrieved on 3 April 2009.</ref><ref>Subhash K Jha (21 August 2008) [http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-08-21/news-interviews/27923991_1_saif-muslim-societies ''\u2018I went to a Muslim builder,' says Saif''] The Times of India. Retrieved on 30 March 2009.</ref> The 2004 romantic comedy ''[[Hum Tum]]'' proved to be Khan's first success in which he played the sole male lead, earning him the [[National Film Award for Best Actor]], and starring roles in the drama ''[[Parineeta (2005 film)|Parineeta]]'' and the romantic comedy ''[[Salaam Namaste]]'' (both 2005) established him as a leading actor in Bollywood.<ref>[http://daily.bhaskar.com/news/CEL-saif-ali-khan-doesnt-want-to-be-called-the-fourth-khan-3536103.html Saif Ali Khan doesn\u2019t want to be called the fourth Khan!], ''[[Daily Bhaskar]]'', 17 July 2012</ref> He went on to earn wide critical praise for his portrayal of an apprentice in the 2006 English film ''[[Being Cyrus]]'', a character based on [[William Shakespeare]]'s antagonist [[Iago]] in the 2006 crime film ''[[Omkara (2006 film)|Omkara]]'' and a terrorist in the 2009 thriller ''[[Kurbaan (2009 film)|Kurbaan]]''. Khan's highest commercial success came with the 2008 thriller ''[[Race (2008 film)|Race]]'' and its 2013 [[Race 2|sequel]], the 2009 romance ''[[Love Aaj Kal]]'', and the 2012 romantic comedy ''[[Cocktail (2012 film)|Cocktail]]''.\n\n===Irrfan Khan===\n[[File:Irrfan Khan May 2015.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Irrfan Khan|Irfan Khan]] in 2015]]\n{{Main|Irrfan Khan}}\nIrrfan Khan has garnered the [[National Film Award for Best Actor]] in the [[60th National Film Awards|60th National Film Awards 2012]], for his performance in ''[[Paan Singh Tomar (film)|Paan Singh Tomar]]''.<ref name=\"60thaward\">{{cite press_release |title=60th National Film Awards Announced |url=http://pib.nic.in/archieve/others/2013/mar/d2013031801.pdf |publisher=Press Information Bureau (PIB), India |accessdate=18 March 2013}}</ref> Khan has won the 2014 [[Asian Film Award for Best Actor]], the [[National Film Award for Best Actor]], three [[Filmfare Awards]], three [[International Indian Film Academy Awards]], an [[Independent Spirit Award]] nomination, and various international honours. He also hosted a television show and commercials. As of 2015, he had appeared in more than 50 Indian films in Bollywood, and a number of international films, such as ''[[Life of Pi (film)|Life of Pi]]'', ''[[New York, I Love You]]'', ''[[A Mighty Heart (film)|A Mighty Heart]]'', ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'', and ''[[Jurassic World]]'', with a featured role alongside [[Tom Hanks]] in the 2016 adaptation of [[Dan Brown]]'s novel ''[[Inferno (Brown novel)|Inferno]]''. In September 2015, he was appointed as the [[brand ambassador]] for \"''Resurgent Rajasthan''\", a campaign by the [[Government of Rajasthan|state government of Rajasthan]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/jaipur/Local-boy-Irrfan-in-Jaipur-as-a-face-of-Resurgent-Rajasthan/articleshow/48879463.cms|title=Local boy Irfan in Jaipur as a face of Resurgent Rajasthan|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=8 September 2015|accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIrrfan Khan is sometimes also considered the \"fourth Khan\", along with Saif Ali Khan.<ref>{{cite news|title=I have no equation or relationship with Irrfan: Nawazuddin Siddiqui|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/230317/i-have-no-equation-or-relationship-with-irrfant-nawazuddin-siddiqui.html|work=[[Deccan Chronicle]]|date=23 March 2017}}</ref> As of 2017, Irrfan Khan's films have grossed over {{US$|3.6 billion|link=yes}} at the worldwide box office, mostly from his work in international productions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Irrfan Khan Movie Box Office Results|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Actor&id=irrfankhan.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|year=2017|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref> His highest-grossing Hindi films are ''[[Hindi Medium]]'' (2017) and ''[[The Lunchbox]]'' (2013).\n\n===Zayed Khan===\n[[File:Zayed Khan 1.jpg|thumb|right|Zayed Khan at the premiere of [[Mod (film)|Mod]].]]\n{{Main|Zayed Khan}}\nZayed Khan made his screen debut in 2003 in the film ''[[Chura Liyaa Hai Tumne]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Meet the new Khan of bollywood |url=http://archive.mid-day.com/entertainment/2002/nov/37762.htm |publisher=[[MiD DAY]] |date=30 November 2002 |accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref> In 2004, he starred in ''[[Main Hoon Na]]'', which was one of the biggest hits in his career. It was the second highest-grossing film of the year behind ''[[Veer-Zaara]]''. Khan was subsequently nominated for the Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor in 2005. His other notable works include ''[[Shabd (film)|Shabd]]'' (2005), ''[[Dus]]'' (2005), ''[[Yuvvraaj]]'' (2008), ''[[Blue (2009 film)| Blue]]'' (2009) and ''[[Anjaana Anjaani]]'' (2010). In 2011, Khan co-produced the film, ''[[Love Breakups Zindagi]]''. In 2017, Khan made his television debut in the show ''[[Haasil (Indian TV series)|Haasil]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/zayed-khan-sizzles-as-ranvir-raichand-in-the-first-teaser-of-haasil-4808660/|title=Zayed Khan sizzles as Ranvir Raichand in the first teaser of Haasil|work=[[The Indian Express]]|publisher=[[Indian Express Group]]|date=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Actors===\n[[File:SalimKhan.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Salim Khan]], part of [[Salim-Javed]] screenwriting duo and father of Salman Khan, in 2011]]\n\n;Male actors\n*[[Amjad Khan (actor)|Amjad Khan]] \u2013 also director\n*[[Arbaaz Khan]] \u2013 Salman Khan's brother, also a director and producer\n*[[Ayub Khan (actor)|Ayub Khan]] \u2013 Nasir Khan's son and Dilip Kumar's nephew, also an [[Indian television]] actor\n*[[Faisal Khan]] \u2013 Aamir Khan's brother\n*[[Fardeen Khan]] \u2013 Feroz Khan's son\n*[[Feroz Khan (actor)|Feroz Khan]] \u2013 Fardeen Khan's father, also a [[film director]] and producer\n*[[Imran Khan (Bollywood actor)|Imran Khan]] \u2013 Aamir Khan's nephew\n*[[Jayant|Jayant (actor)]] \u2013 Amjad Khan's father \n*[[Kader Khan]] \u2013 Indian-Canadian film actor, comedian, script and dialogue writer, as well as director\n*[[Mazhar Khan (actor, born 1955)|Mazhar Khan]] \u2013 Zeenat Amaan's Husband\n*[[Mehboob Khan]] \u2013 best known as a director and producer, also writer\n*[[Nasir Khan (actor)|Nasir Khan]] \u2013 Dilip Kumar's brother\n*[[Nazir Ahmed Khan]] \u2013 director and producer in [[British India]] and then [[Pakistan]] after [[partition of India]], brother-in-law of filmmaker [[K. Asif]]\n*[[Riyaz Khan]] \u2013 predominantly South Indian actor\n*[[Salim Khan]] \u2013 Salman Khan's father, best known as a [[screenwriter]], as part of screenwriting duo [[Salim-Javed]] (along with [[Javed Akhtar]])\n*[[Sanjay Khan]] \u2013 Zayed Khan's father, also a director and producer\n*[[Shadaab Khan]] \u2013 Amjad Khan's son \n*[[Shahbaz Khan (actor)|Shahbaz Khan]] \u2013 also a television actor\n*[[Sohail Khan]] \u2013 Salman Khan's brother, also a director and producer\n*[[Tariq Khan (actor)|Tariq Khan]] \u2013 Aamir Khan's cousin, Nasir Hussain's nephew\n*[[Zain Khan Durrani]] \u2013 also a model\n*[[Zayed Khan]] \u2013 Sanjay Khan's son, also a producer\n*[[Zuber K. Khan|Zuber Khan]] \u2013 also a television actor\n\n;Female actresses  \n*[[Sharmila Tagore]] (Ayesha Sultana Khan) \u2013 actress, [[Model (person)|model]], [[Central Board of Film Certification]] chairperson, mother of Saif Ali Khan\n*[[Farah Khan]] \u2013 best known as a dance [[choreographer]], director and producer\n*[[Gauhar Khan]] \u2013 also a model\n*[[Jiah Khan]] \u2013 British-American actress who worked in Bollywood\n*[[Kareena Kapoor Khan]] \u2013 Saif Ali Khan's wife, Karishma Kapoor's sister, part of [[Kapoor family]], daughter of actor [[Randhir Kapoor]] and actress [[Babita]]\n*[[Krutika Desai Khan]] \u2013 actress working in film, television and theater\n*[[Soha Ali Khan]] \u2013 Saif Ali Khan's sister, daughter of actress Sharmila Tagore\n*[[Sana Khan]] \u2013 also a model and dancer\n*[[Sara Ali Khan]] \u2013 Saif Ali Khan's daughter\n*[[Zareen Khan]] \u2013 Bollywood actress who has also appeared in [[Tamil cinema|Tamil]] and [[Punjabi cinema|Punjabi films]]\n\n===Others===\n*[[Alvira Khan Agnihotri]] \u2013 film producer and [[fashion design]]er, Salman Khan's sister and Salim Khan's daughter\n*[[Gauri Khan]] \u2013 producer, [[interior design]]er, [[costume designer]], Shah Rukh Khan's wife\n*[[Kabir Khan (director)|Kabir Khan]] \u2013 director, screenwriter, cinematographer\n*[[Mansoor Khan]] \u2013 director, producer, screenwriter, Nasir Hussain's son, Aamir Khan's cousin\n*[[Nasir Hussain]] (Nasir Hussain Khan) \u2013 director, producer, screenwriter, Aamir Khan's uncle\n*[[Nikhat Khan]] \u2013 film producer, Aamir Khan's sister\n*[[Parvati Khan]] \u2013 [[Indo-Trinidadian]] singer and model who worked in Bollywood\n*[[Tahir Hussain]] (Tahir Hussain Khan) \u2013 director, producer, Aamir Khan's father\n* [[Faraaz Khan]] - television actor, son of Yusuf Khan.\n\n==See also==\n*[[100 Crore Club]]\n*[[1000 Crore Club]]\n*[[Khan (surname)]]\n*[[List of highest-grossing Indian films]]\n**[[List of highest-grossing films in India]]\n*[[List of highest-grossing Indian films in overseas markets]]\n**[[List of highest-grossing films in China]]\n*[[List of Hindi film clans]]\n**[[Kapoor family]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Shah Rukh Khan}}\n[[Category:Bollywood]]\n[[Category:Film and video terminology]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Indian Muslims]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bollywood actors with surname Khan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| total_width = 335\n| footer = [[Aamir Khan]] (left), [[Shah Rukh Khan]] (middle), and [[Salman Khan]] (right).\n| footer_align = center\n| image1 = Aamir Khan 2013.jpg\n| image2 = Shahrukh Khan CE.jpg\n| image3 = Salman khan at Chillar Party Meet.jpg\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| caption2 = \n}}\n\nThe term '''Khans of Bollywood''' refers to several male actors of [[Bollywood]], the [[Mumbai]]-based [[Hindi]] language [[Cinema of India|Indian film]] industry, whose surnames are [[Khan (surname)|Khan]]. Most commonly, this involves the '''Three Khans''': [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]], [[Salman Khan]] and [[Aamir Khan]]. The three are unrelated, but happen to share the same surname,<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2016/03/20/are-bollywoods-three-khans-the-last-of-the-movie-kings/|title=Are Bollywood's Three Khans The Last Of The Movie Kings?|last=Cain|first=Rob|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> were all born in 1965,<ref>{{cite news|title=Fab At 50: A Tale Of Three Khans|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/anand-vaishnav-/fab-at-fifty-yes-they-kha_b_7482408.html|work=[[Huffington Post]]|date=8 June 2015|language=en-IN}}</ref> and, due to their longevity and high popularity, are considered some of the most successful [[movie star]]s in the history of both Indian and world cinema. \n\nThe dominance of the three Khans at the Indian box office has been compared to that of the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] in [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]].<ref name=\"forbes\"/> Shah Rukh Khan frequently appears among the top three wealthiest actors in the world, while [[Aamir Khan]] has been the only Eastern actor to be ranked first in the world's [[List of highest paid film actors|highest-earning actors in films]], and Salman Khan has been the highest paid celebrity in [[South Asia]] several times. They have also earned critical acclaim, between them winning 6 [[National Film Awards]] and 26 [[Filmfare Awards]], as well as an [[Academy Award]] nomination for Aamir. They are also some of the most famous [[Muslims in India]],<ref name=\"desiblitz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.desiblitz.com/content/the-three-khans-of-bollywood|title=The Three Khans of Bollywood - DESIblitz|date=18 September 2012|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> some of the most famous Indians known overseas, and some of the world's biggest [[movie star]]s.<ref name=\"movie-star\" /> They have been reported by various sources to command high salary packages up to {{INRConvert|50|c|0}} per movie.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://sportrichlist.com/top10/highest-paid-bollywood-actors/ |title=Top 10 Highest Paid Bollywood Actors 2015 |publisher=Sportrichlist.com |date=21 November 2013 |accessdate=19 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202052604/http://sportrichlist.com/top10/highest-paid-bollywood-actors/ |archive-date=2 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sengar |first=Resham |url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/celebrity/take-home-salary-of-top-7-bollywood-stars_146256.html |title=Take home salary of top 7 Bollywood stars &#124; Zee News |publisher=Zeenews.india.com |date=12 November 2013 |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://listtoptens.com/top-10-highest-paid-bollywood-actors/ |title=Top 10 Highest Paid Bollywood Actors |publisher=Listtoptens.com |date= |accessdate=19 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014020246/http://listtoptens.com/top-10-highest-paid-bollywood-actors/ |archive-date=14 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The three Khans have had successful careers since the late 1980s,<ref name=\"desiblitz\" /> and have dominated the Indian box office since the 1990s,<ref>[http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/after-aamir-srk-salman-why-bollywoods-next-male-superstar-may-need-a-decade-to-rise-3049864.html After Aamir, SRK, Salman, why Bollywood's next male superstar may need a decade to rise], [[Firstpost]], 16 October 2016</ref> across three decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/aamir-khan-is-the-king-of-the-king-khans-moved-ahead-of-shah-rukh-salman-1723117|title=Why Aamir Khan Is The King Of Khans: Foreign Media|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> \n\nCombined, they have starred in eight of the top ten [[List of highest-grossing Bollywood films|highest-grossing Bollywood films ever]], half of the ten [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing Indian films]],<ref name=\"worldwide\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/worldwide-total-gross.php|title=Top Worldwide Grossers All Time|website=www.boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> and nearly every [[List of highest-grossing Indian films#Highest-grossing films by year|annual top-grossing Bollywood film]] between 1989 and 2017 (except for 1992{{ndash}}1993 and 2006).<ref name=\"worldwide\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=125&catName=MTk4MC0xOTg5|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014090332/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=125&catName=MTk4MC0xOTg5|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 October 2013|title=Boxofficeindia.com|date=14 October 2013|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"web.archive.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=126&catName=MTk5MC0xOTk5|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014072959/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=126&catName=MTk5MC0xOTk5|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 October 2013|title=Boxofficeindia.com|date=14 October 2013|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> They officially created the [[100 Crore Club]]:<ref name=\"rediff\"/> the first films to [[Gross revenue|gross]] {{INR}}100 crore [[List of highest-grossing films in India|domestically]] were Salman's ''[[Hum Aapke Hain Koun]]'' (1994) and Shah Rukh's ''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]'' (1995),<ref name=\"boxofficeindia\">{{cite web |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3826&nCat= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425231804/http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3826&nCat= |archivedate=25 April 2012 |title=The 100 Crore Worldwide Grossers: 34 Films Since 1994 |publisher=Box Office India |date= |accessdate=19 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"web.archive.org\"/> and Aamir Khan's ''[[Ghajini (2008 film)|Ghajini]]'' (2008) was the first to [[Net income|net]] {{INR}}100 crore.<ref name=\"rediff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/aamir-khans-10-biggest-hits/20141222.htm|title=Aamir Khan's 10 BIGGEST Hits|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> Aamir's ''[[Dangal (film)|Dangal]]'' (2016) created the [[Bollywood 1000 Crore Club]], owing to its overseas success in [[Greater China|Chinese markets]], and eventually created the [[1000 Crore Club|2000 Crore Club]], becoming the highest-grossing Indian film ever (worldwide and [[List of highest-grossing Indian films in overseas markets|overseas]]), and one of the [[List of highest-grossing films in China|highest-grossing films in China]] and India, with his earnings from the film estimated to be {{INRConvert|300|c}},<ref>[http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/dangals-china-success-may-have-brought-aamir-khan-a-neat-rs-100-crore-paycheque-3526673.html Dangal's China success may have brought [[Aamir Khan]] a neat Rs 100 crore paycheque], [[Firstpost]], 7 June 2017</ref> the [[List of highest paid film actors|highest payday]] for a non-Hollywood actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/06/06/aamir-khans-china-paycheck-for-dangal-could-exceed-rs-100-crore-15-mm/|title=Aamir Khan's China Paycheck For 'Dangal' Could Exceed Rs. 100 Crore / $15 MM|first=Rob|last=Cain|publisher=}}</ref> In 2014, Shah Rukh was the richest non-Hollywood actor and the second richest actor in the world, with an estimated [[net worth]] of US$600 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Shah-Rukh-Khan-second-richest-actor-10-richest-actors/articleshow/35431720.cms|title=Shah Rukh Khan second richest actor in the world - Times of India \u25ba|publisher=|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> On the 2016 ''[[Forbes]]'' list of the 10 highest-paid actors in the world, Salman ranked sixth, with total earnings of US$33.5 million for the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/emjl45mmei/7-salman-khan/ |title=Salman Khan - In Photos: The World's Highest-Paid Actors 2015 |work=Forbes |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> On 2017's <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/599b0ba431358e60d7768f66/the-worlds-highest-paid-a/|title=The World's Highest-Paid Actors 2017|website=Forbes}}</ref> and 2018's <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/5b7b16ada7ea43757f2cb680/the-worlds-highest-paid-a/|title=9. Salman Khan|website=Forbes}}</ref> ''[[Forbes]]'' list of the 10 highest-paid actors in the world, Salman Khan ranked 9th both years, earning $37 million and $38.5 million in 2017 and 2018, respectively.\n\nIn addition to the three Khans, there have been other Khans in Bollywood. The most famous Khan prior to them was [[Dilip Kumar]], whose real name is Muhammad Yusuf Khan, for which he has been referred to as the \"First Khan\" of Bollywood. Kumar was one of the biggest Indian movie stars of the 1950s and 1960s.<ref name=\"indianexpress\"/> His 1960 film ''[[Mughal-e-Azam]]'' was the first Indian film with an adjusted gross over [[Bollywood 1000 Crore Club|{{INR}}1000 crore]],<ref name=\"gold\"/><ref name=\"gold3\"/> making it the highest-grossing Indian film for over five decades.<ref name=\"gold3\"/> The term \"fourth Khan\" is sometimes used to refer to either [[Saif Ali Khan]] or [[Irrfan Khan]]\n\n==Three Khans==\n===Aamir Khan===\n[[File:AamirKhan.jpg|thumb|[[Aamir Khan]] at an event in 2008. He has been the most internationally successful Indian actor since the late 2000s.<ref name=\"movie-star\"/>]]\n{{Main|Aamir Khan}}\n[[Aamir Khan]] (born Mohammed Aamir Hussain Khan on 14 March 1965) is one of the biggest and most commercially successful superstars of India.<ref name=\"koimoi.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-news/aamir-khan-is-the-worlds-biggest-superstar-says-a-trade-analyst/|title=Aamir Khan Is The Worlds Biggest Superstar Says A Trade Analyst!|date=29 March 2018}}</ref> He has a reputation of doing fewer movies but with great attention to detail, including content and quality. Through his successful career in [[Bollywood|Hindi films]], Khan has established himself as one of the most popular and influential actors of [[Cinema of India|Indian cinema]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2006/aug/17sd11.htm|title=Readers' Picks: Top Bollywood Actors|date=17 August 2006|publisher=Rediff|accessdate=26 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2006/aug/08sld11.htm|title=Powerlist: Top Bollywood Actors|date=8 August 2006|publisher=Rediff|accessdate=26 January 2010}}</ref> In addition to being highly popular in India, he is also highly popular overseas, particularly in [[China]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/dangal-wins-china-why-aamir-is-truly-the-alpha-khan-of-bollywood-1717537|title=Dangal Wins China: Why Aamir Is Truly The Alpha Khan Of Bollywood|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/06/11/how-to-become-a-foreign-movie-star-in-china-aamir-khans-5-point-formula-for-success/|title=How To Become A Foreign Movie Star In China: Aamir Khan's 5-Point Formula For Success|first=Rob|last=Cain|publisher=}}</ref> the second largest movie market.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://reuters.com/article/india-bollywood-aamir-khan-dangal-interv-idUKKBN18R0RQ|title=Q&A: Aamir Khan on what it takes to crack China's box office|first=Shilpa|last=Jamkhandikar|publisher=|newspaper=Reuters|date=31 May 2017}}</ref> He is \"arguably the world's biggest [[movie star]]\" according to Rob Cain,<ref name=\"movie-star\">{{cite web|last1=Cain|first1=Rob|title=Why Aamir Khan Is Arguably The World's Biggest Movie Star, Part 2|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/10/05/heres-why-aamir-khan-is-arguably-the-worlds-biggest-movie-star-part-2/|website=[[Forbes]]|date=5 October 2017}}</ref> due to his immense popularity in the world's two [[List of countries and dependencies by population|most populous nations]], India and China.<ref name=\"movie-star\"/>\n\nHe is the recipient of [[List of awards and nominations received by Aamir Khan|numerous awards]], including four [[National Film Awards]] and seven [[Filmfare Awards]], as well as an [[Academy Award]] nomination. He was honoured by the [[Government of India]] with the [[Padma Shri]] in 2003 and the [[Padma Bhushan]] in 2010.<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |accessdate=21 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\nKhan first appeared on screen as a child actor in his uncle [[Nasir Hussain]]'s film ''[[Yaadon Ki Baaraat]]'' (1973), the first Bollywood [[masala film]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cain|first1=Rob|title=Aamir Khan's 'Secret Superstar' Could Be India's Next \u20b91,000 Crore/$152M Box Office Hit|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/10/03/aamir-khans-secret-superstar-could-be-indias-next-\u20b91000-crore160m-box-office-hit/|website=[[Forbes]]|date=3 October 2017}}</ref> His first feature film role came with the [[experimental film]] ''[[Holi (1984 film)|Holi]]'' (1984), and he began a full-time acting career with a leading role in the highly successful tragic romance ''[[Qayamat Se Qayamat Tak]]'' (1988). ''Qayamat Se Qayamat Tak'' was a milestone in the history of [[Hindi cinema]], setting the template for Bollywood musical romance films that defined Hindi cinema in the 1990s.<ref name=\"Ray\">{{cite news|last=Ray|first=Kunal|title=Romancing the 1980s|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/Romancing-the-1980s/article16898867.ece|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=18 December 2016|language=en-IN}}</ref><ref name=\"Chintamani\">{{cite book|last=Chintamani|first=Gautam|title=Qayamat Se Qayamat Tak: The Film That Revived Hindi Cinema|date=2016|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|isbn=9789352640980|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Qayamat_Se_Qayamat_Tak_The_Film_That_Rev.html?id=BZYOvgAACAAJ}}</ref> His performance in the film and in the thriller ''[[Raakh]]'' (1989) earned him a [[National Film Award \u2013 Special Jury Award (Feature Film)|Special Jury Award]] at the National Film Award ceremony. He established himself as a leading actor of Hindi cinema in the 1990s by appearing in several commercially successful films, including the romantic drama ''[[Dil (1990 film)|Dil]]'' (1990), the romance ''[[Raja Hindustani]]'' (1996), for which he won his first [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor]], and the drama ''[[Sarfarosh]]'' (1999).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2000/nov/30aamir.htm|title=I become the audience|author=Press Trust India|date=30 November 2000|publisher=[[Rediff]]|accessdate=26 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibosnetwork.com/asp/clsActorDisplay.asp?actor=Aamir+Khan&layout=filmography|title=The Aamir Khan Station|publisher=IBOS Network|accessdate=16 January 2009}}</ref> He was also noted for playing against type in the critically acclaimed [[Cinema of Canada|Canadian]]-Indian film ''[[Earth (1998 film)|Earth]]'' (1998).\n\nIn 2001, Khan started a [[Aamir Khan Productions|production company]], whose first release, ''[[Lagaan]]'', was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]] and earned him a [[National Film Award for Best Popular Film Providing Wholesome Entertainment|National Film Award for Best Popular Film]] and two more Filmfare Awards (Best Actor and [[Filmfare Award for Best Film|Best Film]]). After a four-year absence from the screen, Khan continued to portray leading roles, most notably in the 2006 box-office hits ''[[Fanaa (film)|Fanaa]]'' and ''[[Rang De Basanti]]''. The following year, he made his directorial debut with ''[[Taare Zameen Par]]'', a major success that garnered him the Filmfare Awards for Best Film and [[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]]. Khan's greatest commercial successes came with the thriller ''[[Ghajini (2008 film)|Ghajini]]'' (2008), the comedy-drama ''[[3 Idiots]]'' (2009), the adventure film ''[[Dhoom 3]]'' (2013), the satire ''[[PK (film)|PK]]'' (2014) and wrestling-drama ''[[Dangal (film)|Dangal]]'' (2016) all of which held records for being the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing Indian film of all time]].<ref name=\"pk\">{{cite news|title='PK' highest grosser ever: Aamir Khan to enter Rs 300 crore club|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-pk-highest-grosser-ever-aamir-khan-to-enter-rs-300-crore-club-2049501|accessdate=5 January 2015|work=Daily News and Analysis|date=4 January 2015}}</ref> After the success of Dangal the Question of Aamir Khan Being the Worlds Biggest Superstar <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/121018/is-aamir-khan-worlds-biggest-superstar-heres-what-you-need-to-kno.html|title=Is Aamir Khan World's biggest superstar? Here's what you need to know!|date=12 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movietalkies.com/news/whoa-aamir-khan-worlds-biggest-superstar/|title=Whoa! Aamir Khan Is 'World's Biggest Superstar'!|date=13 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"koimoi.com\"/> has been posed.<ref name=\"Aamir Khan Worlds Biggest Superstar?\">{{cite news|title=Is Aamir Khan World's biggest superstar? Here's what you need to know!|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/121018/is-aamir-khan-worlds-biggest-superstar-heres-what-you-need-to-kno.html|work=deccanchronicle.com}}</ref>\n\n===Salman Khan===\n[[File:Salmanrampwalk.png|150px|thumbnail|right|[[Salman Khan]] ramp walk in 2011.<ref name=\"hindustantimes\"/> He has been the most domestically successful Indian actor in the 2010s.<ref name=\"Groves\">{{cite news|last1=Groves|first1=Don|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dongroves/2017/06/27/tubelight-may-be-a-setback-but-salman-khans-star-power-is-undimmed/|title='Tubelight' May Be A Setback But Salman Khan's Star Power Is Undimmed|date=27 June 2017|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>]]\n{{Main|Salman Khan}}\nAbdul Rashid Salim Salman Khan (born 27 December 1965)<ref>{{cite news|title=Bollywood wishes Salman Khan on his 46th birthday|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_bollywood-wishes-salman-khan-on-his-46th-birthday_1630590|accessdate=27 April 2012|newspaper=[[DNA India]]|date=27 December 2011|agency=Press Trust of India|place=[[New Delhi]]}}</ref> better known as Salman Khan (pronunciation : {{IPA-hns|s\u0259l\u02c8ma\u02d0n \u02c8xa\u02d0n|}};) is one of the biggest and the most economically viable actors of India. In recent years, every movie he has acted in as the main lead has commended over 100 Crores. Referred to in the media as \"The Tiger of Bollywood\", \"Blockbuster Khan\", \"Box-office King\", he is popularly called \"Bhaijaan\" and \"Sallu\" by his fans. Described by the [[CNN]] as one of the world's biggest stars,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/05/06/entertainment/salman-khan-feat/|title=Who is Salman Khan? One of the world's biggest stars - CNN.com|author=Lisa Respers France, CNN|date=6 May 2015|work=CNN|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref> he has a significant following in Asia and the Indian diaspora worldwide. He is cited in the media as one of the most popular, influential<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/list/ls051665794/|title=IMDb: The 25 Greatest Indian Actors Of All Time - a list by swarupbasak|work=IMDb|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref>  and commercially successful actors of [[Bollywood|Hindi cinema]].<ref name=\"hindustantimes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/SALMAN-KHAN-Hail-Bollywood-s-new-king/Article1-920785.aspx |title=SALMAN KHAN: Hail Bollywood's new king |work=Hindustan Times |date=28 August 2012 |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826151520/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/SALMAN-KHAN-Hail-Bollywood-s-new-king/Article1-920785.aspx |archivedate=26 August 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nKhan began his acting career with a supporting role in ''[[Biwi Ho To Aisi]]'' (1988) and achieved a breakthrough with a leading role in his next release {{mdash}} [[Sooraj Barjatya]]'s romance ''[[Maine Pyar Kiya]]'' (1989). Khan went on to establish himself in Bollywood in the 1990s with roles in several top-grossing productions, including the romantic drama ''[[Hum Aapke Hain Koun..!]]'' (1994), the action thriller ''[[Karan Arjun]]'' (1995), the comedy ''[[Biwi No.1]]'' (1999), and the family drama ''[[Hum Saath-Saath Hain]]'' (1999). For his role in [[Karan Johar]]'s romantic drama ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'' (1998), Khan was awarded the [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor]]. After a brief period of decline in the 2000s, He also starred in the critically acclaimed movie ''[[Tere Naam]]'' (2003). Khan achieved greater stardom in the 2010s by playing the lead role in several successful action films, including ''[[Dabangg]]'' (2010), ''[[Bodyguard (2011 Hindi film)|Bodyguard]]'' (2011), ''[[Ek Tha Tiger]]'' (2012), ''[[Kick (2014 film)|Kick]]'' (2014), ''[[Bajrangi Bhaijaan]]'' (2015) and ''[[Tiger Zinda Hai]]'' (2017) nine of the films he has acted in, have accumulated gross earnings of over {{INRConvert|1|b}},<ref name=\"GROSS\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=4409&nCat= |title=Top All Time Worldwide Grossers Updated 11/5/2012 |publisher=[[Box Office India]] |accessdate=11 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007021530/http://boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=4409&nCat= |archivedate=7 October 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"world\">{{cite web|title=Top Worldwide Grossers ALL TIME: 37 Films Hit 100 Crore |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3997&nCat= |publisher=[[Box Office India]] |accessdate=3 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205213224/http://boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3997&nCat= |archivedate= 5 February 2012 |df= }}</ref> and he has starred in the highest-grossing Bollywood films of nine separate years which is a [[Bollywood]] record.<ref>[http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=2043&nCat=box_office_news DABANGG Is 17th ALL TIME BLOCKBUSTER].  [[Box Office India]]. Retrieved 25 May 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924023928/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=2043&nCat=box_office_news |date=24 September 2010 }}</ref> For his contributions to film, the Government of India honored him with the 2008 - [[Rajiv Gandhi]] Award for Outstanding Achievement in Entertainment.\n\nSalman Khan was ranked 7th in [[Forbes]]'s first global list of the highest-paid actor in the world with  US$33.5 million, earning more than Hollywood actors like [[Dwayne The Rock Johnson]], [[Johnny Depp]], [[Brad Pitt]] and [[Leonardo DiCaprio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/salman-amitabh-akshay-among-worlds-top-10-highest-paid-actors/#sthash.IXAelL8Q.dpuf.|title=Salman, Akshay, Big B in Forbes Top 10 highest-paid actors list, earn more than Johnny Depp|date=5 August 2015|work=The Indian Express|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/emjl45mmei/7-salman-khan/|title=Salman Khan - In Photos: The World's Highest-Paid Actors 2015|author=Natalie Robehmed|work=Forbes|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/amitabh-bachchan-salman-khan-akshay-kumar-among-worlds-top-ten-highest-paid-actors-1030476.html|title=Amitabh Bachchan, Salman Khan, Akshay Kumar among world's top ten highest-paid actors|work=IBNLive|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/salman-amitabh-akshay-among-worlds-top-10-highest-paid-actors/|title=Salman, Akshay, Big B in Forbes Top 10 highest-paid actors list, earn more than Johnny Depp|date=5 August 2015|work=The Indian Express|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Shah Rukh Khan===\n[[File:Shahrukh interacts with media after KKR's maiden IPL title.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Shah Rukh Khan]] in 2012. He was the most successful Indian actor for most of the 1990s and 2000s.<ref name=\"movie-star\"/>]]\n\n{{Main|Shah Rukh Khan}}\nShah Rukh Khan (born Shahrukh Khan, 2 November 1965), popularly called as SRK, is sometimes referred to in the media as the \"Baadshah of Bollywood\", \"King of Bollywood\", \"King Khan\", \"King of Romance\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2012/12/68379/bollywood-demigod-khan-casts-spell-on-moroccans/|title=Bollywood 'Demigod' Khan Casts Spell on Moroccans|date=3 December 2012|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-shah-rukh-khan-as-popular-as-pope-german-media-1150157|title=Shah Rukh Khan as popular as Pope: German media|date=10 February 2008|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ranisingh/2015/12/26/shah-rukh-khan-the-biggest-movie-star-in-the-world/#2e7fa2f6567b|title=Shah Rukh Khan - The Biggest Movie Star In The World.|first=Rani|last=Singh|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2016/04/16/dont-worry-heres-proof-that-srk-is-still-absolutely-the-worlds-biggest-movie-star/#787f99fb34e3|title=Don't Worry, Here's Proof That Shah Rukh Khan Is Still The World's Biggest Movie Star|first=Rob|last=Cain|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/04/30/worlds-biggest-movie-star-gives-a-ted-talk-in-vancouver-but-no-one-knows-who-he-is-6606988/|title=World's biggest movie star gives TED talk but no one knows who he is|date=30 April 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclearlife.com/television/shah-rukh-khan-worlds-biggest-movie-star/|title=Meet Shah Rukh Khan, the World's Biggest Movie Star You've Never Heard Of|date=4 January 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/huntsville/index.ssf/2018/05/indian_movie_megastar_shah_ruk.html|title=Indian movie megastar Shah Rukh Khan filming in Alabama|publisher=|date=11 May 2018}}</ref> He is a self-made Superstar who entered Bollywood without any background and became successful. He is the most successful actor in Bollywood. He has appeared in several successful romantic love stories including ''[[Darr]]'', ''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]'', ''[[Dil to Pagal Hai]]'', ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'' and ''[[Veer Zaara]]'' among others. He is also a recipient of 8 Filmfare for 'Best Actor in a leading role awards' (tied with legendary [[Dilip Kumar]]) and won a total of 14 Filmfare awards. He has appeared in more than 80&nbsp;[[Bollywood]] films. Described by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' as perhaps \"The World's Biggest Movie Star\", Khan has a significant following in Asia and the [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Indian diaspora]] worldwide. He is one of the richest actors in the world, with an estimated net worth of {{US$|link=yes}}790 million, and his work in Bollywood has earned him [[List of awards and nominations received by Shah Rukh Khan|numerous accolades]], including 14&nbsp;[[Filmfare Awards]].\n\nKhan started his career with appearances in several television-series in the late 1980s. He made his Bollywood debut in 1992 with ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]''. Early in his career, Khan was recognised for portraying villainous roles in the films ''[[Darr]]'' (1993), ''[[Baazigar]]'' (1993) and ''[[Anjaam]]'' (1994). He then rose to prominence after starring in a series of romantic films, including ''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]'' (1995), ''[[Dil To Pagal Hai]]'' (1997), ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'' (1998) and ''[[Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham...]]'' (2001). He earned critical acclaim for his portrayals of an alcoholic in ''[[Devdas (2002 Hindi film)|Devdas]]'' (2002), a NASA scientist in ''[[Swades]]'' (2004), a hockey coach in ''[[Chak De! India]]'' (2007), a man with [[Asperger syndrome]] in ''[[My Name Is Khan]]'' (2010), a forty-year old bachelor in ''[[Chennai Express]]'' (2013), a dancer in the musical heist comedy movie ''[[Happy New Year (2014 film)|Happy New Year]]'' (2014), a deranged fan in the psychological thriller movie ''[[Fan (film)|Fan]]'' (2016) and a gangster in the crime thriller movie ''[[Raees (film)|Raees]]'' (2017).\n\nMany of his films display themes of Indian national identity and connections with diaspora communities, or gender, racial, social and religious differences and grievances. For his contributions to film, the Government of India honored him with the [[Padma Shri]], and the Government of France awarded him both the [[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]] and the [[Legion of Honour|L\u00e9gion d'honneur]].\n\nAlong with the awards, he has been awarded four honorary doctorates.\n\n==Other Khans==\n{{See also|Khan (surname)|Salim Khan family|List of Hindi film clans}}\n\n===Dilip Kumar (Muhammad Yusuf Khan) ===\n[[File:DilipKumar.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Dilip Kumar]] (Muhammad Yusuf Khan) in 2010. He was one of the biggest Indian movie stars of the 1950s and 1960s.<ref name=\"indianexpress\"/>]]\n{{Main|Dilip Kumar}}\n\n[[Dilip Kumar]], whose real name is Muhammad Yusuf Khan,<ref>Tanuja Chandra (3 March 2004) [http://sify.com/entertainment/movies/bollywood/celebcolumns/fullstory.php?id=13418077 Dilip Kumar: Silent Revolutionary] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040428030606/http://sify.com/entertainment/movies/bollywood/celebcolumns/fullstory.php?id=13418077 |date=28 April 2004 }} Sify Movies. Retrieved on 30 March 2009.</ref> has been retrospectively referred to as the \"First Khan\" of Bollywood.<ref name=\"indianexpress\">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/dilip-kumar-happy-birthday-turns-94-a-look-at-his-journey-india-first-method-actor-4420625/|title=Happy Birthday Dilip Kumar: As Dilip Kumar turns 94, a look at his titanic reputation as India's finest method actor|date=11 December 2016|publisher=}}</ref> He debuted in the 1940s, and became one of the biggest Indian [[movie star]]s of the 1950s and 1960s.<ref name=\"indianexpress\"/> He is credited with bringing realism to film acting in the [[Indian subcontinent]], and is considered one of the greatest and most influential actors of all time. He has been described as \"the ultimate [[method actor]]\" (natural actor) by [[Satyajit Ray]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Unmatched innings|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/magazine/article597902.ece|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208164035/http://www.thehindu.com/arts/magazine/article597902.ece|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 February 2012|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=24 January 2012|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref> Kumar was a pioneer of method acting, predating [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] method actors such as [[Marlon Brando]]. Kumar inspired future generations of Indian actors, from [[Amitabh Bachchan]] and [[Naseeruddin Shah]] to [[Shah Rukh Khan]] to [[Nawazuddin Siddiqui]].<ref>[https://www.thequint.com/entertainment/2015/12/11/before-brando-there-was-dilip-kumar Before Brando, There Was Dilip Kumar], The Quint, 11 December 2015</ref> In the 1950s, Dilip Kumar became the first actor to charge {{INRConvert|1|l|year=1953|lk=l}} per film.<ref>{{cite news|title=B-Town rewind: The tale of the first Bollywood crore|url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/b-town-rewind-the-tale-of-the-first-bollywood-crore/15162064|work=[[Mid Day]]|date=16 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nKumar is known for his roles in films such as the romantic ''[[Andaz (1949 film)|Andaz]]'' (1949), the swashbuckling ''[[Aan]]'' (1952), the dramatic ''[[Devdas (1955 film)|Devdas]]'' (1955), the comical ''[[Azaad (1955 film)|Azaad]]'' (1955) and ''[[Ram Aur Shyam]]'' (1967), the historical ''[[Mughal-e-Azam]]'' (1960), and the social ''[[Ganga Jamuna]]'' (1961). His biggest commercial success was portraying [[Prince Salim]] in [[K. Asif]]'s big-budget epic [[historical film]] ''Mughal-e-Azam'', which was the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing film]] in Indian film history for 15 years until it was surpassed by 1975's ''[[Sholay]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/Mughal-e-Azam-1960/article15939167.ece|title=Mughal-e-Azam (1960)|date=31 July 2009|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> If adjusted for inflation, ''Mughal-e-Azam'' was the highest-grossing Indian film for more than five decades, equivalent to over [[Bollywood 1000 Crore Club|{{INR}}1000 crore]] in 2011,<ref name=\"gold\">[http://www.boxofficeindia.co.in/worth-their-weight-in-gold/ Worth Their Weight In Gold] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915183938/http://boxofficeindia.co.in/worth-their-weight-in-gold |date=15 September 2017 }}, ''[[Box Office India]]'', 1 November 2011</ref><ref name=\"gold3\">[http://boxofficeindia.co.in/top-50-film-of-last-50-years/ Top 50 Film of Last 50 Years] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104181418/http://boxofficeindia.co.in/top-50-film-of-last-50-years/ |date=4 November 2011 }}, ''[[Box Office India]]'', 3 November 2011</ref> until it was surpassed by Aamir Khan's ''[[Dangal (film)|Dangal]]'' in 2017.\n\n===Saif Ali Khan===\n[[File:Saif Ali Khan snapped at Imperial Hotel, New Delhi 05.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Saif Ali Khan]] at [[New Delhi]], [[India]] in 2012]]\n{{Main|Saif Ali Khan}}\nSaif Ali Khan - sometimes referred to as the \"Fourth Khan\", also a [[film producer]], son of [[Mansoor Ali Khan Pataudi]], a former captain of the [[Indian national cricket team]], and actress [[Sharmila Tagore]].<ref name=sak>Deepa Gahlot (July 1998) [http://www.sabrang.com/cc/comold/august98/saif.htm \u2018Religion played a major role in my upbringing\u2019] [[Sabrang Communications]]. Retrieved on 3 April 2009.</ref><ref>Subhash K Jha (21 August 2008) [http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-08-21/news-interviews/27923991_1_saif-muslim-societies ''\u2018I went to a Muslim builder,' says Saif''] The Times of India. Retrieved on 30 March 2009.</ref> The 2004 romantic comedy ''[[Hum Tum]]'' proved to be Khan's first success in which he played the sole male lead, earning him the [[National Film Award for Best Actor]], and starring roles in the drama ''[[Parineeta (2005 film)|Parineeta]]'' and the romantic comedy ''[[Salaam Namaste]]'' (both 2005) established him as a leading actor in Bollywood.<ref>[http://daily.bhaskar.com/news/CEL-saif-ali-khan-doesnt-want-to-be-called-the-fourth-khan-3536103.html Saif Ali Khan doesn\u2019t want to be called the fourth Khan!], ''[[Daily Bhaskar]]'', 17 July 2012</ref> He went on to earn wide critical praise for his portrayal of an apprentice in the 2006 English film ''[[Being Cyrus]]'', a character based on [[William Shakespeare]]'s antagonist [[Iago]] in the 2006 crime film ''[[Omkara (2006 film)|Omkara]]'' and a terrorist in the 2009 thriller ''[[Kurbaan (2009 film)|Kurbaan]]''. Khan's highest commercial success came with the 2008 thriller ''[[Race (2008 film)|Race]]'' and its 2013 [[Race 2|sequel]], the 2009 romance ''[[Love Aaj Kal]]'', and the 2012 romantic comedy ''[[Cocktail (2012 film)|Cocktail]]''.\n\n===Irrfan Khan===\n[[File:Irrfan Khan May 2015.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Irrfan Khan|Irfan Khan]] in 2015]]\n{{Main|Irrfan Khan}}\nIrrfan Khan has garnered the [[National Film Award for Best Actor]] in the [[60th National Film Awards|60th National Film Awards 2012]], for his performance in ''[[Paan Singh Tomar (film)|Paan Singh Tomar]]''.<ref name=\"60thaward\">{{cite press_release |title=60th National Film Awards Announced |url=http://pib.nic.in/archieve/others/2013/mar/d2013031801.pdf |publisher=Press Information Bureau (PIB), India |accessdate=18 March 2013}}</ref> Khan has won the 2014 [[Asian Film Award for Best Actor]], the [[National Film Award for Best Actor]], three [[Filmfare Awards]], three [[International Indian Film Academy Awards]], an [[Independent Spirit Award]] nomination, and various international honours. He also hosted a television show and commercials. As of 2015, he had appeared in more than 50 Indian films in Bollywood, and a number of international films, such as ''[[Life of Pi (film)|Life of Pi]]'', ''[[New York, I Love You]]'', ''[[A Mighty Heart (film)|A Mighty Heart]]'', ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'', and ''[[Jurassic World]]'', with a featured role alongside [[Tom Hanks]] in the 2016 adaptation of [[Dan Brown]]'s novel ''[[Inferno (Brown novel)|Inferno]]''. In September 2015, he was appointed as the [[brand ambassador]] for \"''Resurgent Rajasthan''\", a campaign by the [[Government of Rajasthan|state government of Rajasthan]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/jaipur/Local-boy-Irrfan-in-Jaipur-as-a-face-of-Resurgent-Rajasthan/articleshow/48879463.cms|title=Local boy Irfan in Jaipur as a face of Resurgent Rajasthan|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=8 September 2015|accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIrrfan Khan is sometimes also considered the \"fourth Khan\", along with Saif Ali Khan.<ref>{{cite news|title=I have no equation or relationship with Irrfan: Nawazuddin Siddiqui|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/230317/i-have-no-equation-or-relationship-with-irrfant-nawazuddin-siddiqui.html|work=[[Deccan Chronicle]]|date=23 March 2017}}</ref> As of 2017, Irrfan Khan's films have grossed over {{US$|3.6 billion|link=yes}} at the worldwide box office, mostly from his work in international productions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Irrfan Khan Movie Box Office Results|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Actor&id=irrfankhan.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|year=2017|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref> His highest-grossing Hindi films are ''[[Hindi Medium]]'' (2017) and ''[[The Lunchbox]]'' (2013).\n\n===Zayed Khan===\n[[File:Zayed Khan 1.jpg|thumb|right|Zayed Khan at the premiere of [[Mod (film)|Mod]].]]\n{{Main|Zayed Khan}}\nZayed Khan made his screen debut in 2003 in the film ''[[Chura Liyaa Hai Tumne]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Meet the new Khan of bollywood |url=http://archive.mid-day.com/entertainment/2002/nov/37762.htm |publisher=[[MiD DAY]] |date=30 November 2002 |accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref> In 2004, he starred in ''[[Main Hoon Na]]'', which was one of the biggest hits in his career. It was the second highest-grossing film of the year behind ''[[Veer-Zaara]]''. Khan was subsequently nominated for the Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor in 2005. His other notable works include ''[[Shabd (film)|Shabd]]'' (2005), ''[[Dus]]'' (2005), ''[[Yuvvraaj]]'' (2008), ''[[Blue (2009 film)| Blue]]'' (2009) and ''[[Anjaana Anjaani]]'' (2010). In 2011, Khan co-produced the film, ''[[Love Breakups Zindagi]]''. In 2017, Khan made his television debut in the show ''[[Haasil (Indian TV series)|Haasil]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/zayed-khan-sizzles-as-ranvir-raichand-in-the-first-teaser-of-haasil-4808660/|title=Zayed Khan sizzles as Ranvir Raichand in the first teaser of Haasil|work=[[The Indian Express]]|publisher=[[Indian Express Group]]|date=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Actors===\n[[File:SalimKhan.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Salim Khan]], part of [[Salim-Javed]] screenwriting duo and father of Salman Khan, in 2011]]\n\n;Male actors\n*[[Amjad Khan (actor)|Amjad Khan]] \u2013 also director\n*[[Arbaaz Khan]] \u2013 Salman Khan's brother, also a director and producer\n*[[Ayub Khan (actor)|Ayub Khan]] \u2013 Nasir Khan's son and Dilip Kumar's nephew, also an [[Indian television]] actor\n*[[Faisal Khan]] \u2013 Aamir Khan's brother\n*[[Fardeen Khan]] \u2013 Feroz Khan's son\n*[[Feroz Khan (actor)|Feroz Khan]] \u2013 Fardeen Khan's father, also a [[film director]] and producer\n*[[Imran Khan (Bollywood actor)|Imran Khan]] \u2013 Aamir Khan's nephew\n*[[Jayant|Jayant (actor)]] \u2013 Amjad Khan's father \n*[[Kader Khan]] \u2013 Indian-Canadian film actor, comedian, script and dialogue writer, as well as director\n*[[Mazhar Khan (actor, born 1955)|Mazhar Khan]] \u2013 Zeenat Amaan's Husband\n*[[Mehboob Khan]] \u2013 best known as a director and producer, also writer\n*[[Nasir Khan (actor)|Nasir Khan]] \u2013 Dilip Kumar's brother\n*[[Nazir Ahmed Khan]] \u2013 director and producer in [[British India]] and then [[Pakistan]] after [[partition of India]], brother-in-law of filmmaker [[K. Asif]]\n*[[Riyaz Khan]] \u2013 predominantly South Indian actor\n*[[Salim Khan]] \u2013 Salman Khan's father, best known as a [[screenwriter]], as part of screenwriting duo [[Salim-Javed]] (along with [[Javed Akhtar]])\n*[[Sanjay Khan]] \u2013 Zayed Khan's father, also a director and producer\n*[[Shadaab Khan]] \u2013 Amjad Khan's son \n*[[Shahbaz Khan (actor)|Shahbaz Khan]] \u2013 also a television actor\n*[[Sohail Khan]] \u2013 Salman Khan's brother, also a director and producer\n*[[Tariq Khan (actor)|Tariq Khan]] \u2013 Aamir Khan's cousin, Nasir Hussain's nephew\n*[[Zain Khan Durrani]] \u2013 also a model\n*[[Zayed Khan]] \u2013 Sanjay Khan's son, also a producer\n*[[Zuber K. Khan|Zuber Khan]] \u2013 also a television actor\n\n;Female actresses  \n*[[Sharmila Tagore]] (Ayesha Sultana Khan) \u2013 actress, [[Model (person)|model]], [[Central Board of Film Certification]] chairperson, mother of Saif Ali Khan\n*[[Farah Khan]] \u2013 best known as a dance [[choreographer]], director and producer\n*[[Gauhar Khan]] \u2013 also a model\n*[[Jiah Khan]] \u2013 British-American actress who worked in Bollywood\n*[[Kareena Kapoor Khan]] \u2013 Saif Ali Khan's wife, Karishma Kapoor's sister, part of [[Kapoor family]], daughter of actor [[Randhir Kapoor]] and actress [[Babita]]\n*[[Krutika Desai Khan]] \u2013 actress working in film, television and theater\n*[[Soha Ali Khan]] \u2013 Saif Ali Khan's sister, daughter of actress Sharmila Tagore\n*[[Sana Khan]] \u2013 also a model and dancer\n*[[Sara Ali Khan]] \u2013 Saif Ali Khan's daughter\n*[[Zareen Khan]] \u2013 Bollywood actress who has also appeared in [[Tamil cinema|Tamil]] and [[Punjabi cinema|Punjabi films]]\n\n===Others===\n*[[Alvira Khan Agnihotri]] \u2013 film producer and [[fashion design]]er, Salman Khan's sister and Salim Khan's daughter\n*[[Gauri Khan]] \u2013 producer, [[interior design]]er, [[costume designer]], Shah Rukh Khan's wife\n*[[Kabir Khan (director)|Kabir Khan]] \u2013 director, screenwriter, cinematographer\n*[[Mansoor Khan]] \u2013 director, producer, screenwriter, Nasir Hussain's son, Aamir Khan's cousin\n*[[Nasir Hussain]] (Nasir Hussain Khan) \u2013 director, producer, screenwriter, Aamir Khan's uncle\n*[[Nikhat Khan]] \u2013 film producer, Aamir Khan's sister\n*[[Parvati Khan]] \u2013 [[Indo-Trinidadian]] singer and model who worked in Bollywood\n*[[Tahir Hussain]] (Tahir Hussain Khan) \u2013 director, producer, Aamir Khan's father\n* [[Faraaz Khan]] - television actor, son of Yusuf Khan.\n\n==See also==\n*[[100 Crore Club]]\n*[[1000 Crore Club]]\n*[[Khan (surname)]]\n*[[List of highest-grossing Indian films]]\n**[[List of highest-grossing films in India]]\n*[[List of highest-grossing Indian films in overseas markets]]\n**[[List of highest-grossing films in China]]\n*[[List of Hindi film clans]]\n**[[Kapoor family]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Shah Rukh Khan}}\n[[Category:Bollywood]]\n[[Category:Film and video terminology]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Indian Muslims]]\n", "name_user": "39.46.17.40", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eThree Khans)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khans_of_Bollywood"}
{"title_page": "Columbine High School massacre in popular culture", "text_new": "The following is a list of '''cultural references to the 1999 [[Columbine High School massacre]]'''.\n\n==Music==\nReferences to the shootings have appeared in popular music.\n\n*The entire 2000 album ''[[Holy Wood (In the Shadow of the Valley of Death)]]'' by the band [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]] was written as a reaction and rebuttal against the allegation made by politicians, religious and civic leaders and news media that the group inspired the perpetrators to commit the school shooting.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sterngold, James |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/29/us/terror-in-littleton-the-culture-rock-concerts-are-cancelled.html |title=Terror in Littleton: The Culture; Rock Concerts Are Cancelled |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=1999-04-29 |accessdate=2010-11-22 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701001244/http://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/29/us/terror-in-littleton-the-culture-rock-concerts-are-cancelled.html |archivedate=2016-07-01 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Cullen\">{{cite web|last=Cullen |first=Dave |url=http://www.salon.com/1999/09/23/columbine_4/ |title=Inside the Columbine High investigation |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=1999-09-23 |accessdate=2012-05-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517044320/http://www.salon.com/1999/09/23/columbine_4/ |archivedate=2017-05-17 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Screaming\">{{cite magazine |first=Tom|last=Bryant |date=2010-11-10 |title=Screaming For Vengeance |work=[[Kerrang!]] |issue=1338 |pages=40\u201342 |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |issn=0262-6624}}</ref>\n*A song called \"Leave Me Alone\" by goth band [[The Cr\u00fcxshadows]] was remixed as the \"Leave Me Alone (Shaft 20/20 Mix)\" to incorporate audio clips from the anti-goth segment of the ABC news magazine show [[20/20 (US television series)|''20/20'']] that aired the day after the shooting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.livelovebebelieve.net/discography/until.html#6 |title=Leave Me Alone (Shaft 20/20 Mix) remix lyrics |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829090430/http://www.livelovebebelieve.net/discography/until.html#6#6 |archive-date=2017-08-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*Columbine students Jonathan and Stephen Cohen wrote a song called \"Friend Of Mine (Columbine)\", which briefly received airplay in the US after being performed at a memorial service broadcast on nationwide television. The song was pressed to CD, with the proceeds benefiting families affected by the massacre, and over 10,000 copies were ordered. Shortly following the release of the CD single, the song was also featured on the ''[[Lullaby for Columbine]]'' CD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denver-rmn.com/shooting/0420cohe7.shtml |title=Farewell performance for Columbine song |accessdate=December 26, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061023102448/http://www.denver-rmn.com/shooting/0420cohe7.shtml |archivedate=October 23, 2006 }}</ref>\n*[[Amanda Palmer]], one half of [[The Dresden Dolls]], performed \"Strength Through Music\" during the 2007 [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe|Edinburgh Fringe Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EKjwMIofstQ |title=Amanda Palmer at the Speigeltent, Edinburgh Fringe 2007 |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=2012-07-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523214535/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EKjwMIofstQ |archive-date=2014-05-23 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is a song about Columbine. She stated it was written some time earlier, though she did not clarify the time frame. \"Strength Through Music\" is on her first solo CD ''[[Who Killed Amanda Palmer]]'', and she also did a music video version of it shot in [[Lexington High School (Massachusetts)|Lexington High School, Massachusetts]], her alma mater.  The video has a spoken mode-setting preface.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Michael Pope |author2=BriAnna Olson |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o-WXhw1KLwk&feature=results_video&playnext=1&list=PL91DD90263B6B7FCC |title=Strength Through Music - \"Who Killed Amanda Palmer\" Video Series: Part 6 |publisher=YouTube |quote=Part 6 of the \"Who Killed Amanda Palmer\" video series, the music video for \"Strength Through Music\", Director Michael Pope Produced by BriAnna Olson & MediaVox. From the debut solo album \"Who Killed Amanda Palmer\", produced by Ben Folds |date=2009-02-23 |accessdate=2012-07-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523215339/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o-WXhw1KLwk&feature=results_video&playnext=1&list=PL91DD90263B6B7FCC |archive-date=2014-05-23 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Rapper [[Tyler, the Creator]] made a reference to the shooting in his song \"Yonkers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/Tyler-the-creator-yonkers-lyrics|title=Tyler,&nbsp;The Creator \u2013 Yonkers|work=genius.com|accessdate=29 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829161523/https://genius.com/Tyler-the-creator-yonkers-lyrics|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref> He also has a song entitled \"Pigs\" which he stated in a tweet was inspired by the two shooters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/Tyler-the-creator-pigs-lyrics|title=Tyler,&nbsp;The Creator \u2013 Pigs|work=genius.com|accessdate=29 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829121227/https://genius.com/Tyler-the-creator-pigs-lyrics|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Rapper [[Violent J]] of the hip-hop supergroup [[Dark Lotus]] mentioned the Columbine High School massacre on the Dark Lotus' debut album, ''[[Tales from the Lotus Pod]]'', on the 10th track of the album, \"Bad Rep\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/bad-rep-lyrics-dark-lotus.html|title=Dark Lotus - Bad Rep Lyrics - MetroLyrics|work=metrolyrics.com|accessdate=15 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927032739/http://www.metrolyrics.com/bad-rep-lyrics-dark-lotus.html|archive-date=2015-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Rapper [[Bones (rapper)|Bones]] released an album about the shooting on February 25, 2014 titled TeenWitch. The songs go inside the minds of Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold leading up to and throughout the massacre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/albums/Bones/Teenwitch|title=Genius|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829161714/https://genius.com/albums/Bones/Teenwitch|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Rapper [[Eminem]] references the shooting multiple times throughout his discography. Most famously, \"I'm Back\" off of [[The Marshall Mathers LP|''The Marshall Mathers LP'' (2000)]] contained a line about Columbine that was censored.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/159354|title=Genius|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> He references this censorship in \"Rap God\" ([[The Marshall Mathers LP 2|''The Marshall Mathers LP 2'', 2013]]) and repeats the line, saying it will not be censored this time because he is not as famous as when \"I'm Back\" was released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/2314741|title=Genius|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> \"Remember Me?\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/Eminem-remember-me-lyrics|title=Genius|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829162104/https://genius.com/Eminem-remember-me-lyrics|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"The Way I Am\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/Eminem-the-way-i-am-lyrics|title=Genius|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829120051/https://genius.com/Eminem-the-way-i-am-lyrics|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref> (''The Marshall Mathers LP'') also reference the shooting, and the music video for \"White America\" includes a reference to school shootings during the first chorus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RZIzD0ZfTFg&index=9&list=PLhDAtu5k14pZ9HbBHYK2pM2pUqU-cyQgJ|title=YouTube|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210161630/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RZIzD0ZfTFg&index=9&list=PLhDAtu5k14pZ9HbBHYK2pM2pUqU-cyQgJ|archive-date=2019-02-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Foster the People]]'s \"[[Pumped Up Kicks]]\" was inspired by the [[Columbine High School massacre]].\n* \"[[Broccoli (song)|Broccoli]]\" by [[DRAM (rapper)|DRAM]] mentions the [[Columbine High School massacre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/Dram-broccoli-lyrics|title=Broccoli Lyrics|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|accessdate=January 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914232010/https://genius.com/Dram-broccoli-lyrics|archive-date=2017-09-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Donald Glover|Childish Gambino]]'s song \"The Real\" from his mixtape ''I Am Just a Rapper 2'' briefly references Columbine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/Childish-gambino-the-real-lyrics|title=Childish Gambino - The Real Lyrics|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|accessdate=March 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623222247/https://genius.com/Childish-gambino-the-real-lyrics|archive-date=2018-06-23|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Stage==\n*In 2014 a stage play ''[[The Library (play)|The Library]]'' premiered at [[The Public Theater]] in [[New York City]]. The play was written by [[Scott Z. Burns]] and directed by [[Steven Soderbergh]], and starred [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]]. The play was loosely based on Dave Cullen's book ''[[Columbine (book)|Columbine]]'' about the massacre.<ref>{{cite news |last=Horn |first=John |date=24 April 2014 |title='The Library' rewrites the book on Columbine |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-library-steven-soderbergh-hbo-20140424-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=2018-02-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204070408/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-library-steven-soderbergh-hbo-20140424-story.html |archive-date=2018-02-04 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Rooney |first=David |date=16 January 2014 |title=Steven Soderbergh to Direct Off-Broadway Play Starring Chloe Grace Moretz |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/steven-soderbergh-direct-broadway-play-671668 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204123947/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/steven-soderbergh-direct-broadway-play-671668 |archive-date=2018-02-04 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Screen==\n\n===Television===\n*In a ''[[TV Guide]]'' interview, [[Mike Judge]] told the story of a letter he received regarding the ''[[King of the Hill]]'' episode \"Wings of the Dope\", in which a protagonist's deceased boyfriend visits her in the form of an angel. The episode premiered on May 4, 1999, two weeks after the shooting, and the fan who wrote to Judge had been inside the school during it; she credited the episode with helping her allow herself to grieve a friend of hers she was in love with and, during the shooting, decided to finally tell only to find out later that he was one of the shooters (because of this she had been pressured to repress her feelings).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.goodreads.com/quotes/1330542-i-don-t-get-as-much-fan-mail-as-an-actor | title=Mike Judge quote | last=Judge | first=Mike | access-date=2014-10-30 | publisher=Goodreads | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830144951/http://www.goodreads.com/quotes/1330542-i-don-t-get-as-much-fan-mail-as-an-actor | archive-date=2014-08-30 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Two episodes of [[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (TV series)|''Buffy the Vampire Slayer'']] were postponed after they were to air soon after the shootings. The first was the episode [[Earshot (Buffy episode)|\"Earshot\"]]. Though the episode had to do with school violence, there is a scene reminiscent of the [[University of Texas at Austin#History|University of Texas at Austin]]'s shooting. Also \"[[Graduation Day, Part Two]]\" was delayed by almost two months after the shootings because of the scene where the students are wielding weapons. It was only aired after [[The WB Television Network|The WB]] received \"thousands of letters demanding that the finale be aired\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/eonline/20070417/en_tv_eo/71ba1d6e_c07a454e_9d9f_64d02e08e6cb |title=Fox Pulls Bones in Wake of College Massacre |accessdate=April 20, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070429020530/http://news.yahoo.com/s/eonline/20070417/en_tv_eo/71ba1d6e_c07a454e_9d9f_64d02e08e6cb |archivedate=April 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n*In the ''[[American Horror Story]]'' episode \"[[Halloween (American Horror Story)|Halloween (Part 2)]]\", the ghost of a victim of Tate's high school shooting, which he does not recollect, asks him, \"Do you believe in God?\". When he is surprised by the question, she says, \"You asked me if I believe in God and you put a gun to my head.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2011/11/iAmerican-Horror-Storyi-Recap-A-Halloween-Hangover|title=American Horror Story Recap: \"You don\u2019t get it, do you?\"|author=Lily Hoagland|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=19 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714111729/http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2011/11/iAmerican-Horror-Storyi-Recap-A-Halloween-Hangover|archive-date=2014-07-14|url-status=live}}</ref> In the following episode \"[[Piggy Piggy]]\", a sequence in which Tate shoots several victims in a library is depicted, and it is much like the library massacre in the Columbine shooting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theatlanticwire.com/entertainment/2011/11/american-horror-story-goes-too-far/44808/|work=The Atlantic Wire|date=Nov 10, 2011|title='American Horror Story' Goes Too Far|access-date=2012-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903043122/http://www.theatlanticwire.com/entertainment/2011/11/american-horror-story-goes-too-far/44808/|archive-date=2012-09-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*An episode of the [[Discovery Channel]] show ''[[Zero Hour (2004 TV series)|Zero Hour]]'' documents the events of the massacre, and includes a detailed reenactment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0754392/?ref_=ttep_ep2|title=IMDb - Zero Hour - Massacre at Columbine High|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210161630/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0754392/?ref_=ttep_ep2|archive-date=2019-02-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* In the ''[[Family Guy]]'' episode \"[[Brian & Stewie]]\", [[Stewie Griffin]] mentions that [[Brian Griffin]] cried after Columbine. Which Brian responds because it was a national tragedy, which Stewie then responded it was more of a regional tragedy.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v6sSA6sgtx4</ref> In another Family Guy episode, \"[[Trading Places (Family Guy)|Trading Places]]\", [[Peter Griffin]] is wearing a black trench coat, similar to what Harris and Klebold wore in the massacre and pulls out a shotgun and says it was time to make the popular kids pay for ignoring him.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2012/12/update-pulled-family-guy-episode-to-air-on-sunday-american-dad-haven-on-hold-390711/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701155517/https://deadline.com/2012/12/update-pulled-family-guy-episode-to-air-on-sunday-american-dad-haven-on-hold-390711/ |archive-date=2019-07-01 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Columbine is briefly mentioned in the ''[[Cold Case]]'' episode \"Rampage\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0829658/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-11-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327125147/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0829658/ |archive-date=2017-03-27 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Film===\n*''Reunion'', an acclaimed short film about the 13 victims murdered in the Columbine tragedy and what their lives might have been like had they not been cut short.<ref name=\"titleReunion (2009)\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wixW3cVT-hc&feature=g-upl&context=G24ea386AUAAAAAAAAAA |title=Reunion (2009) |accessdate=2012-04-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206230052/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wixW3cVT-hc&feature=g-upl&context=G24ea386AUAAAAAAAAAA |archive-date=2015-12-06 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*In 2003, a mockumentary called ''[[Zero Day (film)|Zero Day]]'' was released that detailed the events leading up to a school shooting. This was heavily based on Columbine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0365960/|title=IMDb - Zero Day|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408074654/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0365960/|archive-date=2018-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*''[[Bowling for Columbine]]'', a documentary by filmmaker [[Michael Moore]], explores the massacre within the context of American culture at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tc.umn.edu/~ryahnke/filmteach/My-Archive-of-Film-Notes/bowling-columbine-VIEW.htm|title=Film Summary: Bowling for Columbine|last=Yahnke|first=Robert|date=2009|website=umn.edu|access-date=2016-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117012648/http://www.tc.umn.edu/~ryahnke/filmteach/My-Archive-of-Film-Notes/bowling-columbine-VIEW.htm|archive-date=2012-11-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*''[[Freddy vs. Jason]]'' Mentioned by Kia and saying that the police were acting like some kind of Columbine thing.\n*''[[I'm Not Ashamed (film)|I'm Not Ashamed]]'' which was released on October 21, 2016. It was commissioned by Rachel Scott's family to honor their daughter, who was the first victim of Columbine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://imnotashamedfilm.com/|title=I'm Not Ashamed|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712231129/http://imnotashamedfilm.com/|archive-date=2016-07-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*''[[Elephant (2003 film)|Elephant]]'' is a 2003 American drama by Gus Van Sant. Set in fictional Watt High School, it is based in part on the Columbine massacre. The film began as a documentary that Van Sant initially intended to make about Columbine. <ref name=\"Crean\">{{cite news |last1=Crean |first1=Ellen |title=2003: Shades Of Columbine |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/2003-shades-of-columbine/ |accessdate=9 December 2018 |work=cbsnews.com |date=21 May 2003 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825005754/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/2003-shades-of-columbine/ |archive-date=25 August 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n*A 2005 video game titled ''[[Super Columbine Massacre RPG!]]'' was independently made by [[Danny Ledonne]]. In the game, players take control of Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold and act out the massacre, while going through flashbacks of the pair's experiences. Following the massacre, the player takes control of Harris and Klebold in a fictional adventure in [[Hell in Christian beliefs|perdition]]. The game received huge controversy, as people believed it was glorifying the massacre and could be used by potential future killers as inspiration.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2015/11/columbine-massacre-rpg-creator-banned-from-college-campus-film-festival/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818224805/https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2015/11/columbine-massacre-rpg-creator-banned-from-college-campus-film-festival/ |archive-date=2019-08-18 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Literature==\n* Brooks Brown, a survivor who was targeted by law enforcement and students after the massacre due to his lifelong friendship with Dylan Klebold, reacted to the shooting and its aftermath in his 2002 memoir ''No Easy Answers: The Truth Behind Death at Columbine''.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n* The 2009 Jeff Kass book ''Columbine: A True Crime Story'' is a book in which the author explains the events that lead to the tragedy using research.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n* Shooter Dylan Klebold's mother, Susan Klebold, published an essay about the aftermath of the massacre in a 2009 issue of ''O Magazine''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_13530104 |title=Dylan Klebold's mom speaks in \"O\" Magazine |publisher=The Denver Post |date=October 10, 2009 |accessdate=November 27, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208150513/http://www.denverpost.com/ci_13530104 |archive-date=2015-12-08 |url-status=live }}</ref> She has also written a memoir titled ''A Mother's Reckoning: Living in the Aftermath of Tragedy'', released February 15, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://amothersreckoning.com/|title=A MOTHER'S RECKONING|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725121202/http://amothersreckoning.com/|archive-date=2016-07-25|url-status=live}}</ref> \n* Dave Cullen's book ''[[Columbine (book)|Columbine]]'', released in 2009, includes an analysis of the massacre and the shooters.\n*In ''Theory of Bloom'', Tiqqun reveals the revolutionary potential of school shootings.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n*[[Shoot (Hellblazer)|An unpublished issue]] of ''[[Hellblazer]]'' by [[Warren Ellis]] (writer) and [[Phil Jimenez]] (artist) depicted a study of a series of fictional school shootings. The series is monthly and it would have been the September 1999 (#141) issue, however, the August 1999 (#140) was followed by the October 1999 (#141) issue.<ref>Yarbrough, Beau. [http://www.comicbookresources.com/news/newsitem.cgi?id=2166 ''Unpublished School Shooting 'Hellblazer' Online''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224205551/http://www.comicbookresources.com/news/newsitem.cgi?id=2166 |date=2007-12-24 }}. Comic Book Resources. 21 August 2000.</ref><ref>Yarbrough, Beau. [http://www.comicbookresources.com/columns/index.cgi?column=comicwire&article=305 ''JLA/Avengers Team-Up in the Works''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226131919/http://www.comicbookresources.com/columns/index.cgi?column=comicwire&article=305 |date=2007-12-26 }}. Comic Book Resources. 19 July 1999.</ref>\n*The satirical newspaper ''[[The Onion]]'' discussed the massacre in its article \"Columbine Jocks Safely Resume Bullying\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theonion.com/content/node/29298 |title=Columbine Jocks Safely Resume Bullying &#124; The Onion - America's Finest News Source |publisher=The Onion |date=1999-09-08 |accessdate=2012-07-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100226183632/http://www.theonion.com/content/node/29298 |archive-date=2010-02-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Stephen King]] has cited the massacre as a major reason that he has allowed an early novel to fall out of print: ''[[Rage (Stephen King novel)|Rage]]'', written under the [[Richard Bachman]] pen name, which deals with a high school gunman. (However, certain themes in the book were developed into the story of ''[[Carrie (novel)|Carrie]]''.) King actually referred to Carrie as the \"female version of Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold.\"<ref>[http://www.jimboduck.com/html/Stephen%20King%20-%20On%20writing.pdf ''Stephen King: On writing''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930092228/http://www.jimboduck.com/html/Stephen%20King%20-%20On%20writing.pdf |date=2007-09-30 }}.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n<!-- keep alphabetical -->\n* [[Columbine High School]]\n* [[Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold]]\n* [[School shooting]]\n<!-- keep alphabetical -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Columbine High School massacre}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Works about the Columbine High School massacre| ]]\n[[Category:Topics in popular culture]]\n[[Category:United States in popular culture]]\n", "text_old": "The following is a list of '''cultural references to the 1999 [[Columbine High School massacre]]'''.\n\n==Music==\nReferences to the shootings have appeared in popular music.\n\n*The entire 2000 album ''[[Holy Wood (In the Shadow of the Valley of Death)]]'' by the band [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]] was written as a reaction and rebuttal against the allegation made by politicians, religious and civic leaders and news media that the group inspired the perpetrators to commit the school shooting.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sterngold, James |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/29/us/terror-in-littleton-the-culture-rock-concerts-are-cancelled.html |title=Terror in Littleton: The Culture; Rock Concerts Are Cancelled |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=1999-04-29 |accessdate=2010-11-22 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701001244/http://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/29/us/terror-in-littleton-the-culture-rock-concerts-are-cancelled.html |archivedate=2016-07-01 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Cullen\">{{cite web|last=Cullen |first=Dave |url=http://www.salon.com/1999/09/23/columbine_4/ |title=Inside the Columbine High investigation |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=1999-09-23 |accessdate=2012-05-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517044320/http://www.salon.com/1999/09/23/columbine_4/ |archivedate=2017-05-17 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Screaming\">{{cite magazine |first=Tom|last=Bryant |date=2010-11-10 |title=Screaming For Vengeance |work=[[Kerrang!]] |issue=1338 |pages=40\u201342 |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |issn=0262-6624}}</ref>\n*A song called \"Leave Me Alone\" by goth band [[The Cr\u00fcxshadows]] was remixed as the \"Leave Me Alone (Shaft 20/20 Mix)\" to incorporate audio clips from the anti-goth segment of the ABC news magazine show [[20/20 (US television series)|''20/20'']] that aired the day after the shooting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.livelovebebelieve.net/discography/until.html#6 |title=Leave Me Alone (Shaft 20/20 Mix) remix lyrics |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829090430/http://www.livelovebebelieve.net/discography/until.html#6#6 |archive-date=2017-08-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*Columbine students Jonathan and Stephen Cohen wrote a song called \"Friend Of Mine (Columbine)\", which briefly received airplay in the US after being performed at a memorial service broadcast on nationwide television. The song was pressed to CD, with the proceeds benefiting families affected by the massacre, and over 10,000 copies were ordered. Shortly following the release of the CD single, the song was also featured on the ''[[Lullaby for Columbine]]'' CD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denver-rmn.com/shooting/0420cohe7.shtml |title=Farewell performance for Columbine song |accessdate=December 26, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061023102448/http://www.denver-rmn.com/shooting/0420cohe7.shtml |archivedate=October 23, 2006 }}</ref>\n*[[Amanda Palmer]], one half of [[The Dresden Dolls]], performed \"Strength Through Music\" during the 2007 [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe|Edinburgh Fringe Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EKjwMIofstQ |title=Amanda Palmer at the Speigeltent, Edinburgh Fringe 2007 |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=2012-07-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523214535/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EKjwMIofstQ |archive-date=2014-05-23 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is a song about Columbine. She stated it was written some time earlier, though she did not clarify the time frame. \"Strength Through Music\" is on her first solo CD ''[[Who Killed Amanda Palmer]]'', and she also did a music video version of it shot in [[Lexington High School (Massachusetts)|Lexington High School, Massachusetts]], her alma mater.  The video has a spoken mode-setting preface.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Michael Pope |author2=BriAnna Olson |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o-WXhw1KLwk&feature=results_video&playnext=1&list=PL91DD90263B6B7FCC |title=Strength Through Music - \"Who Killed Amanda Palmer\" Video Series: Part 6 |publisher=YouTube |quote=Part 6 of the \"Who Killed Amanda Palmer\" video series, the music video for \"Strength Through Music\", Director Michael Pope Produced by BriAnna Olson & MediaVox. From the debut solo album \"Who Killed Amanda Palmer\", produced by Ben Folds |date=2009-02-23 |accessdate=2012-07-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523215339/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o-WXhw1KLwk&feature=results_video&playnext=1&list=PL91DD90263B6B7FCC |archive-date=2014-05-23 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Rapper [[Tyler, the Creator]] made a reference to the shooting in his song \"Yonkers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/Tyler-the-creator-yonkers-lyrics|title=Tyler,&nbsp;The Creator \u2013 Yonkers|work=genius.com|accessdate=29 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829161523/https://genius.com/Tyler-the-creator-yonkers-lyrics|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref> He also has a song entitled \"Pigs\" which he stated in a tweet was inspired by the two shooters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/Tyler-the-creator-pigs-lyrics|title=Tyler,&nbsp;The Creator \u2013 Pigs|work=genius.com|accessdate=29 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829121227/https://genius.com/Tyler-the-creator-pigs-lyrics|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Rapper [[Violent J]] of the hip-hop supergroup [[Dark Lotus]] mentioned the Columbine High School massacre on the Dark Lotus' debut album, ''[[Tales from the Lotus Pod]]'', on the 10th track of the album, \"Bad Rep\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/bad-rep-lyrics-dark-lotus.html|title=Dark Lotus - Bad Rep Lyrics - MetroLyrics|work=metrolyrics.com|accessdate=15 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927032739/http://www.metrolyrics.com/bad-rep-lyrics-dark-lotus.html|archive-date=2015-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Rapper [[Bones (rapper)|Bones]] released an album about the shooting on February 25, 2014 titled TeenWitch. The songs go inside the minds of Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold leading up to and throughout the massacre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/albums/Bones/Teenwitch|title=Genius|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829161714/https://genius.com/albums/Bones/Teenwitch|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Rapper [[Eminem]] references the shooting multiple times throughout his discography. Most famously, \"I'm Back\" off of [[The Marshall Mathers LP|''The Marshall Mathers LP'' (2000)]] contained a line about Columbine that was censored.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/159354|title=Genius|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> He references this censorship in \"Rap God\" ([[The Marshall Mathers LP 2|''The Marshall Mathers LP 2'', 2013]]) and repeats the line, saying it will not be censored this time because he is not as famous as when \"I'm Back\" was released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/2314741|title=Genius|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> \"Remember Me?\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/Eminem-remember-me-lyrics|title=Genius|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829162104/https://genius.com/Eminem-remember-me-lyrics|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"The Way I Am\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/Eminem-the-way-i-am-lyrics|title=Genius|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829120051/https://genius.com/Eminem-the-way-i-am-lyrics|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref> (''The Marshall Mathers LP'') also reference the shooting, and the music video for \"White America\" includes a reference to school shootings during the first chorus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RZIzD0ZfTFg&index=9&list=PLhDAtu5k14pZ9HbBHYK2pM2pUqU-cyQgJ|title=YouTube|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210161630/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RZIzD0ZfTFg&index=9&list=PLhDAtu5k14pZ9HbBHYK2pM2pUqU-cyQgJ|archive-date=2019-02-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Foster the People]]'s \"[[Pumped Up Kicks]]\" was inspired by the [[Columbine High School massacre]].\n* \"[[Broccoli (song)|Broccoli]]\" by [[DRAM (rapper)|DRAM]] mentions the [[Columbine High School massacre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/Dram-broccoli-lyrics|title=Broccoli Lyrics|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|accessdate=January 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914232010/https://genius.com/Dram-broccoli-lyrics|archive-date=2017-09-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Donald Glover|Childish Gambino]]'s song \"The Real\" from his mixtape ''I Am Just a Rapper 2'' briefly references Columbine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/Childish-gambino-the-real-lyrics|title=Childish Gambino - The Real Lyrics|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|accessdate=March 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623222247/https://genius.com/Childish-gambino-the-real-lyrics|archive-date=2018-06-23|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Stage==\n*In 2014 a stage play ''[[The Library (play)|The Library]]'' premiered at [[The Public Theater]] in [[New York City]]. The play was written by [[Scott Z. Burns]] and directed by [[Steven Soderbergh]], and starred [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]]. The play was loosely based on Dave Cullen's book ''[[Columbine (book)|Columbine]]'' about the massacre.<ref>{{cite news |last=Horn |first=John |date=24 April 2014 |title='The Library' rewrites the book on Columbine |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-library-steven-soderbergh-hbo-20140424-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=2018-02-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204070408/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-library-steven-soderbergh-hbo-20140424-story.html |archive-date=2018-02-04 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Rooney |first=David |date=16 January 2014 |title=Steven Soderbergh to Direct Off-Broadway Play Starring Chloe Grace Moretz |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/steven-soderbergh-direct-broadway-play-671668 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204123947/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/steven-soderbergh-direct-broadway-play-671668 |archive-date=2018-02-04 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Screen==\n\n===Television===\n*In a ''[[TV Guide]]'' interview, [[Mike Judge]] told the story of a letter he received regarding the ''[[King of the Hill]]'' episode \"Wings of the Dope\", in which a protagonist's deceased boyfriend visits her in the form of an angel. The episode premiered on May 4, 1999, two weeks after the shooting, and the fan who wrote to Judge had been inside the school during it; she credited the episode with helping her allow herself to grieve a friend of hers she was in love with and, during the shooting, decided to finally tell only to find out later that he was one of the shooters (because of this she had been pressured to repress her feelings).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.goodreads.com/quotes/1330542-i-don-t-get-as-much-fan-mail-as-an-actor | title=Mike Judge quote | last=Judge | first=Mike | access-date=2014-10-30 | publisher=Goodreads | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830144951/http://www.goodreads.com/quotes/1330542-i-don-t-get-as-much-fan-mail-as-an-actor | archive-date=2014-08-30 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Two episodes of [[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (TV series)|''Buffy the Vampire Slayer'']] were postponed after they were to air soon after the shootings. The first was the episode [[Earshot (Buffy episode)|\"Earshot\"]]. Though the episode had to do with school violence, there is a scene reminiscent of the [[University of Texas at Austin#History|University of Texas at Austin]]'s shooting. Also \"[[Graduation Day, Part Two]]\" was delayed by almost two months after the shootings because of the scene where the students are wielding weapons. It was only aired after [[The WB Television Network|The WB]] received \"thousands of letters demanding that the finale be aired\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/eonline/20070417/en_tv_eo/71ba1d6e_c07a454e_9d9f_64d02e08e6cb |title=Fox Pulls Bones in Wake of College Massacre |accessdate=April 20, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070429020530/http://news.yahoo.com/s/eonline/20070417/en_tv_eo/71ba1d6e_c07a454e_9d9f_64d02e08e6cb |archivedate=April 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n*In the ''[[American Horror Story]]'' episode \"[[Halloween (American Horror Story)|Halloween (Part 2)]]\", the ghost of a victim of Tate's high school shooting, which he does not recollect, asks him, \"Do you believe in God?\". When he is surprised by the question, she says, \"You asked me if I believe in God and you put a gun to my head.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2011/11/iAmerican-Horror-Storyi-Recap-A-Halloween-Hangover|title=American Horror Story Recap: \"You don\u2019t get it, do you?\"|author=Lily Hoagland|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=19 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714111729/http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2011/11/iAmerican-Horror-Storyi-Recap-A-Halloween-Hangover|archive-date=2014-07-14|url-status=live}}</ref> In the following episode \"[[Piggy Piggy]]\", a sequence in which Tate shoots several victims in a library is depicted, and it is much like the library massacre in the Columbine shooting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theatlanticwire.com/entertainment/2011/11/american-horror-story-goes-too-far/44808/|work=The Atlantic Wire|date=Nov 10, 2011|title='American Horror Story' Goes Too Far|access-date=2012-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903043122/http://www.theatlanticwire.com/entertainment/2011/11/american-horror-story-goes-too-far/44808/|archive-date=2012-09-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*An episode of the [[Discovery Channel]] show ''[[Zero Hour (2004 TV series)|Zero Hour]]'' documents the events of the massacre, and includes a detailed reenactment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0754392/?ref_=ttep_ep2|title=IMDb - Zero Hour - Massacre at Columbine High|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210161630/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0754392/?ref_=ttep_ep2|archive-date=2019-02-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* In the ''[[Family Guy]]'' episode \"[[Brian & Stewie]]\", [[Stewie Griffin]] mentions that [[Brian Griffin]] cried after Columbine. Which Brian responds because it was a national tragedy, which Stewie then responded it was more of a regional tragedy.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v6sSA6sgtx4</ref> In another Family Guy episode, \"[[Trading Places (Family Guy)|Trading Places]]\", [[Peter Griffin]] is wearing a black trench coat, similar to what Harris and Klebold wore in the massacre and pulls out a shotgun and says it was time to make the popular kids pay for ignoring him.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2012/12/update-pulled-family-guy-episode-to-air-on-sunday-american-dad-haven-on-hold-390711/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701155517/https://deadline.com/2012/12/update-pulled-family-guy-episode-to-air-on-sunday-american-dad-haven-on-hold-390711/ |archive-date=2019-07-01 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Columbine is briefly mentioned in the [[Cold Case]] episode \"Rampage\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0829658/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-11-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327125147/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0829658/ |archive-date=2017-03-27 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Film===\n*''Reunion'', an acclaimed short film about the 13 victims murdered in the Columbine tragedy and what their lives might have been like had they not been cut short.<ref name=\"titleReunion (2009)\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wixW3cVT-hc&feature=g-upl&context=G24ea386AUAAAAAAAAAA |title=Reunion (2009) |accessdate=2012-04-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206230052/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wixW3cVT-hc&feature=g-upl&context=G24ea386AUAAAAAAAAAA |archive-date=2015-12-06 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*In 2003, a mockumentary called ''[[Zero Day (film)|Zero Day]]'' was released that detailed the events leading up to a school shooting. This was heavily based on Columbine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0365960/|title=IMDb - Zero Day|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408074654/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0365960/|archive-date=2018-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*''[[Bowling for Columbine]]'', a documentary by filmmaker [[Michael Moore]], explores the massacre within the context of American culture at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tc.umn.edu/~ryahnke/filmteach/My-Archive-of-Film-Notes/bowling-columbine-VIEW.htm|title=Film Summary: Bowling for Columbine|last=Yahnke|first=Robert|date=2009|website=umn.edu|access-date=2016-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117012648/http://www.tc.umn.edu/~ryahnke/filmteach/My-Archive-of-Film-Notes/bowling-columbine-VIEW.htm|archive-date=2012-11-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*''[[Freddy vs. Jason]]'' Mentioned by Kia and saying that the police were acting like some kind of Columbine thing.\n*''[[I'm Not Ashamed (film)|I'm Not Ashamed]]'' which was released on October 21, 2016. It was commissioned by Rachel Scott's family to honor their daughter, who was the first victim of Columbine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://imnotashamedfilm.com/|title=I'm Not Ashamed|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712231129/http://imnotashamedfilm.com/|archive-date=2016-07-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*''[[Elephant (2003 film)|Elephant]]'' is a 2003 American drama by Gus Van Sant. Set in fictional Watt High School, it is based in part on the Columbine massacre. The film began as a documentary that Van Sant initially intended to make about Columbine. <ref name=\"Crean\">{{cite news |last1=Crean |first1=Ellen |title=2003: Shades Of Columbine |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/2003-shades-of-columbine/ |accessdate=9 December 2018 |work=cbsnews.com |date=21 May 2003 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825005754/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/2003-shades-of-columbine/ |archive-date=25 August 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n*A 2005 video game titled ''[[Super Columbine Massacre RPG!]]'' was independently made by [[Danny Ledonne]]. In the game, players take control of Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold and act out the massacre, while going through flashbacks of the pair's experiences. Following the massacre, the player takes control of Harris and Klebold in a fictional adventure in [[Hell in Christian beliefs|perdition]]. The game received huge controversy, as people believed it was glorifying the massacre and could be used by potential future killers as inspiration.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2015/11/columbine-massacre-rpg-creator-banned-from-college-campus-film-festival/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818224805/https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2015/11/columbine-massacre-rpg-creator-banned-from-college-campus-film-festival/ |archive-date=2019-08-18 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Literature==\n* Brooks Brown, a survivor who was targeted by law enforcement and students after the massacre due to his lifelong friendship with Dylan Klebold, reacted to the shooting and its aftermath in his 2002 memoir ''No Easy Answers: The Truth Behind Death at Columbine''.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n* The 2009 Jeff Kass book ''Columbine: A True Crime Story'' is a book in which the author explains the events that lead to the tragedy using research.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n* Shooter Dylan Klebold's mother, Susan Klebold, published an essay about the aftermath of the massacre in a 2009 issue of ''O Magazine''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_13530104 |title=Dylan Klebold's mom speaks in \"O\" Magazine |publisher=The Denver Post |date=October 10, 2009 |accessdate=November 27, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208150513/http://www.denverpost.com/ci_13530104 |archive-date=2015-12-08 |url-status=live }}</ref> She has also written a memoir titled ''A Mother's Reckoning: Living in the Aftermath of Tragedy'', released February 15, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://amothersreckoning.com/|title=A MOTHER'S RECKONING|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725121202/http://amothersreckoning.com/|archive-date=2016-07-25|url-status=live}}</ref> \n* Dave Cullen's book ''[[Columbine (book)|Columbine]]'', released in 2009, includes an analysis of the massacre and the shooters.\n*In ''Theory of Bloom'', Tiqqun reveals the revolutionary potential of school shootings.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n*[[Shoot (Hellblazer)|An unpublished issue]] of ''[[Hellblazer]]'' by [[Warren Ellis]] (writer) and [[Phil Jimenez]] (artist) depicted a study of a series of fictional school shootings. The series is monthly and it would have been the September 1999 (#141) issue, however, the August 1999 (#140) was followed by the October 1999 (#141) issue.<ref>Yarbrough, Beau. [http://www.comicbookresources.com/news/newsitem.cgi?id=2166 ''Unpublished School Shooting 'Hellblazer' Online''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224205551/http://www.comicbookresources.com/news/newsitem.cgi?id=2166 |date=2007-12-24 }}. Comic Book Resources. 21 August 2000.</ref><ref>Yarbrough, Beau. [http://www.comicbookresources.com/columns/index.cgi?column=comicwire&article=305 ''JLA/Avengers Team-Up in the Works''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226131919/http://www.comicbookresources.com/columns/index.cgi?column=comicwire&article=305 |date=2007-12-26 }}. Comic Book Resources. 19 July 1999.</ref>\n*The satirical newspaper ''[[The Onion]]'' discussed the massacre in its article \"Columbine Jocks Safely Resume Bullying\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theonion.com/content/node/29298 |title=Columbine Jocks Safely Resume Bullying &#124; The Onion - America's Finest News Source |publisher=The Onion |date=1999-09-08 |accessdate=2012-07-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100226183632/http://www.theonion.com/content/node/29298 |archive-date=2010-02-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Stephen King]] has cited the massacre as a major reason that he has allowed an early novel to fall out of print: ''[[Rage (Stephen King novel)|Rage]]'', written under the [[Richard Bachman]] pen name, which deals with a high school gunman. (However, certain themes in the book were developed into the story of ''[[Carrie (novel)|Carrie]]''.) King actually referred to Carrie as the \"female version of Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold.\"<ref>[http://www.jimboduck.com/html/Stephen%20King%20-%20On%20writing.pdf ''Stephen King: On writing''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930092228/http://www.jimboduck.com/html/Stephen%20King%20-%20On%20writing.pdf |date=2007-09-30 }}.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n<!-- keep alphabetical -->\n* [[Columbine High School]]\n* [[Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold]]\n* [[School shooting]]\n<!-- keep alphabetical -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Columbine High School massacre}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Works about the Columbine High School massacre| ]]\n[[Category:Topics in popular culture]]\n[[Category:United States in popular culture]]\n", "name_user": "Sullay", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Columbine_High_School_massacre_in_popular_culture"}
{"title_page": "Loyalist (American Revolution)", "text_new": "{{other uses|Loyalism|Loyalist (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Colonists loyal to the British Crown during the American Revolution}}\n{{Toryism}}\n[[File:Reception of the American Loyalists.jpg|thumb|[[Britannia (disambiguation)|Britannia]] offers solace and a promise of compensation for her exiled American-born Loyalists. (Reception of the American Loyalists by Great Britain in the Year 1783. Engraving by H. Moses after [[Benjamin West]].)]]\n[[File:Flag of the United Empire Loyalists.svg|thumb|[[United Empire Loyalist]] flag.]]\n\n'''Loyalists''' were American colonies who stayed loyal to the British Crown during the [[American Revolutionary War]], often called '''Tories''', '''Royalists''', or '''King's Men''' at the time. They were opposed by the [[Patriot (American Revolution)|\"Patriots\"]], who supported the revolution, and called them \"persons inimical to the liberties of America\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Barbara Smith|title=The Freedoms We Lost: Consent and Resistance in Revolutionary America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xzs5XX-QEL8C&pg=PT142|year=2013|publisher=New Press|page=142|isbn=9781595585974}}</ref> Prominent Loyalists repeatedly assured the British government that many thousands of them would spring to arms and fight for the crown.  The British government acted in expectation of that, especially in the southern campaigns in 1780\u201381. In practice, the number of Loyalists in military service was far lower than expected since Britain could not effectively protect them except in those areas where Britain had military control. The British were often suspicious of them, not knowing whom they could fully trust in such a conflicted situation; they were often looked down upon.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Devoss |first1=David |title=Divided Loyalties |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/divided-loyalties-107489501/ |website=smithsonianmag.com |publisher=[[Smithsonian Magazine]] |accessdate=11 July 2019 |language=English |date=January 2004 |quote=Curiously, Tories suffered even at the hands of British officers who, for the most part, dismissed them as ignorant provincials. The British especially distrusted Loyalist militia regiments, claiming that they were slow to follow orders and often went off on their own to seek revenge against those who had destroyed their property.}}</ref> Patriots watched suspected Loyalists very closely and would not tolerate any organized Loyalist opposition.  Many outspoken or militarily active Loyalists were forced to flee, especially to their stronghold of New York City. [[William Franklin]], the royal governor of New Jersey and son of Patriot leader [[Benjamin Franklin]], became the leader of the Loyalists after his release from a Patriot prison in 1778.  He worked to build Loyalist military units to fight in the war, but the number of volunteers was much fewer than London expected.\n\nWhen their cause was defeated, about 15 percent of the Loyalists (65,000\u201370,000 people) fled to other parts of the [[British Empire]], to Britain itself, or to [[British North America]] (now Canada).  The southern Loyalists moved mostly to Florida, which had remained loyal to the Crown, and to British Caribbean possessions, often bringing along their slaves.  Northern Loyalists largely migrated to [[Upper Canada|Ontario]], [[Lower Canada|Quebec]], [[New Brunswick]], and [[Nova Scotia]].  They called themselves [[United Empire Loyalist|United Empire Loyalists]].  Most were compensated with Canadian land or British cash distributed through formal claims procedures.  Loyalists who left the US received \u00a33 million{{citation needed|reason=Body of article says 3.5 millon; neither claims cites a source|date=May 2019}} or about 37% of their losses from the British government.  Loyalists who stayed in the US were generally able to retain their property and become American citizens.<ref>Jack P. Greene and J. R. Pole, eds, ''A Companion to the American Revolution'' (2004) pp. 246, 399, 641\u20132</ref>  Historians have estimated that between 15 and 20% of the 2,000,000 whites in the colonies in 1775 were Loyalists (300,000\u2013400,000).<ref>Calhoon, \"Loyalism and neutrality\", p. 235; Middlekauff (2005) pp. 563\u2013564; Thomas B. Allen, ''Tories: Fighting for the King in America's First Civil War'' (20176) p. xx</ref>\n\n==Background==\nFamilies were often divided during the American Revolution, and many felt themselves to be both American and British, still owing a loyalty to the mother country. Maryland lawyer [[Daniel Dulany the Younger|Daniel Dulaney the Younger]] opposed [[No taxation without representation|taxation without representation]] but would not break his oath to the King or take up arms against him. He wrote: \"There may be a time when redress may not be obtained. Till then, I shall recommend a legal, orderly, and prudent resentment\".<ref>Andrews, p.284</ref> Most Americans hoped for a peaceful reconciliation but were forced to choose sides by the Patriots who took control nearly everywhere in the Thirteen Colonies in 1775\u201376.<ref>Jassanoff, ch 1</ref>\n\n==Motives for Loyalism==\n{{Conservatism US}}\nYale historian Leonard Woods Larabee has identified eight characteristics of the Loyalists that made them essentially conservative and loyal to the king and Britain:<ref>Leonard Woods Larabee, ''Conservatism in Early American History'' (1948) pp 164\u201365</ref>\n* They were older, better established, and resisted radical change\n* They felt that rebellion against the Crown\u2014the legitimate government\u2014was morally wrong.\n* They were alienated when the Patriots resorted to violence, such as burning houses and [[tarring and feathering]].\n* They wanted to take a middle-of-the-road position and were angry when forced by the Patriots to declare their opposition.\n* They had a long-standing sentimental attachment to Britain (often with business and family links).\n* They realized that independence was bound to come someday, but wanted to postpone the moment.\n* They were cautious and afraid that chaos and mob rule would result.\n* Some were pessimists who lacked the confidence in the future displayed by the Patriots. Others recalled the dreadful experiences of many [[Jacobitism|Jacobite]] rebels after the failure of the last Jacobite rebellion as recently as 1745 who often lost their lands when the [[House of Hanover|Hanoverian]] government won.<ref>See also N. E. H. Hull, Peter C. Hoffer and Steven L. Allen, \"Choosing Sides: A Quantitative Study of the Personality Determinants of Loyalist and Revolutionary Political Affiliation in New York,\" ''Journal of American History'',  (1978) 65#2 pp. 344\u2013366 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1894084 in JSTOR]</ref><ref>Edwin G. Burrows and Michael Wallace, \"The American Revolution: The Ideology and Psychology of National Liberation,\" ''Perspectives in American History,'' (1972) vol. 6 pp 167\u2013306</ref><ref>Mark Jodoin. ''Shadow Soldiers of the American Revolution: Loyalist Tales from New York to Canada.'' 2009. {{ISBN|978-1-59629-726-5}}. [[The History Press]], Charleston, SC.</ref>\n\nOther motives of the Loyalists included:\n* They felt a need for order and believed that Parliament was the legitimate authority.<ref>Hull, Hoffer and Allen, \"Choosing Sides'' (1978), p, 352</ref>\n* In New York, powerful families had assembled colony-wide coalitions of supporters, Men long associated with the French Huguenot/Dutch [[De Lancey's Brigade|De Lancey]] faction went along when its leadership decided to support the crown.<ref>Hull, Hoffer and Allen, \"Choosing Sides'' (1978), pp 347, 354, 365</ref>\n* They felt themselves to be weak or threatened within American society and in need of an outside defender such as the British Crown and Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/loyalists|title=Loyalists|first=Bruce G.|last=Wilson|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Black Loyalist|Black loyalists]] had been promised freedom from slavery by the British.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brighthubeducation.com/history-homework-help/112430-loyalists-during-the-american-revolution/|title=Loyalists During the American Revolutionary War: What Happened to Them?|website=Bright Hub Education|date=2011-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blackloyalist.com/canadiandigitalcollection/story/revolution/dunmore.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-03-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515175351/http://www.blackloyalist.com/canadiandigitalcollection/story/revolution/dunmore.htm |archivedate=2013-05-15 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpast.org/?q=aah/lord-dunmore-s-ethiopian-regiment|title=Lord Dunmore's Ethiopian Regiment - The Black Past: Remembered and Reclaimed|website=www.blackpast.org|date=2007-06-29}}</ref>\n* They felt that being a part of the British Empire was crucial in terms of commerce and their business operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mountvernon.org/digital-encyclopedia/article/loyalists/|title=Loyalists|website=George Washington's Mount Vernon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.u-s-history.com/pages/h568.html|title=The Loyalists|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Loyalism and military operations==\n{{See also|Loyalists fighting in the American Revolution}}\nIn the opening months of the Revolutionary War, the Patriots [[Siege of Boston|laid siege]] to [[Boston]], where most of the British forces were stationed. Elsewhere there were few British troops and the Patriots seized control of all levels of government, as well as supplies of arms and gunpowder. Vocal Loyalists recruited people to their side, often with the encouragement and assistance of royal governors. In the South Carolina back country, Loyalist recruitment oustripped that of Patriots. A [[Siege of Savage's Old Fields|brief siege]] at [[Ninety Six, South Carolina]] in the fall of 1775 was followed by a rapid rise in Patriot recruiting, and a [[Snow Campaign]] involving thousands of partisan militia resulted in the arrest or flight of most of the back country Loyalist leadership. North Carolina back country Scots and former [[War of the Regulation|Regulators]] joined forces in early 1776, but they were broken as a force at the [[Battle of Moore's Creek Bridge]].\n\nBy July 4, 1776, the Patriots had gained control of virtually all territory in the Thirteen Colonies and expelled all royal officials. No one who openly proclaimed their loyalty to the Crown was allowed to remain, so Loyalists fled or kept quiet. Some of those who remained later gave aid to invading British armies or joined uniformed Loyalist regiments.<ref>Calhoun (1973){{Page needed|date=January 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe British were forced out of Boston by March 17, 1776. They regrouped at Halifax and attacked [[Province of New York|New York]] in August, defeating [[George Washington]]'s army at [[Long Island]] and capturing [[New York City]] and its vicinity, and they occupied the mouth of the [[Hudson River]] until 1783. British forces seized control of other cities, including [[Philadelphia]] (1777), [[Savannah, Georgia]] (1778\u201383), and [[Charleston, South Carolina]] (1780\u201382). But 90% of the colonial population lived outside the cities, with the effective result that Congress represented 80 to 90 percent of the population. The British removed their governors from colonies where the Patriots were in control, but Loyalist civilian government was re-established in coastal [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]<ref name = \"Gerogian\">[http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-2709 Georgia Encyclop\u00e6dia].</ref> from 1779 to 1782, despite presence of Patriot forces in the northern part of Georgia. Essentially, the British were only able to maintain power in areas where they had a strong military presence.\n\n===Numbers of Loyalists===\nHistorian Robert Calhoon wrote in 2000, concerning the proportion of Loyalists to Patriots in the Thirteen Colonies:\n\n{{quote|Historians' best estimates put the proportion of adult white male loyalists somewhere between 15 and 20 percent. Approximately half the colonists of European ancestry tried to avoid involvement in the struggle\u2014some of them deliberate pacifists, others recent immigrants, and many more simple apolitical folk. The patriots received active support from perhaps 40 to 45 percent of the white populace, and at most no more than a bare majority.<ref>Robert M. Calhoon, in 'A companion to the American Revolution' (2000); p 235.</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Jury finding Kentucky County Virginia John Connolly Daniel Boone 1780.jpg|thumb|upright|right|A jury finding from [[Kentucky County, Virginia]] in July 1780, confiscating lands of two men adjudged to be British subject. [[Daniel Boone]] was listed as a member of the jury.]]\n\nBefore Calhoon's work, estimates of the Loyalist share of the population were somewhat higher, at about one-third, but these estimates are now rejected as too high by most scholars.<ref>[[John Adams]] has sometimes been cited as having claimed, in an 1813 letter, that one-third of Americans supported the revolution and one-third were against. However, the passage in question actually refers to the [[French Revolution of 1789]]. {{cite book|author=Robert D. Marcus|title=The American Scene: Varieties of American History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-w_xPy-S3aEC&pg=PA147|year=1971|page=147|isbn=9780390597731}} See also [http://hnn.us/articles/5641.html \"Only 1/3 of Americans Supported the American Revolution?\"], by William Marina. 6-28-2004. Retrieved on July 14, 2008.</ref>  In 1968 historian Paul H. Smith estimated there were about 400,000 Loyalists, or 16% of the white population of 2.25 million in 1780.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ray Raphael|title=A People's History of the American Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HEXNoC7ket4C&pg=PT393|year=2012|publisher=The New Press|page=393|isbn=9781595588517}}</ref><ref>Paul H. Smith, \"The American Loyalists: Notes on Their Organization and Numerical Strength,\" ''William and Mary Quarterly'' (1968) 25#2 pp. 259\u2013277 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1919095 in JSTOR]</ref>\n\nHistorian [[Robert Middlekauff]] summarized scholarly research on the nature of Loyalist support as follows:\n\n<blockquote>The largest number of loyalists were found in the [[Middle Colonies|middle colonies]]: many [[Tenant farmer|tenant farmers]] of [[Province of New York|New York]] supported [[George III of the United Kingdom|the king]], for example, as did many of the [[Dutch Americans|Dutch]] in the colony and in [[Province of New Jersey|New Jersey]]. The [[German Americans|Germans]] in [[Province of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]] tried to stay out of the Revolution, just as many [[Quakers]] did, and when that failed, clung to the familiar connection rather than embrace the new. [[Scottish Americans|Highland Scots]] in [[the Carolinas]], a fair number of [[Anglicanism|Anglican clergy]] and their parishioners in [[Connecticut Colony|Connecticut]] and [[Province of New York|New York]], a few [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterians]] in the [[Southern Colonies|southern colonies]], and a large number of the [[Iroquois]] stayed loyal to the king.<ref>[https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=84633736 Middlekauff, Robert. ''The Glorious Cause: The American Revolution, 1763\u20131789'' (1985)], p 550.</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[File:Johnson Hall, Johnstown, NY.jpg|left|thumb|Johnson Hall, seat of [[Sir John Johnson, 2nd Baronet|Sir John Johnson]] in the [[Mohawk Valley region|Mohawk Valley]]]]\n\nNew York City and Long Island were the British military and political base of operations in North America from 1776 to 1783 and had a large concentration of Loyalists, many of whom were refugees from other states.<ref name=\"Calhoon 1973\">Calhoon (1973)</ref>\n\nAccording to Calhoon,<ref name=\"Calhoon 1973\"/> Loyalists tended to be older and wealthier, but there were also many Loyalists of humble means. Many active [[Church of England]] members became Loyalists. Some recent arrivals from Britain, especially those from Scotland, had a high Loyalist proportion. Loyalists in the southern colonies were suppressed by the local Patriots, who controlled local and state government. Many people\u2014including former [[War of the Regulation|Regulators]] in [[History of North Carolina|North Carolina]] \u2014 refused to join the rebellion, as they had earlier protested against corruption by local authorities who later became Revolutionary leaders. The oppression by the local [[Patriot (American Revolution)|Whigs]] during the Regulation led to many of the residents of backcountry North Carolina sitting out the Revolution or siding with the Loyalists.<ref name=\"Calhoon 1973\"/>\n\nIn areas under Patriot control, Loyalists were subject to [[Confiscation|confiscation of property]], and outspoken supporters of the king were threatened with public humiliation such as [[tarring and feathering]], or physical attack. It is not known how many Loyalist civilians were harassed by the Patriots, but the treatment was a warning to other Loyalists not to take up arms. In September 1775, [[William Drayton]] and Loyalist leader Colonel Thomas Fletchall signed a treaty of neutrality in the interior community of [[Ninety Six, South Carolina|Ninety Six]], [[South Carolina]].<ref>See [http://www.nps.gov/revwar/revolution_day_by_day/1775_main.html online NPS.gov]</ref> For actively aiding the British army when it occupied Philadelphia, two residents of the city were tried for treason, convicted, and executed by returning Patriot forces.<ref>{{cite book|author=Louis P. Masur |title=Rites of Execution: Capital Punishment and the Transformation of American Culture, 1776-1865|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z6KsUQE57fYC&pg=PA75|year=1989|publisher=Oxford UP|page=75|isbn=9780198021582}}</ref>\n\n===Slavery and Black Loyalists===\n{{Main|Black Loyalist}}\n[[File:AricanNovaScotianByCaptain William Booth1788.png|thumb|A [[Black Loyalist]] wood cutter at [[Shelburne, Nova Scotia]] in 1788]]\nAs a result of the looming crisis in 1775, the Royal [[Governor of Virginia]], [[John Murray, 4th Earl of Dunmore|Lord Dunmore]], [[Dunmore's Proclamation|issued a proclamation]] that promised freedom to servants and slaves who were able to bear arms and join his Loyalist [[Ethiopian Regiment]]. Many of the slaves in the South joined the Loyalists with intentions of gaining freedom and escaping the South. About 800 did so; some helped rout the Virginia militia at the [[Battle of Kemp's Landing]] and fought in the [[Battle of Great Bridge]] on the [[Elizabeth River (Virginia)|Elizabeth River]], wearing the motto \"Liberty to Slaves\", but this time they were defeated. The remains of their regiment were then involved in the evacuation of [[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk]], after which they served in the [[Chesapeake, Virginia|Chesapeake]] area. Eventually the camp that they had set up there suffered an outbreak of smallpox and other diseases. This took a heavy toll, putting many of them out of action for some time. The survivors joined other British units and continued to serve throughout the war. Black colonials were often the first to come forward to volunteer and a total of 12,000 African Americans served with the British from 1775 to 1783. This forced the rebels to also offer freedom to those who would serve in the Continental Army; however, such promises were often reneged upon by both sides.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackloyalist.com/canadiandigitalcollection/story/revolution/philipsburg.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-10-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117055926/http://www.blackloyalist.com/canadiandigitalcollection/story/revolution/philipsburg.htm |archivedate=2007-11-17 }}</ref>\n\nAmericans who gained their freedom by fighting for the British became known as [[Black Loyalist|Black Loyalists]]. The British honored the pledge of freedom in New York City through the efforts of General [[Guy Carleton, 1st Baron Dorchester|Guy Carleton]], who recorded the names of African Americans who had supported the British in a document called the [[Book of Negroes]], which granted freedom to slaves who had escaped and assisted the British. About 4,000 Black Loyalists went to the British colonies of [[Nova Scotia]] and [[New Brunswick]], where the British promised them land. They founded communities across the two provinces, many of which still exist today. Over 2,500 settled in [[Birchtown, Nova Scotia]], instantly making it the largest [[Free Negro|free black]] community in North America. However, the inferior grants of land they were given and the prejudices of white Loyalists in nearby [[Shelburne, Nova Scotia|Shelburne]] who regularly harassed the settlement in events such as the [[Shelburne riots|Shelburne Riots]] in 1784, made life very difficult for the community.<ref name=\"blackloyalist.com\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20021110054520/http://www.blackloyalist.com/historypage2.html]</ref> In 1791 Britain's [[Sierra Leone Company]] offered to transport dissatisfied black Loyalists to the British colony of [[Sierra Leone]] in West Africa, with the promise of better land and more equality. About 1,200 left Nova Scotia for Sierra Leone, where they named the capital [[Freetown]].<ref name=\"blackloyalist.com\"/> After 1787 they became Sierra Leone's ruling elite.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}} About 400 to 1,000 free blacks who joined the British side in the Revolution went to London and joined the free black community of about 10,000 there.\n\n=== Loyalist women ===\nWhile men were out fighting for the crown, women served at home protecting their land and property.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Women's Narratives of the Early Americas and the Formation of Empire.|last=Tillman|first=Kacy Dowd|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2016|isbn=|location=New York City, NY|pages=142, 143|chapter=Women Left Behind: Female Loyalism, Coverture, and Grace Growden Galloway's Empire of Self|quote=|via=}}</ref> At the end of the war, many loyalist men left America for the shelter of England, leaving their wives and daughters to protect their land<ref name=\":0\" /> The main punishment for Loyalist families was the expropriation of property, but married women were protected under \"[[Coverture|feme covert]]\", which meant that they had no political identity and their legal rights were absorbed by their husbands.<ref name=\":0\" /> This created an awkward dilemma for the confiscation committees: confiscating the land of such a woman would punish her for her husband's actions.<ref name=\":0\" /> In fact, many women were punished in this way. [[Grace Growden Galloway]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baxter|first=Beverly|year=1978|title=Grace Growden Galloway|url=|journal=Frontiers: A Journal of Women Studies|volume=62|pages=|via=}}</ref> recorded the experience in her diary. Galloway's property was seized by the [[Rebels (American Revolution)|Rebels]] and she spent the rest of her life fighting to regain it.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was returned to her heirs in 1783, after she and her husband had died.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Loyalism in Canada and Nova Scotia===\n[[File:Tory Refugees by Howard Pyle.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Painting shows a woman on horseback, a man with a rifle and a boy fleeing town. In the distance, people are throwing rocks at them.|''Tory Refugees on their way to Canada'' by Howard Pyle]]\nRebel agents were active in [[Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)|Quebec]] (which was then frequently called \"Canada\", the name of the [[Canada (New France)|earlier French province]]) in the months leading to the outbreak of active hostilities. [[John Brown of Pittsfield|John Brown]], an agent of the [[Committees of correspondence|Boston Committee of Correspondence]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Aptheker |first=Herbert |title=The American Revolution, 1763\u20131783 |publisher=International Publishers Co |year=1960 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/americanrevoluti0000apth/page/169 169] |url=https://archive.org/details/americanrevoluti0000apth|url-access=registration |quote=  John Brown  Boston Committee of Correspondence. |isbn=0-7178-0005-9}}</ref> worked with Canadian merchant Thomas Walker and other rebel sympathisers during the winter of 1774\u20131775 to convince inhabitants to support the actions of the [[First Continental Congress]]. However, many of Quebec's inhabitants remained neutral, resisting service to either the British or the Americans.\n\nAlthough some Canadians took up arms in support of the rebellion, the majority remained loyal to the King. [[French Canadians]] had been satisfied by the British government's [[Quebec Act]] of 1774, which offered religious and linguistic toleration; in general, they did not sympathize with a rebellion that they saw as being led by Protestants from [[New England]], who were their commercial rivals and hereditary enemies. Most of the [[English language|English-speaking]] settlers had arrived following the British [[Conquest of 1760|conquest of Canada]] in 1759\u20131760, and were unlikely to support separation from Britain. The older British colonies, [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]] and [[Nova Scotia]] (including what is now [[New Brunswick]]) also remained loyal and contributed military forces in support of the Crown.\n\nIn late 1775 the [[Continental Army]] [[Invasion of Quebec (1775)|sent a force into Quebec]], led by General [[Richard Montgomery]] and Colonel [[Benedict Arnold]], with the goal of convincing the residents of Quebec to join the Revolution. Although only a minority of Canadians openly expressed loyalty to King George, about 1,500 militia fought for the King in the [[Siege of Fort St. Jean]]. In the region south of Montreal that was occupied by the Continentals, some inhabitants supported the rebellion and raised two regiments to join the Patriot forces.<ref name = \"Wade\">Mason Wade, ''The French Canadians'' (1955) 1:67\u20139.</ref>\n\nIn [[Nova Scotia]], there were many Yankee settlers originally from New England, and they generally supported the principles of the revolution. The allegiance toward the rebellion waned as American Privateers [[Nova Scotia in the American Revolution|raided Nova Scotia communities]] throughout the war. As well, the Nova Scotia government used the law to convict people for sedition and treason for supporting the rebel cause. There was also the influence of an influx of recent immigration from the British isles, and they remained neutral during the war, and the influx was greatest in Halifax.<ref>George Rawlyck, ''A People Highly Favoured Of God. The Nova Scotia Yankees. And the American Revolution'' (Toronto: 1972)</ref> Britain in any case built up powerful forces at the naval base of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] after the failure of [[Jonathan Eddy]] to [[Battle of Fort Cumberland|capture Fort Cumberland]] in 1776.<ref>Philip Buckner and John G Reid, eds. ''The Atlantic Region to Confederation: A History'' (1995) pp 168\u2013170</ref><ref>J.B. Brebner, ''The Neutral Yankees of Nova Scotia'' (1937)</ref> Although the Continentals captured [[Montreal]] in November 1775, they were [[Battle of Quebec (1775)|turned back]] a month later at [[Quebec City]] by a combination of the British military under Governor [[Guy Carleton, 1st Baron Dorchester|Guy Carleton]], the difficult terrain and weather, and an indifferent local response. The Continental forces would be driven from Quebec in 1776, after the breakup of ice on the St. Lawrence River and the arrival of British transports in May and June. There would be no further serious attempt to challenge British control of present-day Canada until the [[War of 1812]].\n\nIn 1777, 1,500 Loyalist militia took part in the [[Saratoga campaign]] in New York, and surrendered with General [[John Burgoyne|Burgoyne]] after the [[Battles of Saratoga]] in October.  For the rest of the war, Quebec acted as a base for raiding expeditions, conducted primarily by Loyalists and Indians, against frontier communities.\n\n===Military service===\n{{Main|Loyalists fighting in the American Revolution}}\n\nThe Loyalists rarely attempted any political organization. They were often passive unless regular British army units were in the area. The British, however, assumed a highly activist Loyalist community was ready to mobilize and planned much of their strategy around raising Loyalist regiments. The British provincial line, consisting of Americans enlisted on a regular army status, enrolled 19,000 Loyalists (50 units and 312 companies). The maximum strength of the Loyalist provincial line was 9,700 in December 1780.<ref>Smith 264\u20137.</ref><ref name=\"Calhoon502\">Calhoon 502.</ref> In all about 19,000 at one time or another were soldiers or militia in British forces.<ref>Smith, p 267</ref>  Loyalists from South Carolina fought for the British in the [[Battle of Camden]]. The British forces at the [[Battle of Monck's Corner]] and the [[Battle of Lenud's Ferry]] consisted entirely of Loyalists with the exception of the commanding officer ([[Banastre Tarleton]]).<ref>Wilson, David. ''The Southern Strategy'' (University of South Carolina Press. 2005.)</ref> Both white and black Loyalists fought for the British at the [[Battle of Kemp's Landing]] in Virginia.<ref>Selby, John E; Higginbotham, Don (2007)</ref>\n\n==Emigration from the United States==\n[[File:Shelburnewaterfront.jpg|right|thumb|[[Shelburne, Nova Scotia]], a major early destination of Loyalist refugees]]\n\nHistorian [[Maya Jasanoff]] estimated how many Loyalists departed the U.S. for British North America. She calculates 60,000 in total, including about 50,000 whites (Wallace Brown cites about 80,000 Loyalists in total permanently left the United States.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|last1=Brown|first1=Wallace|title=The American Farmer during the Revolution: Rebel or Loyalist?|journal=Agricultural History|date=1968|volume=42|issue=4|page=331}}</ref>).<ref>However Philip Ranlet estimates that only 20,000 adult white Loyalists went to Canada. \"How Many American Loyalists Left the United States?.\" ''Historian'' 76.2 (2014): 278-307.</ref> The majority of them \u2014 36,000 - to [[New Brunswick]] and [[Nova Scotia]], while about 6,600 went to Quebec and 2,000 to Prince Edward Island. 5,090 white Loyalists went to Florida, bringing along their slaves who numbered about 8,285 (421 whites and 2561 blacks returned to the States from Florida ).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Russell |first1=David Lee |title=The American Revolution in the Southern colonies |date=2000 |publisher=McFarland & Co |isbn=0-7864-0783-2 |page=317}}</ref>  When Florida was returned to Spain, however, very few Loyalists remained there.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> 6,000 whites went to Jamaica and other Caribbean islands notably the Bahamas. About 13,000 went to Britain (including 5,000 free blacks). The total is 60\u201362,000 whites. A precise figure cannot be known because the records were incomplete and not accurate, and small numbers continued to leave after 1783. The 50,000 or-so white departures represented about 10% of the Loyalists (at 20-25% of the white population).<ref>{{cite book|author=Maya Jasanoff|title=Liberty's Exiles: American Loyalists in the Revolutionary World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uGKsn09oVwQC&pg=PA357|year=2012|publisher=Random House |page=357|isbn=9781400075478}}</ref> Loyalists (especially soldiers and former officials) could choose evacuation. Loyalists whose roots were not yet deeply embedded in the United States were more likely to leave; older people who had familial bonds and had acquired friends, property, and a degree of social respectability were more likely to remain in the US.<ref>Lohrenz (1998)</ref> The vast majority of the half-million white Loyalists, about 20-25% of the total number of whites, remained in the U.S. Starting in the mid\u20131780s a small percentage of those who had left returned to the United States. The exiles amounted to about 2% of the total US population of 3 million at the end of the war in 1783.\n\nAfter 1783 some former Loyalists, especially Germans from Pennsylvania, emigrated to Canada to take advantage of the British government's offer of free land. Many departed the fledgling U.S. because they faced continuing hostility. In another migration-motivated mainly by economic rather than political reasons-<ref>''The Canadian Encyclopedia'', \"Loyalists\"; and ''Liberty's Exiles'', Maya Jasanoff, pp.&nbsp;206\u2013208.</ref> more than 20,000 and perhaps as many as 30,000 \"Late Loyalists\" arrived in Ontario in the 1790s attracted by [[John Graves Simcoe|Lieutenant-Governor Simcoe]]'s policy of land and low taxes, one-fifth those in the US and swearing an oath{{when|date=May 2019}} of allegiance to the King.\n\nThe 36,000 or so who went to Nova Scotia were not well-received by the 17,000 Nova Scotians, who were mostly descendants of New Englanders settled there before the Revolution.<ref>Neil MacKinnon, ''This Unfriendly Soil: The Loyalist Experience in Nova Scotia, 1783\u20131791'' (1989)</ref>  \"They [the Loyalists]\", Colonel Thomas Dundas wrote in 1786, \"have experienced every possible injury from the old inhabitants of Nova Scotia, who are even more disaffected towards the British Government than any of the new States ever were. This makes me much doubt their remaining long dependent.\"<ref>S.D. Clark, ''Movements of Political Protest in Canada, 1640\u20131840'' (1959), pp. 150\u201351</ref> In response, the colony of [[New Brunswick]], until 1784 part of Nova Scotia, was created for the 14,000 who had settled in those parts. Of the 46,000 who went to Canada, 10,000 went to Quebec, especially what is now modern-day [[Ontario]], the rest to Nova Scotia and PEI.\n\nRealizing the importance of some type of consideration, on November 9, 1789, [[Guy Carleton, 1st Baron Dorchester|Lord Dorchester]], the governor of Quebec, declared that it was his wish to \"put the mark of Honour upon the Families who had adhered to the Unity of the [[British Empire|Empire]].\" As a result of Dorchester's statement, the printed militia rolls carried the notation:\n\n<blockquote>Those Loyalists who have adhered to the Unity of the Empire, and joined the Royal Standard before the [[Treaty of Paris (1783)|Treaty of Separation]] in the year 1783, and all their Children and their Descendants by either sex, are to be distinguished by the following Capitals, affixed to their names: U.E. Alluding to their great principle The Unity of the Empire.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boudreau|first1=Claire|last2=Cogn\u00e9|first2=Daniel|last3=Vachon|first3=Auguste|title=Proceedings of the 22nd International Congress of Genealogical and Heraldic Sciences in Ottawa from August 18 to 23, 1996|date=1998|publisher=University of Ottawa Press|page=202}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe [[Post-nominal letters|postnominals]] \"U.E.\" are rarely seen today, but the influence of the Loyalists on the evolution of Canada remains. Their ties to Britain and/or their antipathy to the United States provided the strength needed to keep Canada independent and distinct in North America.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}} The Loyalists' basic distrust of [[republicanism]] and \"[[Ochlocracy|mob rule]]\" influenced [[Canadian Confederation|Canada's gradual path to independence]].{{citation needed|date=May 2011}} The new British North American provinces of [[Upper Canada]] (the forerunner of Ontario) and [[New Brunswick]] were founded as places of refuge for the United Empire Loyalists.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nIn an interesting historical twist [[Peter Matthews (rebel)|Peter Matthews]], a son of Loyalists, participated in the [[Upper Canada Rebellion]] which sought relief from oligarchic British colonial government and pursued American-style [[Republicanism]]. He was arrested, tried and executed in [[Toronto]], and later became heralded as a patriot to the movement which led to Canadian self governance.\n\nThe wealthiest and most prominent Loyalist exiles went to Great Britain to rebuild their careers; many received pensions. Many Southern Loyalists, taking along their slaves, went to the [[West Indies]], particularly to the [[Abaco Islands]] in the [[The Bahamas|Bahamas]].\n\nMany Loyalists brought their slaves with them to Canada (mostly to areas that later became [[Ontario]] and [[New Brunswick]]) where [[Slavery in Canada|slavery was legal]]. An imperial law in 1790 assured prospective immigrants to Canada that their slaves would remain their property.<ref>Patrick Bode, \"Upper Canada, 1793: Simcoe and the Slaves.\" ''Beaver'' 1993 73(3): 17\u201319</ref>\n\nThousands of [[Iroquois]] and other [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] were expelled from New York and other states and resettled in Canada. The descendants of one such group of Iroquois, led by [[Joseph Brant]] (Thayendenegea), settled at [[Six Nations of the Grand River]], the largest [[First Nations]] [[Indian reserve|reserve]] in Canada. (The remainder, under the leadership of [[Cornplanter]] (John Abeel) and members of his family, stayed in New York.) A group of African-American Loyalists settled in Nova Scotia but emigrated again for [[Sierra Leone]] after facing [[discrimination]] there.\n\nMany of the Loyalists were forced to abandon substantial properties to America restoration of or compensation for these lost properties was a major issue during the negotiation of the [[Jay Treaty]] in 1794. The British Government eventually settled several thousand claims for more than 3.5 million Pounds Sterling,{{citation needed|reason=Lead says 3.0 million; neither cites a reference|date=May 2019}} an enormous sum of money worth at that time.\n\n==Return of some expatriates==\nThe great majority of Loyalists never left the United States; they stayed on and were allowed to be citizens of the new country. Some became nationally prominent leaders, including [[Samuel Seabury]], who was the first Bishop of the Episcopal Church, and [[Tench Coxe]]. There was a small, but significant trickle of returnees who found life in Nova Scotia and New Brunswick too difficult. Perhaps 10% of the refugees to New Brunswick returned to the States as did an unknown number from Nova Scotia.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Christopher |title=The Loyalists : revolution, exile, settlement |date=1984 |publisher=McClelland & Stewart |isbn=978-0771060939 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/loyalists00chri/page/244 244\u2013252] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/loyalists00chri/page/244 }}</ref>  Some Massachusetts Tories settled in the Maine District. Nevertheless, the vast majority never returned. Captain Benjamin Hallowell, who as Mandamus Councilor in Massachusetts served as the direct representative of the Crown, was considered by the insurgents as one of the most hated men in the Colony, but as a token of compensation when he returned from England in 1796, his son was allowed to regain the family house.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jphs.org/colonial/capt-benjamin-hallowell-homestead.html|title=Jamaica Plain Historical Society - 'Colonial Era' Editor - - Capt Benjamin Hallowell Homestead|website=www.jphs.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080904235939/http://www.jphs.org/colonial/capt-benjamin-hallowell-homestead.html|archivedate=2008-09-04}}</ref>\n\n[[Alexander Hamilton]] enlisted the help of the Tories (ex-Loyalists) in New York in 1782\u201385 to forge an alliance with moderate Whigs to wrest the State from the power of the [[George Clinton (vice president)|Clinton]] faction. Moderate Whigs in other States who had not been in favor of separation from Britain but preferred a negotiated settlement which would have maintained ties to the Mother Country mobilized to block radicals. Most States had rescinded anti-Tory laws by 1787, although the accusation of being a Tory was heard for another generation. Several hundred who had left for Florida returned to Georgia in 1783\u201384. South Carolina which had seen a bitter bloody internal civil war in 1780-82 adopted a policy of reconciliation that proved more moderate than any other state. About 4500 white Loyalists left when the war ended, but the majority remained behind. The state government successfully and quickly reincorporated the vast majority. During the war, pardons were offered to Loyalists who switched sides and joined the Patriot forces. Others were required to pay a 10% fine of the value of the property.  The legislature named 232 Loyalists liable for confiscation of their property, but most appealed and were forgiven.<ref>Rebecca Brannon, ''From Revolution to Reunion: The Reintegration of the South Carolina Loyalists'' (Univ of South Carolina Press, 2016).</ref> In Connecticut much to the disgust of the Radical Whigs the moderate Whigs were advertising in New York newspapers in 1782-83 that Tories who would make no trouble would be welcome on the grounds that their skills and money would help the State's economy. The Moderates prevailed. All anti-Tory laws were repealed in early 1783 except for the law relating to confiscated Tory estates: \"... the problem of the loyalists after 1783 was resolved in their favor after the War of Independence ended.\" In 1787 the last of any discriminatory laws were rescinded.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Zeichner |first1=Oscar |title=The Rehabilitation of Loyalists in Connecticut |journal=The New England Quarterly |date=June 1938 |volume=11 |issue=2 |pages=308\u2013330|doi=10.2307/360711 |jstor=360711 }}</ref>\n\n==Impact of the departure of Loyalist leaders==\nThe departure of so many royal officials, rich merchants and landed gentry destroyed the hierarchical networks that had dominated most of the colonies.  A major result was that a Patriot/Whig elite supplanted royal officials and affluent Tories.<ref>The Forging of the New Nation, 1781-1789, Robert B. Morris, 1987, p. 163.</ref>  In New York, the departure of key members of the De Lancey, De Peyster, Walton and Cruger families undercut the interlocking families that largely owned and controlled the Hudson Valley.  Likewise in Pennsylvania, the departure of powerful families\u2014Penn, Allen, Chew, Shippen\u2014destroyed the cohesion of the old upper class there.  Massachusetts passed an act banishing forty-six Boston merchants in 1778, including members of some of Boston's wealthiest families.  The departure of families such as the Ervings, Winslows, Clarks, and Lloyds deprived Massachusetts of men who had hitherto been leaders of networks of family and clients. The bases of the men who replaced them were much different.  One rich Patriot in Boston noted in 1779 that \"fellows who would have cleaned my shoes five years ago, have amassed fortunes and are riding in chariots.\"  New men became rich merchants but they shared a spirit of republican equality that replaced the former elitism.<ref>{{cite book|author=Gordon S. Wood|title=The Radicalism of the American Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6lGinKwz7l8C&pg=PA177|year=1992|publisher=Random House |pages=176\u2013177|isbn=9780307758965}}</ref>\n\nThe Patriot reliance on Catholic France for military, financial and diplomatic aid led to a sharp drop in anti-Catholic rhetoric.  Indeed, the king replaced the pope as the demon Patriots had to fight against.  Anti-Catholicism remained strong among Loyalists, some of whom went to Canada after the war most remained in the new nation.  By the 1780s, Catholics were extended legal toleration in all of the New England states that previously had been so hostile. \"In the midst of war and crisis, New Englanders gave up not only their allegiance to Britain but one of their most dearly held prejudices.\"<ref>Francis Cogliano, ''No King, No Popery: Anti-Catholicism in Revolutionary New England'' (1995) pp 154-55, quote p 155. [https://www.questia.com/library/3763417/no-king-no-popery-anti-catholicism-in-revolutionary online]</ref>\n\n==Loyalists in art==\n* [[John Singleton Copley]] painted many prominent Loyalists and produced an oil-on-canvas depiction of a soldier wearing the uniform of the Royal Ethiopian Regiment (a regiment composed of black Loyalist soldiers) in ''[[The Death of Major Peirson, 6 January 1781|The Death of Major Pierson]]'' (1784).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atlanticportal.hil.unb.ca/acva/blackloyalists/en/context/gallery/copley.html|title=Black Loyalists in New Brunswick, 1783-1854: 'The Death of Major Peirson', John Singleton Copley|website=atlanticportal.hil.unb.ca}}</ref>\n* [[Benjamin West]] characterized the ethnic and economic diversity of the Loyalists in his ''Reception of the American Loyalists by Great Britain in the Year 1783''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toriesfightingfortheking.com/WhoTories.htm |title=Tories: Fighting for the King in America's First Civil War |first=Thomas |last=Allen |website=www.toriesfightingfortheking.com}}</ref> The original painting was lost, but a smaller version of it can be seen in the background of West's portrait of John Eardley Wilmot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atlanticportal.hil.unb.ca/acva/blackloyalists/en/context/gallery/wilmot.html|title=Black Loyalists in New Brunswick, 1783-1854: 'John Eardley Wilmot' by Benjamin West|website=atlanticportal.hil.unb.ca}}</ref>\n* [[Gilbert Stuart]] painted a portrait of [[James De Lancey|James DeLancey]] around 1785. It stays in the collection of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], a bequest of his descendant George DeLancey Harris, Jr. of New York City & [[Annapolis Royal|Annapolis Royal, NS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/19826|title=Gilbert Stuart - James DeLancey|website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:John Singleton Copley 001.jpg|John Copley's \"The Death of Major Pierson\"\nFile:Benjamin West - John Eardley Wilmot - Google Art Project.jpg|Benjamin West's \"John Eardley Wilmot\"\n</gallery>\n\n==Loyalists in literature==\n{{See also|:Category:American Revolutionary War novels}}\n* ''The Adventures of Jonathan Corncob, Loyal American Refugee'' (1787) by Jonathan Corncob. According to Maya Jasanoff, \"traveling to London to file a claim served as the opening gambit\" for this \"[[picaresque novel]] about the American Revolution\".<ref>Maya Jasanoff (2011), p, 386, n. 67.</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=18Et4ZikXLMC&pg=PA427&lpg=PA427&dq=the+adventures+of+jonathan+corncob#v=onepage&q=the+adventures+of+jonathan+corncob&f=false|title=Revolution and the Word: The Rise of the Novel in America|first=Cathy N.|last=Davidson|date=30 September 2004|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|via=Google Books|isbn=9780195177718}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=fO9zG7ILq10C&pg=PR10&lpg=PR10&dq=the+adventures+of+jonathan+corncob+phd#v=onepage&q=the+adventures+of+jonathan+corncob+phd&f=false|title=A Reader's Delight|first=Noel|last=Perrin|date=8 June 1988|publisher=UPNE|via=Google Books|isbn=9780874514322}}</ref>\n* \"[[Rip Van Winkle]]\" (1819), short story by [[Washington Irving]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enotes.com/rip-van-winkle-reference/rip-van-winkle|title=Rip Van Winkle Summary - eNotes.com|website=eNotes}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Spy (Cooper novel)|The Spy: a Tale of the Neutral Ground]]'' (1821), novel by [[James Fenimore Cooper]]\n* ''Oliver Wiswell'' (1940), a novel by [[Kenneth Roberts (author)|Kenneth Roberts]]\n* ''[[The Book of Negroes (novel)|The Book of Negroes]]'' (2007) by [[Lawrence Hill]]\n* ''[[The Fort (novel)|The Fort]]'' (2010), novel by [[Bernard Cornwell]]\n* {{cite book | first=Wendy| last=Long Stanley | year=2019 | title=The Power to Deny: A Woman of the Revolution Novel | publisher=Carmenta Publishing | isbn=978-1-951747-00-8 }} Well received historical fiction account of the life of Elizabeth Graeme Fergusson\n\n==Notable Loyalists==\n{{div col|colwidth=50em}}\n\n===A===\n* [[Samuel Adams (Loyalist)|Samuel Adams]] (1730\u20131810), Vermont physician; not related to [[Samuel Adams]], the Patriot leader in Boston\n* [[John Agnew (New Brunswick politician)|Rev. John Agnew]] (d. 1812, New Brunswick), served a [[Church of England]] parish in Suffolk, Virginia<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 154\u2013155.</ref>\n* [[Andrew Allen (Pennsylvania)|Andrew Allen]] (1740\u20131825), Pennsylvanian Delegate to the [[Second Continental Congress]]\n* [[William Allen (loyalist)|William Allen]] (1704\u20131780), Chief Justice of [[Province of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]] and former mayor of [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]]<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 157\u2013158.</ref>\n* [[Brigadier General]] [[Benedict Arnold]] (January 14, 1741 [O.S. January 3, 1740/1741] \u2013 June 14, 1801), commissioned in 1780; originally a Patriot general\n* [[John Askin]] (1739\u20131815), trader and land speculator at [[Detroit]]\n\n===B===\n* [[John Bacon (Loyalist)|John Bacon]] (died 1783), New Jersey privateer and marauder who preyed on Patriots in and around the [[Pine Barrens (New Jersey)|Pine Barrens]] and South East New Jersey \n* [[Thomas Henry Barclay]] (1753\u20131830), New York City lawyer and later Governor of Nova Scotia\n* [[Richard Bayley|Dr. Richard Bayley]] (1745\u20131801), New York physician and father of American-born saint [[Elizabeth Ann Seton]]\n* [[John Beardsley|Rev. John Beardsley]] (1732\u20131809), [[Church of England|Anglican]] minister in [[Poughkeepsie, New York]] and [[Fishkill, New York]] who, in 1778, he served as chaplain to [[Beverley Robinson|Beverley Robinson's]] [[Loyal American Regiment]]<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 222-223.</ref>\n* [[Joseph Bettys]], resident of the Town of [[Ballston, New York]]; hanged as a spy in 1782<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stone|first1=William Leete|title=Life of Joseph Brant, Thayendanegea|date=1838|publisher=George Dearborn & Co.|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/lifeofjosephbran01lcston/page/210 210]\u2013\u2013214|url=https://archive.org/details/lifeofjosephbran01lcston|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Christopher Billopp]] ({{circa}}1738 \u2013 March 29, 1827), [[Staten Island]] resident who commanded a Tory detachment \n* [[Sampson Salter Blowers]] (March 10, 1742 \u2013 October 25, 1842), Boston, Massachusetts attorney\n* [[Amos Botsford]] (1744\u20131812), [[Yale College]] graduate and judge\n* [[Jonathan Boucher]] (1738\u20131804), [[Church of England]] priest in [[Maryland]] and [[Virginia]] and tutor to [[John Parke Custis]], the stepson of [[George Washington]]<ref>Anne Y. Zimmer. ''Jonathan Boucher, loyalist in exile''. Detroit, MI: Wayne State University Press, 1978.</ref><ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 240\u2013241.</ref>\n* [[William Augustus Bowles]] (1763\u20131805), also known as Estajoca, served with the [[Maryland Loyalist Battalion]] and was a Maryland-born English adventurer and organizer of Native American attempts to create their own state outside of Euro-American control.<ref>Maya Jasanoff (2011), pp. xiv\u2013xv,234\u2013242, 321\u2013323, 348.</ref><ref>J. Leitch Wright. ''William Augusutus Bowles: Director General of the Creek Nation''. Athens, GA: University of Georgia Press, 1967.</ref><ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, p. 245-246.</ref>\n* [[Joseph Brant|Joseph Brant Thayendenegea]] (1743\u20131807), Mohawk war leader\n* [[Molly Brant]] ({{circa}}1736\u20131796), also known as Mary Brant, Konwatsi'tsiaienni, and Degonwadonti; influential Mohawk leader and sister of Joseph Brant\n* [[Elisabeth Brewer]] served as a nurse in the Continental Army while covertly gathering information for the British in New Jersey\n* [[Thomas Brown (loyalist)|Thomas Brown]] (1750\u20131825), LTC commanding King's Rangers in Georgia<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 260\u2013265.</ref>\n* [[Brigadier General]] [[Montfort Browne]] ([[floruit|fl.]] 1760\u20131780), commanding Prince of Wales American Regiment, 1777\n* [[William Bull II]] (1710\u20131791), lieutenant governor of the province of South Carolina, 1759\u20131775\n* [[Colonel]] [[John Butler (pioneer)|John Butler]] (1728\u20131796), commanded [[Butler's Rangers]] in the Mohawk Valley<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 278\u2013280.</ref>\n* [[Walter Butler (Loyalist)|Walter Butler]] (1752\u20131781), Captain in Butler's Rangers; son of John Butler<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, p. 280.</ref>\n* [[Mather Byles|Rev. Mather Byles]] (1706\u20131788), [[Harvard University|Harvard]] graduate and prominent Boston clergyman\n\n===C===\n* [[William Caldwell (ranger)|William Caldwell]] (c. 1750\u20131822), Scots-Irish who served in [[Butler's Rangers]] \n* [[Benedict Swingate Calvert]] ({{circa}}1730 to 1732\u20131788), Judge of the Land Office, Maryland\n* [[Elizabeth Calvert]] (1731 \u2013 1788), wife and cousin of Loyalist politician Benedict Swingate Calvert\n* [[John Camm|Rev. John Camm]] (1718\u20131778), seventh president of the [[College of William and Mary]]\n* [[Lt. Col. James Chalmers]] (d. 1806), Commander, First Battalion of Maryland Loyalists; author of anti-\"[[Common Sense (pamphlet)|Common Sense]]\" pamphlet \"Plain Truth\" in 1776<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, p. 301.</ref>\n* Dr. [[Benjamin Church (physician)|Benjamin Church]] (1734\u2013disappeared at sea 1778), Director Medical General Patriot Army and a Loyalist spy\n* [[Richard Clarke (merchant)|Richard Clarke]] (1711\u20131795), Boston merchant\n* [[Daniel Claus|Christian Daniel Claus]] (1727\u20131787), commissioner of Indian affairs \n* [[Cheney Clow]] (1734\u20131788), Delaware plantation owner; served earlier as a British officer; involved in an act of hostility on April 18, 1778 which is known today as Cheney Clow's Rebellion\n* [[Sir Isaac Coffin, 1st Baronet]] (1759\u20131839), Royal Navy officer and member of a prominent Massachusetts Loyalist family\n* [[John Connolly (loyalist)|John Connolly]] ({{circa}}1741\u20131813), planned with Lord Dunmore to raise a regiment of Loyalists and Indians in Canada called the Loyal Foresters and lead them to Virginia to help Dunmore put down the rebellion\n* [[Myles Cooper]] (1735\u20131785), [[Church of England]] clergyman President of King's College in New York City<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, p. 335.</ref>\n* [[John Singleton Copley]] (1738\u20131815), innovative painter\n* [[Bloody Bill Cunningham|William Cunningham]] (d. 1787, [[Nassau, Bahamas]]), earned the name \u2033Bloody Bill\u2033 for his exploits against Backcountry South Carolina Patriots<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, p. 348-349.</ref>\n\n===D===\n* [[James De Lancey (loyalist)|James De Lancey]] (1746\u20131804), of [[Westchester County, New York]], led a Loyalist unit known as \"De Lancey's Cowboys\" and was known as the \"Outlaw of the Bronx\"\n* [[Oliver De Lancey (American loyalist)|Brigadier General Oliver De Lancey]] (1718\u20131785), commanded De Lancey's Brigade 1776<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 363\u2013366.</ref>\n* [[Stephen De Lancey]] (1738\u20131809), Loyalist lawyer and political figure in New York state and Nova Scotia\n* [[Abraham de Peyster (captain)|Abraham de Peyster]], Officer of King's American Regiment<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 372\u2013374.</ref>\n* [[Colonel]] [[Arent DePeyster]] (1736\u20131822), Officer of the 8th Regiment of Foot\n* [[Colonel]] [[Andrew Deveaux]] (1758\u20131812), Colonel in South Carolina Loyalist militia<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 377\u2013378.</ref>\n* [[Doan Outlaws]], fallen Pennsylvania [[Quaker]] family of British [[espionage|spies]] and [[banditry|bandits]]<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 381\u2013383.</ref>\n* [[Margaret Green Draper]] (1727\u2013{{circa}}1804), Boston printer and journalist; one of the first American women to run an independent business; [[United Empire Loyalist]]; supported the British\n\n===E===\n* [[Sir Robert Eden, 1st Baronet, of Maryland]] ({{circa}}1741\u20131784), [[List of colonial governors of Maryland|Provincial Governor of Maryland]] and last Royal Governor of Maryland<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, p. 402.</ref>\n* [[Jacob Ellegood]] (1742\u20131801), Virginia-born farmer who became a political figure in early [[New Brunswick]]\n\n===F===\n* [[Thomas Fairfax, 6th Lord Fairfax of Cameron]] (1693\u20131781), of Virginia; the only British [[peerage|peer]] resident in Colonial America<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 408\u2013412.</ref>\n* [[David Fanning (loyalist)|David Fanning]] (1755\u20131825), commander of militia in [[North Carolina]], and later Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]], 1791\u20131801\n* [[Edmund Fanning (colonial administrator)|Edmund Fanning]] (1739\u20131818), commanded militia in the [[War of the Regulation]] and Loyalist militia in the [[American Revolution]]; later Lieutenant Governor of [[Nova Scotia]] and [[Prince Edward Island|Saint John's Island]]<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 417\u2013418.</ref>\n* [[David Farnsworth]] (d. 1778), British agent hanged for his participation in a plot to undermine the American economy by distributing counterfeit currency\n* [[Elizabeth Graeme Fergusson]], Loyalist who wrote poems lamenting her husband's desertion of her; these shared the grief of herself and other women left behind\n* [[William Franklin]] ({{circa}}1730\u20131813), [[Governor of New Jersey]]; son of [[Benjamin Franklin]]\n* [[Rebecca Franks]] (1760\u20131823), prominent member of Loyalist society in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania during the American Revolution\n\n===G===\n* [[Grace Growden Galloway]] (1727\u20131783), Loyalist who documented her fight for property rights\n* [[Joseph Galloway]] (1731\u20131803), Member of the [[Pennsylvania Provincial Assembly]]<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 453\u2013457.</ref>\n* [[Alexander Garden (naturalist)|Alexander Garden]] (1720\u20131791), Scottish-born naturalist who lived in Charles Town, South Carolina until fleeing to London in 1783\n*  Dr. [[Silvester Gardiner]] (1708\u20131786), Massachusetts physician, visionary land developer; in 1774 added his name to a letter addressed to Massachusetts Royal Governor Thomas Hutchinson, affirming his allegiance to the Loyalist cause\n* [[David George (Baptist)|David George]] ({{circa}}1743\u20131810), African-American Baptist preacher and a Black Loyalist from the American South who escaped to British lines in [[Savannah, Georgia]]; later accepted transport to Nova Scotia and land there; eventually resettled in [[Freetown, Sierra Leone]]\n* [[Abraham Gesner (politician)|Abraham Gesner]] (1756\u20131851), served with the King's Orange Rangers during the American Revolution; purchased a commission of major in the British Army\n* [[Simon Girty]] (1741\u20131818), British liaison with the Indians\n* [[John Goodrich (Loyalist)|John Goodrich]] (1722-1785), Loyalist privateer\n* [[Harrison Gray (Treasurer)|Harrison Gray]] (1711\u20131794), wealthy merchant; Treasurer and Receiver-General for the Province of Massachusetts Bay\n\n===H===\n* [[John Hamilton (American Revolution)|John Hamilton]] (died 1816), commander of the Royal North Carolina Regiment, later British consul in Norfolk, Virginia<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, p. 511-512.</ref>\n* [[Harpe brothers]], North Carolina [[banditry|bandits]] and allegedly America's first [[serial killer]]s\n* [[John Howe (loyalist)|John Howe]] (1754\u20131835), printer of the Massachusetts ''Gazette'' and Boston ''Weekly News-Letter''<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 548\u2013550.</ref>\n* [[Thomas Hutchinson (governor)|Thomas Hutchinson]] (1711\u20131780), last royal [[Governor of Massachusetts]]\n\n===I===\n* [[Charles Inglis (bishop)|Charles Inglis]] (1734\u20131816), first Bishop of the Anglican [[Diocese of Nova Scotia and Prince Edward Island|Diocese of Nova Scotia]]<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, pp. 563-565.</ref>\n* [[Ralph Inman]] (1713\u20131788), Boston, Massachusetts merchant<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 1, p. 566.</ref>\n\n===J===\n* [[Samuel Jarvis (American)|Samuel Jarvis]] (1720\u20131780), [[Stamford, Connecticut]] official forced out of office due to his Loyalism; father of William Jarvis\n* [[William Jarvis (Upper Canada official)|William Jarvis]] (1756\u20131817), New Yorker who served in the [[Queen's Rangers]]\n* [[Edward Jessup]] (1735\u20131816), Colonel of Jessup's [[Loyal Rangers]] near Albany, New York; and his brothers Ebenezer and Joseph\n* [[Sir John Johnson]] (1741\u20131820), commander of the [[King's Royal Regiment of New York]]\n* [[Thomas Jones (historian)|Thomas Jones]] (1731\u20131792), [[Recorder of New York City]], 1769\u20131773; historian who authored ''History of New York During the Revolutionary War and of the Leading Events in the Other Colonies at That Period''; fled to Britain and died in [[Hoddesdon|Hoddesdon, Hertfordshire]]\n\n===K===\n* [[Boston King]] ({{circa}}1760\u20131802), [[Black Loyalist]]; settled in [[Nova Scotia]] and later [[emigrated]] to [[Sierra Leone]], where he helped found [[Freetown]] and became the first [[Methodist]] [[missionary]] to African indigenous people\n\n===L===\n* [[Elisha Leavitt]] (1714\u20131790), [[Hingham, Massachusetts]] merchant and landowner\n* [[Sir Egerton Leigh, 1st Baronet]] (1733\u20131781), South Carolina colonial official<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 2, p. 9\u201310.</ref>\n* [[Daniel Leonard]] (1740\u20131829), son of a [[Taunton, Massachusetts]] Patriot; later served as the Chief Justice of the Bermudas<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 2, pp. 10\u201312.</ref> \n* [[Isaac Low]] (1735\u20131791), delegate for New York to the [[First Continental Congress]] in 1774 and to [[New York Provincial Congress]]; first President of the New York Chamber of Commerce<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 2, pp. 32\u201333.</ref>\n* [[George Duncan Ludlow|George Ludlow]], New York judge\n\n===M===\n* [[David Mathews]], [[Princeton University]] graduate and [[Mayor of New York City]]; subsequent administrator of [[Cape Breton Island|Cape Breton]], Nova Scotia\n* [[William McCormick (businessman)|William McCormick]] (1742\u20131815), North Carolina merchant<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 2, p. 55.</ref>\n* [[Colonel]] [[Alexander McKee]] (''ca''. 1735\u20131799), liaison between the British and the Shawnees\n* [[Benjamin Milliken]], founder of Ellsworth Maine, mill and ship owner \n* [[James Moody (loyalist)|James Moody]], Lieutenant, First New Jersey Volunteers, March 1781<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blupete.com/Hist/BiosNS/1800-67/List.htm#M|title=Historical Biographies, Nova Scotia, 1800-1867.|website=www.blupete.com}}</ref>\n* [[John Murray (Massachusetts)|John Murray]], Representative to the Great and General Court of the Province of Massachusetts Bay\n\n===O===\n* Rev. [[Jonathan Odell]] (1737\u20131818), New Jersey Anglican clergyman and Loyalist poet\n* [[Peter Oliver (loyalist)|Peter Oliver]](1713\u20131791), Massachusetts judge briefly satirized in \"[[McFingal]]\"<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 2, p. 128-129.</ref>\n\n===P===\n* [[Richard Pearis]] (1725\u20131794), [[Indian trader]] and pioneer settler of [[Upstate South Carolina]]\n* [[Frederick Philipse III]] (1720\u20131786), militia colonel and politician in New York; last lord of [[Philipsburg Manor]]\n\n===R===\n* [[John Randolph (Williamsburg)|John Randolph]] (1727\u20131784), King's Attorney for [[Province of Virginia|Virginia]]<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 2, pp. 208\u2013209.</ref>\n* [[James Rivington]] (1734\u20131802), Loyalist editor of ''Rivington Gazette''; Patriot spy\n* Colonel [[Beverley Robinson]] (1723\u20131792), of New York, [[Loyal American Regiment]]<ref>Maya Jasanoff (2011), pp. xi, 34\u201336, 93\u201394, 123\u2013125, 131, 134, 143, 313.</ref><ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 2, pp. 221\u2013225.</ref>\n* [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] [[Robert Rogers (soldier)|Robert Rogers]] (1731\u20131795), commander of [[Rogers' Rangers]]/[[Queen's Rangers]] to 1777 (now [[The Queen's York Rangers (1st American Regiment) (RCAC)]]), innovator of [[Rangers Standing Orders|ranging tactics]]\n* [[Timothy Ruggles]] (1711\u20131795), colonial military leader, Massachusetts jurist and politician, who served as president of the 1765 [[Stamp Act Congress]]\n\n===S===\n* [[Peggy Shippen]] (1760\u20131804), Philadelphia socialite and second wife of [[Benedict Arnold]]\n* [[John Graves Simcoe]] (1752\u20131806), commander of [[Queen's Rangers]] from 1777 (now [[The Queen's York Rangers (1st American Regiment) (RCAC)]]); founding [[Lieutenant Governor of Upper Canada]] (today the Province of Ontario, Canada)\n* [[Philip Skene]] (1725\u20131810), colonial New York \"[[patroon]]\" and British officer, of Scottish birth\n* Brigadier [[Cortlandt Skinner]] (1727\u20131799), commanded New Jersey Volunteers, September 4, 1776\n* [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] [[William Stark (loyalist)|William Stark]] (1724\u20131776), of New Hampshire; brother of [[John Stark]], a [[major general]] in the [[Continental Army]]\n* [[George H. Steuart (planter)|George H. Steuart]] (1700\u20131784), planter; Judge of the Land Office, Maryland\n* [[Joel Stone]] (1749\u20131833), Connecticut merchant who helped Loyalists escape to British-controlled part of the Colonies, including [[David Mathews]]\n\n===T===\n* [[Benjamin Thompson|Sir Benjamin Thompson]] (Count Rumford) (1753\u20131814), of Massachusetts, Royal official and scientist, established the [[Royal Institution]] in England.<ref>Bradley 1974</ref>\n* [[Consider Tiffany]] (1732\u20131796), Connecticut storekeeper and sergeant during the French and Indian War<ref>Connecticut Births and Christenings 1649-1906. Consider Tiffany, 15 Mar 1732; citing; FHL microfilm.</ref> \n* [[William Tryon]] (1729\u20131788), Royal Governor of North Carolina<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 2, pp. 364\u2013366.</ref>\n\n===V===\n* [[Peter van Schaack]] (1747\u20131832), New York lawyer\n* [[John Vardill]] (1749\u20131811), New York City-born British spy, clergyman, educator, pamphleteer, playwright, and poet\n\n===W===\n* [[Sir John Wentworth, 1st Baronet]] (1737\u20131820), last Royal Governor of New Hampshire at the time of the American Revolution; Lieutenant-Governor of Nova Scotia<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 2, pp. 410\u2013413.</ref>\n* [[Charles Woodmason]] ({{circa}}1720\u20131789), [[Church of England]] missionary in [[South Carolina]], [[Virginia]], and [[Maryland]], diarist, poet, and corresponding member of the [[Royal Society of Arts]], [[London]].<ref>Richard J. Hooker, ed. ''The Carolina Backcountry on the Eve of the Revolution: The Journal and Other Writings of Charles Woodmason, Anglican Itinerant''. 1953.</ref><ref>Joseph R. Gainey. \"Rev. Charles Woodmason (''c''. 1720\u20131789): Author, Loyalist, Missionary, and Psalmodist.\" ''West Gallery: The Newsletter of the West Gallery Music Association'', Issue No. 59 (Autumn 2011), pp.&nbsp;18\u201325.</ref> He authored an article published (under the pseudonym \"Sylvanus\") in the ''South Carolina Gazette and Country-Journal'' on March 28, 1769 chiding the local Patriot leaders for hypocrisy and asked pointedly how they could justly complain of \"No taxation without representation!\" regarding Acts of Parliament, while these very same powerful men denied the Carolina Backcountry any representation in South Carolina's Assembly, yet expected them to pay taxes passed by that body.<ref>''South Carolina Gazette and Country-Journal'' in the March 28, 1769 issue (much abridged and heavily edited). The complete text is in Hooker, pp. 260\u2013263.</ref>\n* [[James Wright (governor)|James Wright]] (1716\u20131785), last Royal Governor of Georgia, buried in [[Westminster Abbey]]\n\n===X, Y, Z===\n* [[John Joachim Zubly]] (1724\u20131781), [[Calvinism|Reformed]] minister and delegate from Georgia to the [[Continental Congress]]<ref>Sabine (1864), Vol. 2, pp. 466\u2013468.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Military history of Nova Scotia#American Revolution|American Revolution - Nova Scotia theatre]]\n* [[:Category:Loyalists in the American Revolution|Loyalists in the American Revolution]]\n* [[Expulsion of the Loyalists]]\n* [[List of places named for Loyalists (American Revolution)]]\n* [[Frederick Haldimand]] (1718\u20131791) while serving in Canada amassed a huge [https://archive.is/20130628045904/http://collectionscanada.gc.ca/pam_archives/index.php?fuseaction=genitem.displayItem&lang=eng&rec_nbr=105513 collection] filling 115 microfilm reels of documents, letters, etc. reflecting the Loyalist experience in Canada.  A [https://archive.is/20130628065452/http://db.archives.queensu.ca/dbtw-wpd/exec/dbtwpub.dll?AC=GET_RECORD&XC=/dbtw-wpd/exec/dbtwpub.dll&BU=http://db.archives.queensu.ca/dbtw-wpd/fondsdb/query-fonds.html&TN=fonds&SN=AUTO6470&SE=950&RN=0&MR=20&TR=0&TX=1000&ES=0&CS=2&XP=&RF=Fonds+Results&EF=&DF=HTML+-+Fonds+Display&RL=1&EL=1&DL=1&NP=3&ID=&MF=&MQ=&TI=0&DT=&ST=0&IR=7418&NR=0&NB=0&SV=0&BG=ffffff&FG=000080&QS=query&OEX=ISO-8859-1&OEH=ISO-8859-1 partial finding aid] to this collection may be found on the Queens University Archives website.\n* [[Godfrey\u2013Milliken Bill]], proposed Canadian law demanding compensation from the U.S. for Loyalist claims after U.S. independence.\n* [[Lorenzo Sabine]] (1803\u20131877), early historian and chronicler of the Loyalist experience\n* ''[[Martin v. Hunter's Lessee]]''\n* [[Maryland Loyalists Battalion]]\n* [[Tory]]\n* [[Treaty of Paris (1783)]]\n* [[United Empire Loyalist]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Thomas B. Allen (author)|Allen, Thomas B.]] ''Tories: Fighting for the King in America's First Civil War.'' New York: HarperCollins, 2010. 496 pp. {{ISBN|9780061241819}}\n* Andrews, Matthew Page, ''History of Maryland'', Doubleday, New York (1929)\n* [[Bernard Bailyn|Bailyn, Bernard]]. ''The Ideological Origins of the American Revolution'' (2nd ed. 1992) pp 230\u2013319.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014. ''The Ordeal of Thomas Hutchinson: Loyalism and the Destruction of the First British Empire'' (1974), full scale biography of the most prominent Loyalist\n* Brown, Wallace. ''The King's Friends: The Composition and Motives of the American Loyalist Claimants'' (1966).\n* Calhoon, Robert M. \"Loyalism and neutrality\" in Jack P. Greene and J.R. Pole, eds., ''The Blackwell Encyclopedia of the American Revolution''  (1991); reprinted in {{cite book|last1=Greene|first1=Jack P.|last2=Pole|first2=J. R.|title=A Companion to the American Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xK1NuzpAcH8C&pg=PA235|year=2008|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|pages=235\u201347|isbn=9780470756447}}\n* Calhoon, Robert M. ''The Loyalists in Revolutionary America, 1760\u20131781'' (1973), the most detailed scholarly study\n* Calhoon, Robert M., Timothy M. Barnes and George A. Rawlyk, eds. ''Loyalists and Community in North America''  (1994).\n* Chopra, Ruma. \"Enduring Patterns of Loyalist Study: Definitions and Contours\" ''History Compass'' (2013) 11#11 pp 983\u2013993, DOI: 10.1111/hic3.12105\n* Chopra, Ruma. ''Choosing Sides: Loyalists in Revolutionary America'' (2015)\n* Dor\u00e9, Gilbert. \"Why The Loyalists Lost,\" ''Early America Review'' (Winter 2000) [http://www.earlyamerica.com/review/winter2000/loyalists.html online]\n* Frazer, Gregg L. ''God Against the Revolution: The Loyalist Clergy's Case against the American Revolution'' Lawrence, KS: University Press of Kansas, 2018.\n* [[Maya Jasanoff|Jasanoff, Maya]]. ''Liberty's Exiles: American Loyalists in the Revolutionary World''  (2011), excellent comprehensive treatment and winner of the 2011 [[National Book Critics Circle Award]] for Non-Fiction and 2012 [[George Washington Book Prize]]\n* [[Merrill Jensen|Jensen, Merrill]]. ''The New Nation: A History of the United States during the Confederation, 1781\u20131789'' 1950; detailed discussion of return of Loyalists, popular anger at their return; repeal of wartime laws against them\n* Kermes, Stephanie. \"'I Wish for Nothing 