{"title_page": "Nimbuzz", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox software\n| logo = Nimbuzz logo.png\n| logo size = 150px\n| name = Nimbuzz\n| developer = Nimbuzz B.V.<br>\nMSM Global Holdings Limited\n| released = 13 May 2008<ref name=\"launched\">{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz's All-in-One Mobile IM & VoIP App |newspaper=gigaom.com \n|date=13 May 2008 |url=http://gigaom.com/2008/05/13/nimbuzz-launches-symbian-client-for-mobile-smsimvoip/ \n|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref>\n| discontinued = Yes\n| latest release date = discontinued\n| operating system = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[BlackBerry OS]], [[Symbian]], [[Windows Phone]], [[Java Platform, Micro Edition|Java ME]], [[Windows]], and [[Mac OS]].\n| language = English, Spanish, French, German, Italian, Dutch, Portuguese, Russian, Hindi, Arabic and more.<ref name=\"languages\">{{cite news |title=Windows Phone 8 \u2013 Now Connected! |newspaper=Nimbuzz blog |date=3 April 2013 |url=http://blog.nimbuzz.com/2013/04/03/windows-phone-8-now-connected/ |accessdate=31 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407172428/http://blog.nimbuzz.com/2013/04/03/windows-phone-8-now-connected/ |archive-date=7 April 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| genre = Instant Messaging Client & VoIP\n| licence = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]]\n| website = {{URL|www.nimbuzz.com/en/}}\n}}\n\n'''Nimbuzz''' is a [[Proprietary software|proprietary]] [[cross-platform]] [[instant messaging]] aggregator for [[smartphone]]s, [[tablet computer|tablets]] and [[personal computer]]s developed by MSM Global Holdings Limited, with the origins of its technology dating back to the early 2000s. As of March 2013, Nimbuzz had 150 million users in 200 countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz reaches 150 million users |newspaper=Telecompaper.com |date=15 March 2013 |url=http://www.telecompaper.com/news/nimbuzz-reaches-150-million-users--931519 |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> By April 2014, Nimbuzz was growing by more than 210,000 new registrations per day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/in/2014/04/24/nimbuzz-targets-skype-with-deal-to-pre-install-its-app-on-lg-devices-with-100-minutes-of-free-calls/|title=Nimbuzz targets Skype with deal to pre-install its app on LG devices, with 100 minutes of free calls|last1=Russell|first1=Jon|date=24 April 2014|work=TheNextWeb|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref> In October 2014, now with over 200 million users, New Call acquired 70% of Nimbuzz, valuing the business at $250 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2014/10/28/big-in-india-messaging-app-nimbuzz-goes-to-uks-new-call-in-250m-deal/|title=Messaging App Nimbuzz Goes To UK\u2019s New Call In $250M Deal|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref> Under CEO Anubhav Nagar's leadership from March 2015,<ref>{{Cite press release|url=http://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2017/03/24/943899/0/en/Mara-Social-Media-Acquires-Global-Instant-Messaging-Communications-Platform-Nimbuzz.html|title=Mara Social Media Acquires Global Instant Messaging & Communications Platform \u201cNimbuzz\u201d|first=Mara Group Holdings|last=Limited|date=24 March 2017|website=GlobeNewswire News Room}}</ref> the Nimbuzz suite of applications enables users to enjoy [[free calls]], [[instant messaging]], [[social-network games]], [[file sharing]], and [[social networking]] on their mobile device. In addition, Nimbuzz offers discounted calling rates to most countries in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/in/2013/10/22/nimbuzz-launches-low-cost-international-calling-in-india-aiming-to-disrupt-a-1-5-billion-industry/|title=Nimbuzz Launches Low-Cost International Calls in India|first=Jon|last=Russell|date=22 October 2013|website=The Next Web}}</ref> Nimbuzz site and servers went offline in 2019, and as at February 2020, remain unavailable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nimbuzz.com|title=Nimbuzz Homepage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090320111712/http://www.nimbuzz.com/|archive-date=20 March 2009|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Company history and background==\nAdopting the Nimbuzz brand from 2004 onwards, the company entered the mainstream VoIP market in January 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title=No Buzz for Nimbuzz |url=http://gigaom.com/2007/01/16/no-buzz-for-nimbuzz/ |accessdate=31 May 2013 |newspaper=gigaom.com |date=16 January 2007}}</ref> In May 2008, the company launched its combined [[Voice over IP|Voice-over-Internet Protocol]] (VoIP) and instant messaging client.<ref name=\"launched\" /> In January 2009, the company was selected as one of 100 winners of the [[Red Herring (magazine)|Red Herring]] Global 100 technology industry awards for 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz in Red Herring top 100 |language=Dutch |newspaper=Emerce |location=The Netherlands |date=21 January 2009 |url=http://www.emerce.nl/nieuws/nimbuzz-in-red-herring-top-100 |accessdate=2 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz awarded Red Herring 100 |newspaper=Techwatch |date=23 January 2009 |url=http://www.techwatch.co.uk/2009/01/23/nimbuzz-awarded-red-herring-100/ |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nEarly stage investors over three rounds between December 2005 and July 2008 included [[Skype]]- and [[Wix.com|Wix.com-]]<nowiki/>backer [[Mark Tluszcz]]'s [http://www.mangrovepartners.com/ Mangrove Capital Partners], [[Naspers]] and [http://www.hvventures.com/ HV Holtzbrinck Ventures],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/nimbuzz#section-funding-rounds|title=Nimbuzz funding rounds|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> before its eventual majority acquisition by New Call in October 2014. MSM consolidated Nimbuzz with Holaa! and some of its other [[social media]], [[digital currency]], [[digital wallet]], VoIP and instant messaging technologies in March 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/dubai-based-social-media-firm-buys-messaging-app-668272.html|title=Dubai-based social media firm buys messaging app|last=Trenwith|first=Courtney|website=ArabianBusiness.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2017/03/24/943899/0/en/Mara-Social-Media-Acquires-Global-Instant-Messaging-Communications-Platform-Nimbuzz.html|title=MSM consolidates Nimbuzz technologies|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMSM is headquartered in Dubai with its principal development centres in [[Gurgaon|Gurugram]] and [[New Delhi]], India, after a relocation in May 2012 to be closer to the mobile Internet boom and rapidly growing smartphone penetration across South Asia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz to relocate global headquarters to India |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tech/tech-news/telecom/Nimbuzz-to-relocate-global-headquarters-to-India/articleshow/13392034.cms |accessdate=31 May 2013 |newspaper=The Times of India |date=22 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz moves HQ from Netherlands to India |newspaper=IndianTelevision.com |date=14 July 2012 |url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/mam/headlines/y2k12/july/julymam70.php |accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz appoints Vikas Saxena as CEO |newspaper=TelecomTiger |date=1 February 2013 |url=http://www.telecomtiger.com/Policy_Movement_fullstory.aspx?storyid=16719&section=S205 |accessdate=2 July 2013}}</ref> A fifth of Nimbuzz's users reside in India, and the app accounts for a quarter of the smartphone chat market in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz chat application relocates global headquarters to India |newspaper=The Economic Times |date=22 May 2012 |url= http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-05-22/news/31814443_1_nimbuzz-india-operations-aircel |accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref> Additional offices are located in [[Rotterdam]], the Netherlands, in [[San Francisco]], California, in [[Sao Paulo]], Brazil, and in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]], Argentina, where a further software development team is located.<ref>{{cite news |title=Company Overview of Nimbuzz B.V. |publisher=Businessweek.com |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=28846240 |accessdate=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nRevenue for the company, which in 2015 was reportedly approximately US$30 million, comes from NimbuzzOut, [[e-commerce]] sales on N-World, from in-app purchases and subscriptions. An advertising and partners\u2019 platform provides additional revenue opportunities.<ref name=\"income\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz bets big on mobile advertising |newspaper=The Hindu Business Line |date=6 May 2013 |url= http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/nimbuzz-bets-big-on-mobile-advertising/article4689528.ece |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> The company also partners directly with telecom operators.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz To Double Manpower, Revenue Growth in 2013 |newspaper=Light Reading India |date=4 April 2013 |url= http://www.lightreading.in/lightreadingindia/news-analysis/156254/nimbuzz-double-manpower-revenue-growth-2013#.UbA6npxafpE |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Khan|first=Danish|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/telecom/new-call-telecom-acquires-70-stake-in-nimbuzz-for-175-million/articleshow/44954217.cms?from=mdr|title=New Call Telecom acquires 70% stake in Nimbuzz for $ 175 million|date=2014-10-28|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n==Features and functionality==\nNimbuzz has been made available for [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[BlackBerry OS]], [[Symbian]], [[Windows Phone]] and [[Java Platform, Micro Edition|Java ME]] mobile operating systems. It was one of the few instant messaging apps available for Java-based phones, and they account for 25% of Nimbuzz users.<ref>{{cite news |last=Butcher |first=Mike |title=Nimbuzz Hits 150M Emerging Market Users, Puts The Heat on Facebook in Asia |newspaper=TechCrunch |date=15 March 2013 |url= https://techcrunch.com/2013/03/15/nimbuzz-hits-150m-emerging-market-users-puts-the-heat-on-facebook-in-asia/ |accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kanal |first=Nishtha |title=Nimbuzz reaches 150 million worldwide user mark |newspaper=Tech2 |date=16 March 2013 |url=http://tech2.in.com/news/apps/nimbuzz-reaches-150-million-worldwide-user-mark/829012 |accessdate=3 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429202743/http://tech2.in.com/news/apps/nimbuzz-reaches-150-million-worldwide-user-mark/829012 |archive-date=29 April 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz Planning to Join Asia Chat App Wars |url=http://www.techinasia.com/nimbuzz-asia-plans/ |accessdate=7 June 2013 |newspaper=Tech in Asia |date=17 December 2012}}</ref> For non-natively supported devices, a [[Wireless Application Protocol|WAP]] interface is available. For desktop computers, clients are available for both [[Windows]] and [[Mac OS X]]. It is available in Spanish, French, German, Italian, Dutch, Portuguese, Russian, Hindi and Arabic.<ref name=\"languages\" />\n\nNimbuzz users can send [[XMPP]] based instant messages, images, and share their location. Group chat is also supported. [[Voice over IP|Voice-over-Internet Protocol]] calls between most Nimbuzz clients is supported,<ref>{{cite news |title=Alternative To Skype on the Mobile |url=http://blog.nimbuzz.com/2010/11/11/alternative-to-skype-on-the-mobile/#more-4915 |accessdate=3 June 2013 |newspaper=Nimbuzz blog |date=11 November 2010}}</ref> and there is a VoIP-to-[[PSTN]] (landline/cellular) service branded as NimbuzzOut.<ref name=\"NimbuzzOut\">{{cite web |title=NimbuzzOut |url=http://www.nimbuzz.com/en/nimbuzzout/index |publisher=Nimbuzz |accessdate=3 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023185213/http://www.nimbuzz.com/en/nimbuzzout/index |archive-date=23 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Nimbuzz can be set up with any valid SIP (VoIP) account.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nimbuzz SIP Settings for voip configuration |url=http://www.voipvoip.com/nimbuzz/ |publisher=voipvoip.com |accessdate=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nNimbuzz supported interaction with popular messaging services such as [[Twitter]], [[Facebook Chat]] and [[Google Talk]]. In February 2012, Nimbuzz announced the discontinuation of support for ICQ, AIM, Myspace and Hyves because of the general lack of usage of these chat services.<ref>{{cite web |title=Discontinuation of AOL, ICQ, MySpace, Hyves |publisher=nimbuzz.com |url=http://blog.nimbuzz.com/2012/02/23/nimbuzz-says-goodbye-to-aim-icq-myspace-and-hyves/ |accessdate=5 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nNimbuzz has an in-app portal called N-World, with applications, gifts, games, avatars and other virtual goods for sale. N-World has its own digital currency called Nimbuckz.<ref name=\"income\">{{cite news |last=Wee |first=Willis |title=Nimbuzz Dominates India and Middle East |newspaper=Tech in Asia |date=31 May 2013 |url=http://www.techinasia.com/150-million-users-chat-app-nimbuzz-dominates-india-middle-east/ |accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Nimbuzz Support |url=http://www.nimbuzz.com/en/support |publisher=Nimbuzz |accessdate=3 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521084121/http://www.nimbuzz.com/en/support/ |archive-date=21 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Exclusive: Nimbuzz Update Introduces N-World for Android |newspaper=Tech 2 |date=3 January 2011 |url=http://tech2.in.com/news/windows-mobile/exclusive-nimbuzz-update-introduces-nworld-for-android/183402 |accessdate=6 June 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.nimbuzz.com/en/}}\n{{Instant messaging}}\n\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n[[Category:BlackBerry software]]\n[[Category:Windows Mobile software]]\n[[Category:Symbian software]]\n[[Category:Java device platform]]\n[[Category:Communication software]]\n[[Category:Mobile instant messaging clients]]\n[[Category:VoIP software]]\n[[Category:2017 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox software\n| logo = Nimbuzz logo.png\n| logo size = 150px\n| name = Nimbuzz\n| developer = Nimbuzz B.V.<br>\nMSM Global Holdings Limited\n| released = 13 May 2008<ref name=\"launched\">{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz's All-in-One Mobile IM & VoIP App |newspaper=gigaom.com \n|date=13 May 2008 |url=http://gigaom.com/2008/05/13/nimbuzz-launches-symbian-client-for-mobile-smsimvoip/ \n|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref>\n| discontinued = Yes\n| latest release date = discontinued\n| operating system = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[BlackBerry OS]], [[Symbian]], [[Windows Phone]], [[Java Platform, Micro Edition|Java ME]], [[Windows]], and [[Mac OS]].\n| language = English, Spanish, French, German, Italian, Dutch, Portuguese, Russian, Hindi, Arabic and more.<ref name=\"languages\">{{cite news |title=Windows Phone 8 \u2013 Now Connected! |newspaper=Nimbuzz blog |date=3 April 2013 |url=http://blog.nimbuzz.com/2013/04/03/windows-phone-8-now-connected/ |accessdate=31 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407172428/http://blog.nimbuzz.com/2013/04/03/windows-phone-8-now-connected/ |archive-date=7 April 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| genre = Instant Messaging Client & VoIP\n| licence = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]]\n| website = {{URL|www.nimbuzz.com/en/}}\n}}\n\n'''Nimbuzz''' was a [[Proprietary software|proprietary]] [[cross-platform]] [[instant messaging]] aggregator for [[smartphone]]s, [[tablet computer|tablets]] and [[personal computer]]s developed by MSM Global Holdings Limited, with the origins of its technology dating back to the early 2000s. As of March 2013, Nimbuzz had 150 million users in 200 countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz reaches 150 million users |newspaper=Telecompaper.com |date=15 March 2013 |url=http://www.telecompaper.com/news/nimbuzz-reaches-150-million-users--931519 |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> By April 2014, Nimbuzz was growing by more than 210,000 new registrations per day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/in/2014/04/24/nimbuzz-targets-skype-with-deal-to-pre-install-its-app-on-lg-devices-with-100-minutes-of-free-calls/|title=Nimbuzz targets Skype with deal to pre-install its app on LG devices, with 100 minutes of free calls|last1=Russell|first1=Jon|date=24 April 2014|work=TheNextWeb|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref> In October 2014, now with over 200 million users, New Call acquired 70% of Nimbuzz, valuing the business at $250 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2014/10/28/big-in-india-messaging-app-nimbuzz-goes-to-uks-new-call-in-250m-deal/|title=Messaging App Nimbuzz Goes To UK\u2019s New Call In $250M Deal|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref> Under CEO Anubhav Nagar's leadership from March 2015,<ref>{{Cite press release|url=http://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2017/03/24/943899/0/en/Mara-Social-Media-Acquires-Global-Instant-Messaging-Communications-Platform-Nimbuzz.html|title=Mara Social Media Acquires Global Instant Messaging & Communications Platform \u201cNimbuzz\u201d|first=Mara Group Holdings|last=Limited|date=24 March 2017|website=GlobeNewswire News Room}}</ref> the Nimbuzz suite of applications enables users to enjoy [[free calls]], [[instant messaging]], [[social-network games]], [[file sharing]], and [[social networking]] on their mobile device. In addition, Nimbuzz offers discounted calling rates to most countries in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/in/2013/10/22/nimbuzz-launches-low-cost-international-calling-in-india-aiming-to-disrupt-a-1-5-billion-industry/|title=Nimbuzz Launches Low-Cost International Calls in India|first=Jon|last=Russell|date=22 October 2013|website=The Next Web}}</ref> Nimbuzz site and servers went offline in 2019, and as February 2020, remain unavailable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nimbuzz.com|title=Nimbuzz Homepage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090320111712/http://www.nimbuzz.com/|archive-date=20 March 2009|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Company history and background==\nAdopting the Nimbuzz brand from 2004 onwards, the company entered the mainstream VoIP market in January 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title=No Buzz for Nimbuzz |url=http://gigaom.com/2007/01/16/no-buzz-for-nimbuzz/ |accessdate=31 May 2013 |newspaper=gigaom.com |date=16 January 2007}}</ref> In May 2008, the company launched its combined [[Voice over IP|Voice-over-Internet Protocol]] (VoIP) and instant messaging client.<ref name=\"launched\" /> In January 2009, the company was selected as one of 100 winners of the [[Red Herring (magazine)|Red Herring]] Global 100 technology industry awards for 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz in Red Herring top 100 |language=Dutch |newspaper=Emerce |location=The Netherlands |date=21 January 2009 |url=http://www.emerce.nl/nieuws/nimbuzz-in-red-herring-top-100 |accessdate=2 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz awarded Red Herring 100 |newspaper=Techwatch |date=23 January 2009 |url=http://www.techwatch.co.uk/2009/01/23/nimbuzz-awarded-red-herring-100/ |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nEarly stage investors over three rounds between December 2005 and July 2008 included [[Skype]]- and [[Wix.com|Wix.com-]]<nowiki/>backer [[Mark Tluszcz]]'s [http://www.mangrovepartners.com/ Mangrove Capital Partners], [[Naspers]] and [http://www.hvventures.com/ HV Holtzbrinck Ventures],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/nimbuzz#section-funding-rounds|title=Nimbuzz funding rounds|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> before its eventual majority acquisition by New Call in October 2014. MSM consolidated Nimbuzz with some of its other technologies in March 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/dubai-based-social-media-firm-buys-messaging-app-668272.html|title=Dubai-based social media firm buys messaging app|last=Trenwith|first=Courtney|website=ArabianBusiness.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2017/03/24/943899/0/en/Mara-Social-Media-Acquires-Global-Instant-Messaging-Communications-Platform-Nimbuzz.html|title=MSM consolidates Nimbuzz technologies|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMSM is headquartered in Dubai with its principal development centre in [[New Delhi]], India, after a relocation in May 2012 to be closer to the mobile Internet boom and rapidly growing smartphone penetration across South Asia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz to relocate global headquarters to India |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tech/tech-news/telecom/Nimbuzz-to-relocate-global-headquarters-to-India/articleshow/13392034.cms |accessdate=31 May 2013 |newspaper=The Times of India |date=22 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz moves HQ from Netherlands to India |newspaper=IndianTelevision.com |date=14 July 2012 |url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/mam/headlines/y2k12/july/julymam70.php |accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz appoints Vikas Saxena as CEO |newspaper=TelecomTiger |date=1 February 2013 |url=http://www.telecomtiger.com/Policy_Movement_fullstory.aspx?storyid=16719&section=S205 |accessdate=2 July 2013}}</ref> A fifth of Nimbuzz's users reside in India, and the app accounts for a quarter of the smartphone chat market in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz chat application relocates global headquarters to India |newspaper=The Economic Times |date=22 May 2012 |url= http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-05-22/news/31814443_1_nimbuzz-india-operations-aircel |accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref> Additional offices are located in [[Rotterdam]], the Netherlands, in [[San Francisco]], California, in [[Sao Paulo]], Brazil, and in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]], Argentina, where a further software development team is located.<ref>{{cite news |title=Company Overview of Nimbuzz B.V. |publisher=Businessweek.com |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=28846240 |accessdate=4 June 2013}}</ref> Revenue for the company comes from NimbuzzOut, [[e-commerce]] sales on N-World, and from advertising inside the application.<ref name=\"income\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz bets big on mobile advertising |newspaper=The Hindu Business Line |date=6 May 2013 |url= http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/nimbuzz-bets-big-on-mobile-advertising/article4689528.ece |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> The company also partners directly with telecom operators.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz To Double Manpower, Revenue Growth in 2013 |newspaper=Light Reading India |date=4 April 2013 |url= http://www.lightreading.in/lightreadingindia/news-analysis/156254/nimbuzz-double-manpower-revenue-growth-2013#.UbA6npxafpE |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Features and functionality==\nNimbuzz has been made available for [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[BlackBerry OS]], [[Symbian]], [[Windows Phone]] and [[Java Platform, Micro Edition|Java ME]] mobile operating systems. It was one of the few IM apps available for Java-based phones, and they account for 25% of Nimbuzz users.<ref>{{cite news |last=Butcher |first=Mike |title=Nimbuzz Hits 150M Emerging Market Users, Puts The Heat on Facebook in Asia |newspaper=TechCrunch |date=15 March 2013 |url= https://techcrunch.com/2013/03/15/nimbuzz-hits-150m-emerging-market-users-puts-the-heat-on-facebook-in-asia/ |accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kanal |first=Nishtha |title=Nimbuzz reaches 150 million worldwide user mark |newspaper=Tech2 |date=16 March 2013 |url=http://tech2.in.com/news/apps/nimbuzz-reaches-150-million-worldwide-user-mark/829012 |accessdate=3 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429202743/http://tech2.in.com/news/apps/nimbuzz-reaches-150-million-worldwide-user-mark/829012 |archive-date=29 April 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nimbuzz Planning to Join Asia Chat App Wars |url=http://www.techinasia.com/nimbuzz-asia-plans/ |accessdate=7 June 2013 |newspaper=Tech in Asia |date=17 December 2012}}</ref> For non-natively supported devices, a [[Wireless Application Protocol|WAP]] interface is available. For desktop computers, clients are available for both [[Windows]] and [[Mac OS X]]. It is available in Spanish, French, German, Italian, Dutch, Portuguese, Russian, Hindi and Arabic.<ref name=\"languages\" />\n\nNimbuzz users can send [[XMPP]] based instant messages, images, and share their location. Group chat is also supported. [[Voice over IP|Voice-over-Internet Protocol]] calls between most Nimbuzz clients is supported,<ref>{{cite news |title=Alternative To Skype on the Mobile |url=http://blog.nimbuzz.com/2010/11/11/alternative-to-skype-on-the-mobile/#more-4915 |accessdate=3 June 2013 |newspaper=Nimbuzz blog |date=11 November 2010}}</ref> and there is a VoIP-to-[[PSTN]] (landline/cellular) service branded as \"NimbuzzOut\".<ref name=\"NimbuzzOut\">{{cite web |title=NimbuzzOut |url=http://www.nimbuzz.com/en/nimbuzzout/index |publisher=Nimbuzz |accessdate=3 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023185213/http://www.nimbuzz.com/en/nimbuzzout/index |archive-date=23 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Nimbuzz can be set up with any valid SIP (VoIP) account.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nimbuzz SIP Settings for voip configuration |url=http://www.voipvoip.com/nimbuzz/ |publisher=voipvoip.com |accessdate=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nNimbuzz supported interaction with popular messaging services such as [[Twitter]], [[Facebook Chat]] and [[Google Talk]]. In February 2012, Nimbuzz announced the discontinuation of support for ICQ, AIM, Myspace and Hyves because of the general lack of usage of these chat services.<ref>{{cite web |title=Discontinuation of AOL, ICQ, MySpace, Hyves |publisher=nimbuzz.com |url=http://blog.nimbuzz.com/2012/02/23/nimbuzz-says-goodbye-to-aim-icq-myspace-and-hyves/ |accessdate=5 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nNimbuzz has an in-app portal called N-World, with applications, gifts, games, avatars and other virtual goods for sale. N-World has its own currency called Nimbuckz.<ref name=\"income\">{{cite news |last=Wee |first=Willis |title=Nimbuzz Dominates India and Middle East |newspaper=Tech in Asia |date=31 May 2013 |url=http://www.techinasia.com/150-million-users-chat-app-nimbuzz-dominates-india-middle-east/ |accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Nimbuzz Support |url=http://www.nimbuzz.com/en/support |publisher=Nimbuzz |accessdate=3 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521084121/http://www.nimbuzz.com/en/support/ |archive-date=21 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Exclusive: Nimbuzz Update Introduces N-World for Android |newspaper=Tech 2 |date=3 January 2011 |url=http://tech2.in.com/news/windows-mobile/exclusive-nimbuzz-update-introduces-nworld-for-android/183402 |accessdate=6 June 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.nimbuzz.com/en/}}\n{{Instant messaging}}\n\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n[[Category:BlackBerry software]]\n[[Category:Windows Mobile software]]\n[[Category:Symbian software]]\n[[Category:Java device platform]]\n[[Category:Communication software]]\n[[Category:Mobile instant messaging clients]]\n[[Category:VoIP software]]\n[[Category:2017 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "name_user": "Gumbolimp", "label": "safe", "comment": "Further citations and links and some additional detail", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nimbuzz"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Portland, Oregon}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon\n| width =\n| image         = File:Coronavirus responses in Portland Oregon.jpeg\n| image_size    = \n| image_upright =\n| alt           =\n| caption       = Sign on a storefront in [[Portland, Oregon]], noting a temporary closure due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing coronavirus pandemic]]\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| map4 =\n| legend4 =\n| map5 =\n| legend5 =\n| disease = [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19)\n| virus_strain = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|Severe acute respiratory syndrome<br />coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2)\n| location = [[Portland, Oregon]]\n| first_case =\n| arrival_date = <!-- or | dates = -->\n| date = \n| origin =\n| type =\n| confirmed_cases =\n| active_cases =\n| suspected_cases =\n| severe_cases =\n| recovery_cases =\n| deaths =\n| territories =\n| total_ili =\n| website = {{URL|https://beta.portland.gov/novel-coronavirus-covid-19}}\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon''', is an ongoing viral pandemic of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). Efforts to prevent the virus spreading include event postponements and cancellations, and facility closures.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Coronavirus disease 2019|Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2}}\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oregon}}\n[[File:Ghost Hug chalk writing on Hawthorne during Coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|Chalk writing on a sidewalk in southeast Portland during the pandemic]]\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] is an ongoing [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The outbreak started in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]] province, [[China]], in December 2019. The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) declared the outbreak to be a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]] on 30 January 2020 and a pandemic on 11 March 2020.\n\nAs of {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date|editlink=|ref=no}}, more than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|conround|editlink=|ref=no}} cases of COVID-19 have been reported in more than 200 countries and territories, resulting in more than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|dround|editlink=|ref=no}} deaths.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}} More than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|recround|editlink=|ref=no}} people have recovered.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}}\n\nThe pandemic was first confirmed to have spread to the United States in January 2020. Cases have been confirmed in all fifty U.S. states, [[Washington, D.C.]], and all inhabited [[Territories of the United States|U.S. territories]] except [[American Samoa]].<ref name=\"mariana\">{{cite web|url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/28/saipan-confirms-two-covid-19-positive-cases/2932326001/|title=Saipan confirms two COVID-19 positive cases|date=March 28, 2020|website=samoanews.com|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330220357/https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/28/saipan-confirms-two-covid-19-positive-cases/2932326001/|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> {{As of|2020|03|31|df=US}}, the U.S. has the most confirmed active cases in the world and ranks third in the number of total deaths from the virus.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905173559/https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|archive-date=September 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The pandemic was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Oregon]] on February 28, 2020.\n\n==Cases==\nOregon's first presumptive case was announced in Portland on February 28, 2020. Governor [[Kate Brown]] spoke and the director of the [[Oregon Health Authority]] confirmed someone from [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]] who worked at Forest Hills Elementary School in [[Lake Oswego, Oregon|Lake Oswego]] was being treated at [[Hillsboro, Oregon|Hillsboro]]'s [[Kaiser Westside Medical Center]]. The [[Lake Oswego School District]] closed the school for cleaning.<ref name=\"first\">{{cite news |title=State officials announce first presumptive case of coronavirus in Oregon |url=https://www.kptv.com/news/state-officials-announce-first-presumptive-case-of-coronavirus-in-oregon/article_6ac26688-5a93-11ea-a0af-d346d4e06ef0.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[KPTV]] |date=February 28, 2020 |location=Portland, Oregon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304134326/https://www.kptv.com/news/state-officials-announce-first-presumptive-case-of-coronavirus-in-oregon/article_6ac26688-5a93-11ea-a0af-d346d4e06ef0.html |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"firstabc\">{{cite news |last1=Selsky |first1=Andrew |title=Oregon has 1st coronavirus case: elementary school employee |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/oregon-1st-coronavirus-case-elementary-school-employee-69298619 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |via=[[Associated Press]] |date=February 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229155313/https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/oregon-1st-coronavirus-case-elementary-school-employee-69298619 |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first case in [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] and fifteenth in Oregon was confirmed on March 10; the patient was treatment at the [[Veterans Affairs Medical Center (Oregon)|Veterans Affairs Medical Center]].<ref name=\"case15\">{{cite news |title=Oregon confirms 15th coronavirus case in state |url=https://www.registerguard.com/news/20200310/oregon-confirms-15th-coronavirus-case-in-state |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The Register-Guard]] |date=March 10, 2020 |location=Eugene, Oregon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320150843/https://www.registerguard.com/news/20200310/oregon-confirms-15th-coronavirus-case-in-state |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> An employee who worked at the [[Wells Fargo Center (Portland, Oregon)|Wells Fargo Center]] tested positive on March 14, prompting building tenant [[Davis Wright Tremaine]] to close offices in Portland.<ref name=\"skyscraper\">{{cite news |last1=Rogoway |first1=Mike |title=Coronavirus case linked to downtown Portland skyscraper |url=https://pamplinmedia.com/pt/9-news/456350-372216-coronavirus-case-linked-to-downtown-portland-skyscraper-pwoff |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316013205/https://pamplinmedia.com/pt/9-news/456350-372216-coronavirus-case-linked-to-downtown-portland-skyscraper-pwoff |archive-date=March 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> More than 30 people in the Portland metropolitan area tested positive by April 1.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/strong-evidence-seen-that-oregons-coronavirus-restrictions-are-working.html |title=\u2018Strong evidence\u2019 seen that Oregon\u2019s coronavirus restrictions are working |website=The Oregonian |date=April 1, 2020 |access-date=April 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401215612/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/strong-evidence-seen-that-oregons-coronavirus-restrictions-are-working.html |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Healthcare at Foster Creek nursing home in southeast Portland was Oregon's largest coronavirus death cluster, as of mid April, with 50 confirmed cases and 14 deaths. The [[Oregon Department of Human Services]] identified many safety violations.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/portland-nursing-home-reports-14-deaths-after-slew-of-coronavirus-violations.html</ref><ref>https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/oregon-coronavirus-nursing-home-14-deaths-safety-violations/283-b574e186-6a80-4430-80bc-fd45d1857319</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n{{Main|U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Multnomah County Library Northwest branch with closure notice during 2020 coronavirus epidemic.jpg|thumb|left|Closure notice posted at the [[Northwest Library]] on March 16, 2020]]\n\nOn March 13, the [[Portland Police Bureau]] announced a reduction of in-person responses to reduce virus transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kobi5.com/news/portland-police-reduce-in-person-responses-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-123900/|title=Portland police reduce in-person responses amid coronavirus outbreak|date=March 13, 2020|website=KOBI-TV NBC5 / KOTI-TV NBC2|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325013939/https://kobi5.com/news/portland-police-reduce-in-person-responses-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-123900/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/public-global-health/487984-police-nationwide-ask-criminals-to-halt-activity|title=Police nationwide ask criminals to halt activity during coronavirus outbreak|first=Justine|last=Coleman|date=March 17, 2020|website=TheHill|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325013923/https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/public-global-health/487984-police-nationwide-ask-criminals-to-halt-activity|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Multnomah County Library]] closed all branch libraries and [[Portland Parks and Recreation]] (PPR) closed arts and community centers, sports facilities, and swimming pools, based on recommendations issued by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], [[Multnomah County Health Department]], and the Oregon Health Authority. PPR canceled athletic programs and indoor activities at community centers, but did not close golf courses, natural areas, parks, playgrounds, or trails, or cancel outdoor events for less than 250 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/covid--closures-multnomah-county-libraries-some-portland-parks-rec/article_d56dbd54-659a-11ea-a9dc-637432f6280c.html|title=COVID-19 closures: Multnomah County libraries, some Portland Parks & Rec facilities shut down|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323150334/https://www.kptv.com/news/covid--closures-multnomah-county-libraries-some-portland-parks-rec/article_d56dbd54-659a-11ea-a9dc-637432f6280c.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Portland Police have received 469 reports of social distancing violation between March 25, and April 14, yet have issued zero citations. The police reasoned that it would overburden the criminal justice system and compared the enforcement to enforcing every traffic violation being reported<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/how-to-report-people-who-arent-social-distancing/283-a90abfa0-389c-4bd0-baee-4e3a171883dd|title='This really isn't social distancing': What to do if you come across social distance violators|last=|first=|date=April 15, 2020|website=KGW|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16|quote=in reporter's video. at 3m25s and in body}}</ref> In comparison, [[Manhattan Beach, California]] have issued 129 citations over a weekend in early April.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:Portland, Oregon during the coronavirus pandemic, March 2020 - 16.jpg|thumb|upright|COVID-19 sign on a  bus-stop shelter in [[Woodstock, Portland, Oregon|Woodstock]]]]\nOn March 17, Multnomah County Chair Deborah Kafoury announced plans to add as many as 400 beds for county residents affected by the pandemic requiring shelter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/multnomah-county-to-add-hundreds-of-homeless-shelter-beds-within-the-week-for-people-with-symptoms-of-coronavirus.html|title=Multnomah County to add hundreds of homeless shelter beds within the week to help with coronavirus|first=Molly|last=Harbarger|date=March 17, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323212540/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/multnomah-county-to-add-hundreds-of-homeless-shelter-beds-within-the-week-for-people-with-symptoms-of-coronavirus.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> 120 beds were made available at the PPR-owned [[Charles Jordan Community Center]] in north Portland on March 19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/first-coronavirus-related-emergency-homeless-shelter-to-open-in-north-portland.html|title=First coronavirus-related emergency homeless shelter to open in North Portland|first=Molly|last=Harbarger|date=March 19, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323212537/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/first-coronavirus-related-emergency-homeless-shelter-to-open-in-north-portland.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]]'s [[Oregon Convention Center]], unable to host events since March 12, was converted into a temporary shelter with 130\u2013140 beds. The Joint Office of Homeless Services, a collaboration between the City of Portland and Multnomah County, hoped to open additional beds for healthy individuals as overflow from existing shelters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/oregon-convention-center-shelter/283-3f46becb-f2fa-4865-9cc1-65b35c741085|title=Oregon Convention Center to become temporary coronavirus-related homeless shelter|publisher=[[KGW]]|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323212534/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/oregon-convention-center-shelter/283-3f46becb-f2fa-4865-9cc1-65b35c741085|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/homeless-will-find-refuge-at-oregon-convention-center/|title=Homeless will find refuge at Oregon Convention Center|date=March 20, 2020|publisher=[[KOIN (TV)|KOIN]]|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323222632/https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/homeless-will-find-refuge-at-oregon-convention-center/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Trucks normally used by Multnomah Country Library and for animal control were repurposed to assist with the convention center conversion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/tape-and-two-hours-to-transform-oregon-convention-center-into-coronavirus-homeless-shelter.html |title=Tape and 2 hours to transform Oregon Convention Center into coronavirus homeless shelter |first=Molly |last=Harbarger |date=March 21, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323221955/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/tape-and-two-hours-to-transform-oregon-convention-center-into-coronavirus-homeless-shelter.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nOn March 22, Mayor [[Ted Wheeler]] said he was prepared to issue a [[stay-at-home order]] for Portland residents if Governor Brown would not issue a similar order for Oregon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/wheeler-to-brown-issue-statewide-stay-at-home-order/|title=Wheeler to Brown: Issue statewide stay-at-home order|date=March 22, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134322/https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/wheeler-to-brown-issue-statewide-stay-at-home-order/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/mayor-wheeler-on-stay-at-home-order-im-ready-to-act-for-portland-tomorrow|title=Mayor Wheeler on stay-at-home order: 'I'm ready to act for Portland tomorrow'|date=March 22, 2020|publisher=[[KATU]]|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322235314/https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/mayor-wheeler-on-stay-at-home-order-im-ready-to-act-for-portland-tomorrow|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The governor was also pressured by 25 Portland-area mayors, Metro's council, multiple county chairs, and other elected and health officials. She issued an executive order on March 23 requiring home [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]] for Oregonians, with some exceptions, and to practice [[social distancing]]. Violators may be punished with 30 days in jail and fines as high as $1,250 as a class C [[misdemeanor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-stay-at-home-order-coronavirus-covid-19-kate-brown/|title=Gov. Kate Brown Issues Order Directing Oregonians To 'Stay Home'|first=Dirk|last=VanderHart|date=March 2, 2020|publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323202624/https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-stay-at-home-order-coronavirus-covid-19-kate-brown/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Portland Police Bureau confirmed criminal citations were a \"last resort measure\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/23/portland-police-can-now-issue-criminal-citations-to-those-who-violate-browns-stay-at-home-order/|title=Portland Police May Now Issue Criminal Citations to Anyone Who Violates Brown\u2019s Stay at Home Order|date=March 23, 2020|first1=Tess|last1=Riski|newspaper=Willamette Week|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324134348/https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/23/portland-police-can-now-issue-criminal-citations-to-those-who-violate-browns-stay-at-home-order/|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The police have issued a statement to the public to not call 911 to report violations of stay-at-home order, but to call the non-emergency line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-police-dont-call-911-to-report-people-violating-coronavirus-stay-home-order.html|title=Portland police: Don\u2019t call 911 to report people violating coronavirus stay-home order|last=Acker|first=Lizzy|date=2020-03-29|website=oregonlive|publisher=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nCity official extended the [[Portland Arts Tax]] deadline from April 15 to July 15, 2020.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-arts-tax-now-due-in-july-due-to-coronavirus-city-says.html</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n{{Main|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{See also|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Hand sanitizer and gloves sold out due to Coronavirus 10 57 26 366000.jpeg|thumb|right|Empty [[latex glove]] shelves at a [[Rite Aid]] store in [[downtown Portland]]]]\n\n[[Delta Air Lines]] reduced flights between Portland and Japan. United Airlines cut 4 of 20 flights from Portland as well as one from Eugene. [[Sun Country Airlines]] reduced flights between Portland and Honolulu, Las Vegas, and San Francisco.<ref name=Outlook>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-darkens-oregons-economic-outlook-but-impacts-are-muted-for-now.html |title=Coronavirus darkens Oregon's economic outlook, but impacts are muted -- for now |first=Mike |last=Rogoway |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312163905/https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-darkens-oregons-economic-outlook-but-impacts-are-muted-for-now.html |archive-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSchool closures and event cancellations prompted people to stock up on groceries. Long lines were seen at grocery stores and food pantries throughout the Portland metropolitan area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-grocery-stores-and-food-pantries-busy-as-covid-/article_67560a58-6656-11ea-b7d7-c3c87e0e2492.html|title=Portland grocery stores and food pantries busy as COVID-19 closures begin|first=John|last=Hendricks|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323145749/https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-grocery-stores-and-food-pantries-busy-as-covid-/article_67560a58-6656-11ea-b7d7-c3c87e0e2492.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Local [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] dispensaries saw an increased demand as customers stocked up in case stores were forced to close temporarily.<ref name=Open>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-portland-coronavirus-covid-19-whats-open/|title=Life In The Time Of Coronavirus: What's Still Open In Oregon?|first=Donald|last=Orr|date=March 19, 2020|publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324011921/https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-portland-coronavirus-covid-19-whats-open/|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Oregon Liquor Control Commission]] (OLCC) permitted stores to operate via curbside pick-up and home delivery temporarily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/weve-been-having-420-every-day-for-the-last-2-weeks-oregon-pot-shops-see-spike-in-business-with-new-curbside-delivery/283-163e563c-a5e4-4b2a-87e1-76578a607346|title=\u2018We\u2019ve been having 4/20 every day\u2019: Oregon pot shops see spike in business with new curbside delivery|website=KGW|access-date=2020-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327173032/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/weve-been-having-420-every-day-for-the-last-2-weeks-oregon-pot-shops-see-spike-in-business-with-new-curbside-delivery/283-163e563c-a5e4-4b2a-87e1-76578a607346|archive-date=2020-03-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/at-home-because-of-the-coronavirus-shutdown-heres-who-delivers-cannabis-products-in-portland.html|title=At home because of the coronavirus shutdown? Here's who delivers cannabis products in Portland|first=Lizzy|last=Acker|date=March 25, 2020|website=The Oregonian|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327173312/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/at-home-because-of-the-coronavirus-shutdown-heres-who-delivers-cannabis-products-in-portland.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186115/oregon-cannabis-dispensaries-now-allowed-to-offer-curbside-pickup|title=Oregon Cannabis Dispensaries Now Allowed to Offer Curbside Pickup|first1=Wm Steven|last1=Humphrey|date=March 23, 2020|work=Portland Mercury|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326153724/https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186115/oregon-cannabis-dispensaries-now-allowed-to-offer-curbside-pickup|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Beverage Container Redemption Center in Oregon .jpg|right|thumb|Long line of people queued up in front of the BottleDrop redemption center in East Portland in April 2020. ]]\n\nOLCC suspended the enforcement of the [[Oregon Bottle Bill]] on March 15 so that grocers can focus on restocking, sanitation and social distancing management. Grocers may elect to not accept bottle returns during this period. The Oregon Beverage Recycling Cooperative (OBRC) which operates Beverage container redemption centers throughout Oregon is keeping their centers open.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-grocers-close-bottle-drop-service-due-to-coronavirus-staffing-issues.html|title=Oregon grocers close bottle return service due to coronavirus staffing issues|last=Harbarger|first=Molly|date=March 18, 2020|website=oregonlive|publisher=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/olcc-extends-bottle-bill-reprieve-for-oregon-businesses-due-to-pandemic/article_39a30206-744c-11ea-b7b3-574ecfd6fa66.html|title=OLCC extends bottle bill reprieve for Oregon businesses due to pandemic|last=Staff|first=FOX 12|website=KPTV.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The enforcement suspension remains in effect until June 1, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/04/23/oregon-grocery-stores-dont-have-to-accept-returnable-cans-and-bottles-until-june-1/|title=Oregon Grocery Stores Don\u2019t Have to Accept Returnable Cans and Bottles Until June 1|last=Jaquiss|first=Nigel|date=April 23, 2020|website=Willamette Week|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> ''[[The Oregonian]]'' reported on April 23 that the City of Portland has been operating a bottle return site at an \"undisclosed site in North Portland\" based at one of the city's clinic that provides drug addicts with services such as clean syringes and opioid overdose antidote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/the-peoples-depot-is-portlands-semi-secret-bottle-return-program-to-help-those-impacted-by-state-bottle-bill-decision.html|title=The People\u2019s Depot is Portland\u2019s semi-secret bottle return program to help those impacted by state Bottle Bill decision|last=Harbarger|first=Molly|date=2020-04-23|website=oregonlive|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, Oregon temporarily lifted the prohibition on self-pump at gas stations at least until April 11 to ensure fuel is available during staffing issues related to the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/news/2020/03/oregon-temporarily-lifts-prohibition-on-self-service-gas-in-response-to-coronavirus.html|title=Oregon temporarily allows drivers to pump their own gas|last=Borrud|first=Hillary|date=2020-03-28|website=oregonlive|publisher=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n===Business closures and event cancellations===\n{{Main|List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Portland, Oregon during the coronavirus pandemic, March 2020 - 15.jpg|thumb|left|upright|People practicing social distancing while waiting to enter [[New Seasons Market]] in the [[Woodstock, Portland, Oregon|Woodstock]] neighborhood]]\n\n[[Adidas]] closed offices at Montgomery Park and Portland Village after two employees had close content with someone who tested positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/nba/adidas-closes-north-american-headquarters-amid-covid-19-pandemic|title=Adidas closes North American headquarters amid COVID-19 pandemic|date=March 12, 2020|website=NBC Sports Northwest|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151019/https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/nba/adidas-closes-north-american-headquarters-amid-covid-19-pandemic|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Powell's Books]] five stores closed,<ref name=Rogoway/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/local/powells-books-closes-as-coronavirus-spreads-in-portland-metro|title=Powell's Books closes as coronavirus spreads in Portland metro|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=KATU|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317193824/https://katu.com/news/local/powells-books-closes-as-coronavirus-spreads-in-portland-metro|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and laid off most staff members.<ref name=Open/> [[Portland Incubator Experiment]] canceled PIE Demo Day; the March 19 event scheduled to be held at [[Revolution Hall]] was held online.<ref name=Stein/> On March 25, [[Daimler Trucks North America]] shut down a plant on Swan Island until April 6.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/daimler-trucks-shutting-down-portland-plant-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Daimler Trucks shutting down Portland plant amid coronavirus outbreak|first=Mike|last=Rogoway|date=March 25, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327172243/https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/daimler-trucks-shutting-down-portland-plant-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Portland-based companies [[Puppet (company)|Puppet]] and [[Vacasa]] laid off employees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/silicon-forest/2020/03/portland-marketing-technology-startup-opal-lays-off-20-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Portland technology companies lay off dozens amid coronavirus outbreak|first=Mike|last=Rogoway|date=March 27, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328201124/https://www.oregonlive.com/silicon-forest/2020/03/portland-marketing-technology-startup-opal-lays-off-20-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In April, [[Evraz]] announced plans to lay off 230 employees at a Portland steel plant, and [[Precision Castparts Corp.]] confirmed plans to close its main Portland site.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/04/precision-castparts-will-shut-its-main-portland-site-coronavirus-latest-blow-to-oregons-economy.html</ref> \n\n[[Oaks Amusement Park]] and the [[Oaks Park Roller Skating Rink]], the [[Oregon Historical Society]], the [[Oregon Zoo]], [[Portland Children's Museum]],<ref name=Stein>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/event-cancellationspostponements-due-to-coronavirus-concerns.html|title=Events canceled in Oregon over the next months|first=Rosemarie|last=Stein|date=March 10, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323223733/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/event-cancellationspostponements-due-to-coronavirus-concerns.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Portland Japanese Garden]] closed as well.<ref name=Rogoway/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/list-portland-area-museums-attractions-closed-amid-coronavirus-response/|title=LIST: Portland area museums, attractions closed amid coronavirus response|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316131605/https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/list-portland-area-museums-attractions-closed-amid-coronavirus-response/|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of March 19, the [[Portland Art Museum]] and [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] are closed through March 31 and mid April, respectively.<ref name=Open/> The [[Crystal Ballroom (Portland, Oregon)|Crystal Ballroom]] and [[Hawthorne Theatre]] canceled or postponed planned shows through mid April.<ref name=Open/> The [[City Club of Portland]] canceled activities.<ref name=MCL>{{Cite news|last=Monahan|first=Rachel|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/city/2020/03/13/multnomah-county-library-closed-as-of-today-in-response-to-the-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Multnomah County Library Closed in Response to the Coronavirus Outbreak|date=March 13, 2020|work=[[Willamette Week]]|accessdate=April 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403220746/https://www.wweek.com/news/city/2020/03/13/multnomah-county-library-closed-as-of-today-in-response-to-the-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Portland Rose Festival]] has postponed annual events, including the [[Starlight Parade]], indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=https://www.wweek.com/arts/2020/03/19/the-portland-rose-festival-has-been-postponed-indefinitely/|title=The Portland Rose Festival Has Been Postponed Indefinitely|date=March 19, 2020|work=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323180902/https://www.wweek.com/arts/2020/03/19/the-portland-rose-festival-has-been-postponed-indefinitely/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/entertainment/2020/03/the-portland-rose-festival-has-been-postponed.html |title=The 2020 Portland Rose Festival has been postponed due to coronavirus crisis |first1=Rosemarie |last1=Stein |first2=Kjerstin |last2=Gabrielson |date=March 19, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323180907/https://www.oregonlive.com/entertainment/2020/03/the-portland-rose-festival-has-been-postponed.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Herbal Products Association]]'s Hemp-CBD Congress, scheduled for mid April at the [[Benson Hotel]], was canceled.<ref name=Stein/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/09/28113766/coronavirus-and-cannabis-how-pot-is-impacted-by-a-pandemic |title=Coronavirus and Cannabis: How Pot Is Impacted by a Pandemic |first1=Josh |last1=Jardine |date=March 9, 2020 |newspaper=[[Portland Mercury]] |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313032723/https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/09/28113766/coronavirus-and-cannabis-how-pot-is-impacted-by-a-pandemic |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Road Runners Club of America]]'s annual convention, slated to be held at the [[Hilton Portland Hotel]] during March 19\u201322, was also canceled.<ref name=Stein/> A conference on [[affordable housing]], climate, and community stability featuring [[Julian Castro]] during April 2\u20134 was canceled.<ref name=Stein/> [[TechfestNW]] was to be held at [[Portland State University]] during April 2\u20133, but was rescheduled for August 6\u20137. April 11's Cider Rite of Spring was rescheduled for November, and Design Week Festival was moved from the week starting April 18 to August 1\u20138. The arts and technology festival [[XOXO (festival)|XOXO]] scheduled for September has been canceled.<ref name=Stein/> [[Pride Northwest]]'s annual [[pride parade]] has been postponed, and the Portland Retro Gaming Expo has been canceled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186244/todays-coronavirus-news-roundup-brown-issues-stay-home-order-dems-slam-gop-stimulus-bill-and-trump-keeps-getting-in-the-way|title=Today's Coronavirus News Roundup: Brown Issues \"Stay Home\" Order, Dems Slam GOP Stimulus Bill, and Trump Keeps Getting in the Way|date=March 23, 2020|work=Portland Mercury|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324133621/https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186244/todays-coronavirus-news-roundup-brown-issues-stay-home-order-dems-slam-gop-stimulus-bill-and-trump-keeps-getting-in-the-way|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Waterfront Blues Festival]], slated for July 2\u20135, was canceled on March 25.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/waterfront-blues-festival-canceled-for-2020-will-return-in-2021.html|title=Waterfront Blues Festival canceled for 2020, will return in 2021|first=Samantha|last=Swindler|date=March 24, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325160751/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/waterfront-blues-festival-canceled-for-2020-will-return-in-2021.html|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=https://www.wweek.com/music/2020/03/24/the-waterfront-blues-festival-has-been-canceled-due-to-the-pandemic/|title=The Waterfront Blues Festival Has Been Canceled Due to the Pandemic|date=March 24, 2020|newspaper=Willamette Week|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325160755/https://www.wweek.com/music/2020/03/24/the-waterfront-blues-festival-has-been-canceled-due-to-the-pandemic/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/organizers-cancel-waterfront-blues-festival-over-coronavirus-concerns|title=Organizers cancel Waterfront Blues Festival over coronavirus concerns|author=KATU Staff|date=March 24, 2020|website=KATU|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325160751/https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/organizers-cancel-waterfront-blues-festival-over-coronavirus-concerns|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhile cheer and dance competitions were still being held at the Oregon Convention Center in early March,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/crowds-gather-at-convention-center-despite-virus-concerns/|title=Crowds gather at convention center despite virus concerns|date=March 7, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323224315/https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/crowds-gather-at-convention-center-despite-virus-concerns/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> many events planned to be hosted at the venue were canceled. On February 5, the Materials Show scheduled for February 12\u201313 was canceled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-trade-show-canceled-over-coronavirus-concerns/article_28d3fde8-4889-11ea-bcd6-8bb625985644.html|title=Portland trade show canceled over coronavirus concerns|date=February 5, 2020|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323223337/https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-trade-show-canceled-over-coronavirus-concerns/article_28d3fde8-4889-11ea-bcd6-8bb625985644.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://q13fox.com/2020/02/05/portland-convention-rescheduled-over-coronavirus-fears/|title=Portland convention rescheduled over coronavirus fears|date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206124911/https://q13fox.com/2020/02/05/portland-convention-rescheduled-over-coronavirus-fears/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Gem Faire and the Multnomah County Democrats' annual Celsi Celebration slated for the weekend of March 21 were also canceled.<ref name=Stein/> On March 6, organizers of the Go West Summit, an international travel conference for March 24\u201327 expecting approximately 800 people, was postponed.<ref name=Hotels>{{Cite news|last=Iboshi|first=Kyle|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/portland-hotels-see-significant-room-cancellations-travel-conference-postponed/283-6d3b08c3-7a8a-4b56-a65c-bac4919cd73d|title=Portland hotels see 'significant' room cancellations; travel conference postponed|date=March 6, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=April 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406020722/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/portland-hotels-see-significant-room-cancellations-travel-conference-postponed/283-6d3b08c3-7a8a-4b56-a65c-bac4919cd73d|archive-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Oregon Dental Association's annual Oregon Dental Conference for April 2\u20134 was canceled.<ref name=Stein/> On March 9, the Burning Cat event being organized by the company behind the card game [[Exploding Kittens]] for May was canceled.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/09/event-canceled-at-oregon-convention-center-amid.html|title=Event canceled at Oregon Convention Center|last=|first=|date=March 9, 2020|newspaper=Portland Business Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, the newspaper [[Portland Mercury]] announced it was suspending print publications until further notice due to the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/14/28141336/the-mercury-is-temporarily-switching-to-online-only|title=The Mercury Is Temporarily Switching to Online Only|website=Portland Mercury|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, restrictions prompted the closures of amusement parks, barber shops, bowling alleys, gyms, hair and nail salons, malls, spas, and theaters.<ref name=Lillard>{{Cite web|last=Nemec|first=Andrew|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/blazers/2020/03/damian-lillard-joins-nba-instagram-encourages-social-distancing-staying-home-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Damian Lillard joins NBA Instagram, encourages social distancing, staying home amid coronavirus outbreak|date=March 23, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323232851/https://www.oregonlive.com/blazers/2020/03/damian-lillard-joins-nba-instagram-encourages-social-distancing-staying-home-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Film industry and the performing arts====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n{{multiple image\n | width = 200\n | image1 = Bagdad Theater, Portland Oregon, during coronavirus closure.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | image2 = Businesses closed in Portland because of Coronavirus .jpeg\n | alt2 = \n | footer = [[Bagdad Theatre]] (left) and [[Laurelhurst Theater]] (right) with marquee messages acknowledging closures because of the pandemic  \n}}\n\nLocal movie theaters were forced to close temporarily. Among them were [[Cinema 21]] and [[Laurelhurst Theater]],<ref name=Venues/> which was unable to continue operating with capacity limits and social distancing measures, despite efforts.<ref name=Open/> On March 13, the [[Hollywood Theatre (Portland, Oregon)|Hollywood Theatre]] confirmed plans to close from March 14 to April 8; previously, the theater was limiting capacity to 250 people per Oregon's ban on events and other social gatherings.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=https://www.wweek.com/arts/movies/2020/03/13/portlands-hollywood-theatre-will-close-until-april-8/|title=Portland's Hollywood Theatre Will Close Until April 8|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323231117/https://www.wweek.com/arts/movies/2020/03/13/portlands-hollywood-theatre-will-close-until-april-8/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Movie Madness Video]], a [[video rental shop]] and [[history of film]] museum, closed and waived late fees on rentals.<ref name=Open/> Cinema 21 later allowed people to stream independent films at home.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Cook|first=Katherine|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/entertainment/local-theaters-let-customers-stream-independent-films-from-home/283-d3c31d70-3985-4ed4-8047-284195efcc54|title=Local theaters let customers stream independent films from home|date=March 30, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=Apr 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401211940/https://www.kgw.com/article/entertainment/local-theaters-let-customers-stream-independent-films-from-home/283-d3c31d70-3985-4ed4-8047-284195efcc54|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Arlene Schnitzer Concert Hall]] and Brunish Theatre at [[Antoinette Hatfield Hall]] closed,<ref name=Venues>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-response-public-venues-omsi-childrens-museum-ohs-close-for-2-weeks.html|title=Oregon closures: Libraries, recreation centers, museums, ski resorts, zoo, retailers|first=Rosemarie|last=Stein|date=March 13, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323150627/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-response-public-venues-omsi-childrens-museum-ohs-close-for-2-weeks.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> forcing the [[Oregon Symphony]] to cancel performances.<ref name=Rogoway/> Initially, the symphony canceled performances between March 13 and April 6.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/12/oregon-symphony-cancels-march-early-april-shows.html|title=Oregon Symphony cancels March, Early April shows|date=March 12, 2020|newspaper=Portland Business Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> 76 musicians, two conductors, and 19 staff members were laid off, and the organization's [[President (corporate title)|president]] and [[chief executive officer]] has submitted an appeal for funding to Governor Brown.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-symphony-lays-off-orchestra-conductors-and-staff-amid-coronavirus-crisis.html |title=Oregon Symphony lays off orchestra, conductors and staff amid coronavirus crisis |first=Nathan |last=Rizzo |date=March 20, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324045834/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-symphony-lays-off-orchestra-conductors-and-staff-amid-coronavirus-crisis.html |archive-date=March 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Portland Center Stage]] canceled productions for eight weeks (through April 8) and furloughed 78 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/radio/article/coronavirus-fears-affect-oregons-biggest-arts-organizations/|title=Coronavirus Closures Endanger Oregon's Most Prominent Arts Organizations|first1=Steven|last1=Tonthat|first2=Eric|last2=Slade|publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324045832/https://www.opb.org/radio/article/coronavirus-fears-affect-oregons-biggest-arts-organizations/|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Portland Opera]] canceled March 20\u201328 performances of ''[[Bajazet (opera)|Bajazet]]'' at Antoinette Hatfield Hall's Newmark Theatre.<ref name=Stein/> The arts center [[Disjecta]] canceled or postponed activities.<ref name=Stein/> The [[Northwest Film Center]] closed and the Portland International Film Festival was canceled.<ref name=Open/> [[The Old Church (Portland, Oregon)|The Old Church]] has postponed concerts through April 8, forcing [[Chamber Music Northwest]] to reschedule some performances.<ref name=Stein/>\n\n====Food service and restaurant industry====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry}}\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry in the United States}}\n[[File:Businesses closed in Portland because of Coronavirus16 13 59 290000.jpeg|thumb|left|Sign noting [[Screen Door (restaurant)|Screen Door]]'s closure]]\n\nThe city's restaurant industry was \"completely obliterated\" by the state's bar and restaurant ban.<ref name=Rogoway>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-brings-oregon-a-sudden-economic-catastrophe-the-worst-week-ever.html|title=Coronavirus brings Oregon a sudden economic catastrophe: 'The worst week ever'|first=Mike|last=Rogoway|date=March 22, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323094044/https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-brings-oregon-a-sudden-economic-catastrophe-the-worst-week-ever.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Governor Brown banned in-house consumption across Oregon, effective March 17. Some restaurants closed entirely, while others implemented [[food delivery]] and [[take-out]] operations.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/dining/2020/03/responding-to-coronavirus-pandemic-vegan-fine-dining-restaurant-farm-spirit-upscale-steakhouse-el-gaucho-will-close-temporarily.html |title=Portland restaurants close dining rooms; some offer delivery |first=Michael |last=Russell |date=March 13, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323150658/https://www.oregonlive.com/dining/2020/03/responding-to-coronavirus-pandemic-vegan-fine-dining-restaurant-farm-spirit-upscale-steakhouse-el-gaucho-will-close-temporarily.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Closures>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/13/21178995/covid-19-coronavirus-closures-portland|title=A Number of Restaurants Once Open for Takeout and Delivery Have Closed List Last Week|first=Brooke|last=Jackson-Glidden|date=March 13, 2020|website=[[Eater (website)|Eater Portland]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323144522/https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/13/21178995/covid-19-coronavirus-closures-portland|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Acadia: A New Orleans Bistro]], [[Doug Fir Lounge]], [[Ken's Artisan Pizza]], [[Le Bistro Montage]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/dining/2020/03/portland-restaurants-closed-due-to-coronavirus.html |title=Here are all the Portland restaurants to close or embrace takeout, delivery-only service |first=Michael |last=Russell |date=March 14, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323150704/https://www.oregonlive.com/dining/2020/03/portland-restaurants-closed-due-to-coronavirus.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Le Pigeon]], [[Nostrana (restaurant)|Nostrana]], [[Olympia Provisions]], [[Pok Pok]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/25/21194167/pok-pok-closed|title=The Pok Pok Empire Closes Indefinitely in Wake of Coronavirus Crisis|first=Alex|last=Frane|date=March 25, 2020|website=Eater Portland|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325210015/https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/25/21194167/pok-pok-closed|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/how-to-make-pok-poks-fish-sauce-wings-at-home.html|title=With Pok Pok restaurants closed, here's how to make those famous fish sauce wings at home|first=Michael|last=Russell|date=March 26, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327172445/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/how-to-make-pok-poks-fish-sauce-wings-at-home.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Screen Door (restaurant)|Screen Door]] all closed.<ref name=Closures/> [[Hot Lips Pizza]], [[Oven and Shaker]], and [[Sizzle Pie]] continued pizza pickup and delivery service, as of March 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/27/21194686/where-to-find-a-pizza-during-the-restaurant-shutdown|title=Where to Find a Pizza During the Restaurant Shutdown|first=Sam|last=Hill|date=March 27, 2020|website=Eater Portland|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327225926/https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/27/21194686/where-to-find-a-pizza-during-the-restaurant-shutdown|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Shine Distillery and Grill]] began producing [[hand sanitizer]] from alcohol for customers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2020/03/19/oregon-shine-distillery-making-hand-sanitizer-coronavirus-bts-ctn-vpx.cnn|title=Oregon distillery is making its own in-house hand sanitizer and giving it away|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323133625/https://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2020/03/19/oregon-shine-distillery-making-hand-sanitizer-coronavirus-bts-ctn-vpx.cnn|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Prewitt|first=Andi|url=https://www.wweek.com/bars/2020/03/10/a-portland-distillery-is-making-its-own-hand-cleaner-in-the-wake-of-coronavirus/|title=A Portland Distillery Is Making Its Own Hand Cleaner in the Wake of Coronavirus|date=March 10, 2020|work=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323043652/https://www.wweek.com/bars/2020/03/10/a-portland-distillery-is-making-its-own-hand-cleaner-in-the-wake-of-coronavirus/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-distillery-makes-hand-sanitizer-to-give-to-customers/article_c79023bc-6292-11ea-832b-e3a4b8d06435.html|title=Portland distillery makes hand sanitizer to give to customers|first=Audrey|last=Weil|publisher=KPTV|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318141255/https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-distillery-makes-hand-sanitizer-to-give-to-customers/article_c79023bc-6292-11ea-832b-e3a4b8d06435.html|archive-date=2020-03-18|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/11/21174997/shine-distillery-hand-cleaning-solution|title=North Portland's Shine Distillery Is Giving Away House-Made, 80-Percent-Alcohol Hand 'Cleaner'|first=Brooke|last=Jackson-Glidden|date=March 11, 2020|website=Eater Portland|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323043653/https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/11/21174997/shine-distillery-hand-cleaning-solution|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The website 'PDX2Go' was created to track businesses still accepting orders, and some food carts continued to operate.<ref name=Open/> The Liberty Glass, a bar and \"neighborhood institution\" in north Portland, closed permanently in mid April \"due to COVID-19-related financial concerns\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frane |first1=Alex |title=North Portland Bar Liberty Glass, a Neighborhood Institution, Will Permanently Close |url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/4/17/21225721/liberty-glass-closes-coronavirus |website=Eater Portland |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwelve of 27 laid off [[Crush Bar]] employees staged a protest and accused the owner of \"[breaking] the law by denying their use of accrued sick hours to cover lost wages\". The demonstration was supposed to last for 24 hours but was stopped by police after an hour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/17/21184325/crush-bar-sit-in-layoffs-covid-19|title=Crush Bar Employees Staged Sit-In After Mass Layoffs [Updated]|first=Alex|last=Frane|date=March 17, 2020|website=Eater Portland|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323144519/https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/17/21184325/crush-bar-sit-in-layoffs-covid-19|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[strip club]] Lucky Devil Lounge continued to offer a full menu with home delivery service by \"scantily clad strippers\" under the business operation Boober Eats.<ref name=Lucky>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-strip-club-forced-to-close-so-dancers-now-do-delivery.html|title=Portland strip club forced to close, so dancers now do delivery|first=Samantha|last=Swindler|date=March 22, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323190325/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-strip-club-forced-to-close-so-dancers-now-do-delivery.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wweek.com/bars/2020/03/17/a-portland-strip-club-has-started-a-meal-delivery-service-where-dancers-bring-food-directly-to-your-door-to-your-home/|title=A Portland Strip Club Has Started a Meal Delivery Service Where Dancers Bring Food Directly to Your Door|work=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323131431/https://www.wweek.com/bars/2020/03/17/a-portland-strip-club-has-started-a-meal-delivery-service-where-dancers-bring-food-directly-to-your-door-to-your-home/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/23/strippers-staff-boober-eats-delivery-service-during-coronavirus-lockdown/|title=Strippers staff 'Boober Eats' delivery service during coronavirus lockdown|first=Hannah|last=Sparks|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323204932/https://nypost.com/2020/03/23/strippers-staff-boober-eats-delivery-service-during-coronavirus-lockdown/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Approximately 25 strippers have participated; dancers are driven and protected by security guards, armed with gloves, masks, and hand sanitizer,<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/boober-eats-lucky-devil-lounge-strip-club-covid-19-coronavirus-quarantine-971544/|title=With Clubs Closed for COVID-19, Strippers in Portland, Oregon, Take to Topless Food Delivery|first1=E. J.|last1=Dickson|first2=E. J.|last2=Dickson|date=March 23, 2020|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323224406/https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/boober-eats-lucky-devil-lounge-strip-club-covid-19-coronavirus-quarantine-971544/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and touching by customers is not allowed.<ref name=Lucky/>\n\n====Hospitality industry====\nThe [[hospitality industry]] also experienced a wave of guest cancellations followed by a decline in bookings.<ref name=Hotels/> The [[Jupiter Hotel (Portland, Oregon)|Jupiter Hotel]] laid off half its staff by March 18 after daily occupancy rates fell to 7\u201320 percent.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-hotels-lay-off-workers-question-survival-after-wave-of-coronavirus-cancellations.html |title=Oregon hotels lay off workers, question futures after wave of coronavirus cancellations |first=Jamie |last=Goldberg |date=March 19, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323225544/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-hotels-lay-off-workers-question-survival-after-wave-of-coronavirus-cancellations.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Jupiter partnered with Multnomah County to use the hotel's 81 rooms as a temporary homeless shelter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pamplinmedia.com/go/42-news/459054-373887-portlands-jupiter-hotel-becomes-coronavirus-shelter-for-medically-fragile-homeless-people|title=Portland's Jupiter Hotel becomes coronavirus shelter for medically fragile homeless people|first=Molly|last=Harbarger|date=March 26, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327170944/https://pamplinmedia.com/go/42-news/459054-373887-portlands-jupiter-hotel-becomes-coronavirus-shelter-for-medically-fragile-homeless-people|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katu.com/news/local/portland-hotel-donates-rooms-to-help-homeless-with-coronavirus-symptoms-stay-in-quarantine|title=Portland hotel donates rooms to help homeless with coronavirus symptoms stay in quarantine|first=KATU|last=Staff|date=March 26, 2020|website=KATU|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327170950/https://katu.com/news/local/portland-hotel-donates-rooms-to-help-homeless-with-coronavirus-symptoms-stay-in-quarantine|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Hanson|first=Nate|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/homeless/jupiter-hotel-homeless-shelter-portland-coronavirus/283-370d4b13-f607-4460-98ed-6a6d5465d83d|title=Jupiter Hotel in Portland to become homeless shelter during coronavirus pandemic|date=March 26, 2020|publisher=KGW|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327170943/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/homeless/jupiter-hotel-homeless-shelter-portland-coronavirus/283-370d4b13-f607-4460-98ed-6a6d5465d83d|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[The Nines (hotel)|The Nines]] suspended hotel and restaurant operations on March 19, effective March 22.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-luxury-hotel-nines-suspends-services-due-to-covid/article_6b47548a-6a40-11ea-adb7-4f0a8a298283.html|title=Portland luxury hotel Nines suspends services due to COVID-19|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324141326/https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-luxury-hotel-nines-suspends-services-due-to-covid/article_6b47548a-6a40-11ea-adb7-4f0a8a298283.html|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Hyatt Regency Portland]], which opened in December 2019, also suspended operations in March.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/14/business/convention-hotels-municipal-bonds-coronavirus.html</ref> In early April, Travel Portland reported approximately 80 percent decreases in the demand for lodging, revenue, and occupancy rates in Portland compared to last year.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/hotel-demand-in-portland-down-roughly-80-percent-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html</ref> The president of Provenance Hotels, which owns or manages six hotels in Portland, left the company in mid April because of the pandemic.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/04/bashar-wali-to-leave-provenance-hotels-covid-19-convinced-him-to-change-course.html</ref>\n\n====Impact on professional sports====\n[[File:Providence Park box office notice - closed due to COVID-19 epidemic, 3-16-2020.jpg|thumb|Box office closure sign at [[Providence Park]], home of the [[Portland Timbers]] and [[Portland Thorns FC]], on March 16, 2020]]\n\nFollowing season suspensions by the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/local/mls-suspends-season-due-to-coronavirus-delaying-timbers-season|title=MLS suspends season due to coronavirus, delaying Timbers season|first=Evan|last=Schreiber|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=KATU|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324024859/https://katu.com/news/local/mls-suspends-season-due-to-coronavirus-delaying-timbers-season|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] and [[Portland Timbers]] canceled games.<ref name=Rogoway/> The Trail Blazers and Timbers games averaged approximately 19,000 and 25,000 people at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/service-industry-portland-coronavirus-nba-mls-moda-center/|title=Portland Service Industry Reeling And Uncertain With NBA, MLS On Hold|first1=Troy|last1=Brynelson|first2=Bradley W.|last2=Parks|date=March 16, 2020|publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323131406/https://www.opb.org/news/article/service-industry-portland-coronavirus-nba-mls-moda-center/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> MLS initially announced a 30-day suspension, when the Timbers were scheduled to play at [[Providence Park]] five times between March 12 and mid April.<ref name=NBC>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/portland-timbers/breaking-mls-suspends-season-due-coronavirus|title=BREAKING: MLS suspends season due to coronavirus|date=March 12, 2020|website=NBC Sports Northwest|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324024538/https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/portland-timbers/breaking-mls-suspends-season-due-coronavirus|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The soccer league extended the suspension to eight weeks on March 19.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Goldberg|first=Jamie|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/major-league-soccer-extends-season-postponement-for-another-month/283-d59a5f0d-0416-4929-893e-73399e61476f|title=Major League Soccer extends season postponement for another month|date=March 19, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324025836/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/major-league-soccer-extends-season-postponement-for-another-month/283-d59a5f0d-0416-4929-893e-73399e61476f|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Portland Thorns FC]]'s pre-season tournament slated for March 29 \u2013 April 4 was canceled on March 12, shortly before the [[National Women's Soccer League]] canceled pre-season games across the league.<ref name=Thorns>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/portland-thorns/2020/03/portland-thorns-cancel-preseason-tournament-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Thorns cancel preseason tournament amid coronavirus outbreak|first=Jamie|last=Goldberg|date=March 12, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324025317/https://www.oregonlive.com/portland-thorns/2020/03/portland-thorns-cancel-preseason-tournament-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Timbers and Thorns tickets will be valid for rescheduled matches, as of March 12.<ref name=Thorns/> On March 17, the Timbers and Thorns announced part-time workers would still receive compensation for canceled games, among other community initiatives.<ref>{{Cite news|author=KGW Staff|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/portland-timbers-thorns-to-pay-part-time-workers/283-ae77774b-161a-4b19-9699-266bd9ef8e26|title=Portland Timbers, Thorns to pay part-time workers for games missed during coronavirus outbreak|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324025854/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/portland-timbers-thorns-to-pay-part-time-workers/283-ae77774b-161a-4b19-9699-266bd9ef8e26|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Damian Lillard]] encouraged fans to remain at home and practice social distancing. He said on the NBA's [[Instagram]] account on March 23, \"I've been washing my hands, social distancing \u2014 keep your space. Don't join in crowds, stay in small groups. It'd be best to stay in the house. I hope everybody is stocked up on everything they need so they can stay safe. Do everything the way we've been asked to help this pass faster. Like I said, ya'll stay safe, ya'll be good, man.\"<ref name=Lillard/>\n\n==Impact on education==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education}}\n[[File:Portland, Oregon during the coronavirus pandemic, March 2020 - 05.jpg|thumb|Sign noting [[Reed College]]'s closure]]\n\nGovernor Brown initially closed schools all K\u201312 schools through March 31.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/portland-metro-school-district-tigard-tualatin-lake-oswego-coronavirus-board-meeting-emergency-covid-students/|title=Brown orders all K-12 schools closed through March|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323210338/https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/portland-metro-school-district-tigard-tualatin-lake-oswego-coronavirus-board-meeting-emergency-covid-students/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A four-week extension was added; students are scheduled to return on April 28. [[Portland Public Schools (Oregon)|Portland Public Schools]] designated 15 buildings as sites for student meal distributions, and has considered providing 45,000 devices to students for [[distance education]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-public-schools-begins-plans-for-6-week-closure.html|title=Portland Public Schools begins plans for 6-week closure|first=Eder|last=Campuzano|date=March 18, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323131440/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-public-schools-begins-plans-for-6-week-closure.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> High school and college graduation ceremonies were canceled.<ref name=Rogoway/> On April 8, Brown extended the school closures through to the end of the 2019\u20132020 school year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katu.com/news/local/oregon-gov-brown-addresses-education-issues-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Oregon Gov. Brown Addresses Education Issues Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|archive-date=April 8, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAll Multnomah County Library branches were closed on March 13.<ref name=MCL/> The library system waived late fees and continued to provide public [[Wi-Fi]].<ref name=Open/>\n\nStudents at [[Oregon Health & Science University]] and the University of Portland began offering childcare and errand services for local health care professionals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-area-healthcare-workers-can-request-free-childcare-other-support-from-local-medical-and-nursing-students.html|title=Portland-area healthcare workers can request free childcare, other support from local medical and nursing students|first=Amy|last=Wang|date=March 21, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323181637/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-area-healthcare-workers-can-request-free-childcare-other-support-from-local-medical-and-nursing-students.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Universities and collegiate sports===\n[[Portland State University]] canceled in-person final exams,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/schools/2020/03/12/portland-state-university-cancels-in-person-final-exams-moves-spring-classes-online/|title=Portland State University Cancels In-Person Final Exams, Moves Spring Classes Online|last=Mesh|first=Aaron|last2=|first2=|date=March 12, 2020|newspaper=Willamette Week|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313034235/https://www.wweek.com/news/schools/2020/03/12/portland-state-university-cancels-in-person-final-exams-moves-spring-classes-online/|archive-date=March 13, 2020|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=|first3=}}</ref> and eliminated in-person classes for the spring term, opting for distance learning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-state-university-will-not-resume-in-person-classes-this-spring.html|title=Portland State will not resume in-person classes this spring|last=Goldberg|first=Jamie|date=March 19, 2020|newspaper=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325150842/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-state-university-will-not-resume-in-person-classes-this-spring.html|archive-date=March 25, 2020|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The [[University of Portland]] moved to online instruction and canceled all sports games and practices for the spring term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/university-of-oregon-classes-remotely-coronavirus/283-b5b5abc3-463f-442a-abc6-964fb9036d54|title=UO, OSU, PSU, UP to cancel in-person classes amid coronavirus outbreak|publisher=KGW|access-date=2020-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313070840/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/university-of-oregon-classes-remotely-coronavirus/283-b5b5abc3-463f-442a-abc6-964fb9036d54|archive-date=2020-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/pilots/2020/03/university-of-portland-pilots-cancel-all-future-spring-sports-events-activities-due-to-coronavirus.html|title=University of Portland Pilots cancel all future spring sports events, activities due to coronavirus|last=Brown|first=Tim|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401233443/https://www.oregonlive.com/pilots/2020/03/university-of-portland-pilots-cancel-all-future-spring-sports-events-activities-due-to-coronavirus.html|archive-date=April 1, 2020|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> [[Lewis and Clark College]], [[Linfield College]], and [[Willamette University]] also implemented distance learning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/university-of-portland-willamette-cancel-in-person-classes-latest-colleges-to-shift-amid-coronavirus-concerns.html|title=University of Portland, Willamette, Lewis & Clark, Linfield cancel in-person classes amid coronavirus concerns|last=Davis|first=Rob|date=March 12, 2020|newspaper=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404102829/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/university-of-portland-willamette-cancel-in-person-classes-latest-colleges-to-shift-amid-coronavirus-concerns.html|archive-date=April 4, 2020|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on public transit==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on public transport}}\n[[File:Coronavirus physical-distancing sticker on door of a MAX light rail car.jpg|thumb|Sticker on the glass of a door of a TriMet MAX Light Rail car encouraging physical distancing on board]]\n[[File:TriMet bus with seats marked by \"Don't sit here\" signs during coronavirus pandemic, April 2020.jpg|thumb|Signs in a [[TriMet]] bus promoting physical distancing during a temporary 10-passenger limit imposed in April]]\n\nOn March 5, 2020, workers of the Portland area's regional transit agency, [[TriMet]], began nightly disinfections of the interior surfaces of its buses, [[MAX Light Rail]] and [[WES Commuter Rail]] trains, and LIFT [[paratransit]] vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/05/amid-coronavirus-fear-trimet-begins-nightly-wipedown-of-bus-and-train-doors/ |last=Mesh |first=Aaron |title=Amid Coronavirus Fear, TriMet Begins Nightly Wipedown of Bus and Train Doors |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |date=March 5, 2020 |access-date=March 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306232656/https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/05/amid-coronavirus-fear-trimet-begins-nightly-wipedown-of-bus-and-train-doors/ |archive-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Prevent>{{cite news |url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/what-pdx-trimet-and-others-are-doing-to-keep-customers-staff-safe-from-coronavirus/283-c1d5be93-c504-41f4-91a1-5468534eba33 |last=Cowley |first=Jared |title=What PDX, TriMet and others are doing to prevent the spread of coronavirus |publisher=[[KGW]] |date=March 11, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325030145/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/what-pdx-trimet-and-others-are-doing-to-keep-customers-staff-safe-from-coronavirus/283-c1d5be93-c504-41f4-91a1-5468534eba33 |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later on March 19, TriMet reported a significant decrease in ridership; approximately 140,000 fewer people rode TriMet vehicles compared to the weekday average in February.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/commuting/2020/03/trimet-is-not-cutting-service-yet-but-everything-is-on-the-table-amid-coronavirus-fears.html |last=Theen |first=Andrew |title=TriMet is not cutting service yet, but 'everything is on the table' amid coronavirus fears |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323131256/https://www.oregonlive.com/commuting/2020/03/trimet-is-not-cutting-service-yet-but-everything-is-on-the-table-amid-coronavirus-fears.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/trimet-sees-decrease-in-ridership-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ |last1=Powell |first1=Meerah |last2=Vance |first2=Bryan M. |title=TriMet Sees Decrease In Ridership Amid Coronavirus Outbreak |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323163842/https://www.opb.org/news/article/trimet-sees-decrease-in-ridership-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 28, the agency announced reductions to its services.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://katu.com/news/local/trimet-to-adjust-schedules-because-of-steep-drop-in-ridership |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=TriMet to adjust schedules because of steep drop in ridership |publisher=[[KATU]] |date=March 28, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329055217/https://katu.com/news/local/trimet-to-adjust-schedules-because-of-steep-drop-in-ridership |archive-date=March 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Effective April 5, MAX trains began running every 15{{nbsp}}minutes while WES trains ran every 45{{nbsp}}minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/trimet-reduces-train-and-bus-service/ |last=Powell |first=Meerah |title=TriMet Reduces Train, Bus Service In Response To Decreased Ridership |publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting |date=March 28, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328210920/https://www.opb.org/news/article/trimet-reduces-train-and-bus-service/ |archive-date=March 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> 84 bus lines saw schedule changes and the 272\u2013PDX Night Bus route was suspended.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/alerts/reducedservice.htm |title=Reduced Service |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329202724/https://trimet.org/alerts/reducedservice.htm |archive-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ptld-trib-trimet-reductions\">{{cite news |last1=Redden |first1=Jim |title=TriMet: Service reductions take effect Sunday |url=https://pamplinmedia.com/pt/9-news/460992-374755-trimet-service-reductions-take-effect-sunday |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |work=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>  On its website,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/health/ |title=COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Updates |publisher=[[TriMet]] |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325062205/https://trimet.org/health/ |archive-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> TriMet requested the public to \"maintain six feet of distance from other riders and the operator\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/19/28168598/fewer-riders-more-cleaning-heightened-uncertainty-how-are-trimet-employees-managing-the-covid-19-outbreak |last=Stenvick |first=Blair |title=Fewer Riders, More Cleaning, Heightened Uncertainty: How Are TriMet Employees Managing the COVID-19 Outbreak? |newspaper=[[Portland Mercury]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130807/https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/19/28168598/fewer-riders-more-cleaning-heightened-uncertainty-how-are-trimet-employees-managing-the-covid-19-outbreak |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The agency also asked people to \"only take transit if necessary\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/23/trimet-please-only-take-transit-if-necessary.html |last=Danko |first=Pete |title=TriMet: 'Please only take transit if necessary' |newspaper=[[Portland Business Journal]] |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 26, TriMet temporarily stopped accepting cash payment of fares on buses, asking all riders to pay with the [[Hop Fastpass]] system, so as to minimize the time that boarding passengers spend near the driver.<ref name=\"WW-TriMet-No-Cash-Buses\">{{cite news |last1=Mesh |first1=Aaron |title=TriMet Will No Longer Accept Cash Fares on Buses |url=https://www.wweek.com/news/city/2020/03/26/trimet-will-not-longer-accept-cash-fares-on-buses/ |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |work=[[Willamette Week]] |date=March 26, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327205626/https://www.wweek.com/news/city/2020/03/26/trimet-will-not-longer-accept-cash-fares-on-buses/ |archivedate=March 27, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On April 9, the agency indefinitely imposed a temporary limit of 10 passengers per bus, or up to 15 if including family members traveling together, and began installing signs on bus seats to enforce this physical distancing.<ref name=\"don't sit here signs\">{{cite news |last1=Theen |first1=Andrew |title=TriMet placing \u2018don\u2019t sit here\u2019 signs on bus seats, limiting passengers to 15 per bus |work=The Oregonian |date=April 2, 2020<!--(print edition of April 3, p. A10)--> |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/commuting/2020/04/coronavirus-in-oregon-trimet-to-place-dont-sit-here-signs-on-bus-seats-no-more-than-15-passengers-allowed.html |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther transit agencies across the region have adopted similar measures, as well as measures to assist community members in need. On March 19, [[South Metro Area Regional Transit]] (SMART) buses in [[Wilsonville, Oregon|Wilsonville]] began temporarily operating fare-free in support of transit-dependent commuters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ridesmart.com/transit/page/temporary-free-rides-all-smart-routes |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Temporary FREE RIDES on all SMART Routes |publisher=[[South Metro Area Regional Transit]] |date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325065703/https://www.ridesmart.com/transit/page/temporary-free-rides-all-smart-routes |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2020|3|24|df=us}}, SMART services continue to operate without any schedule reductions.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ridesmart.com/transit/page/transit-covid-19-coronavirus-updates |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=TRANSIT COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Updates |publisher=South Metro Area Regional Transit |date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325065621/https://www.ridesmart.com/transit/page/transit-covid-19-coronavirus-updates |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 23, the [[Portland Streetcar]] reduced its regular weekday schedule from every 15{{nbsp}}minutes to every 20{{nbsp}}minutes in response to the statewide stay-at-home order.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/news/2020/03/streetcar-service-will-reduce-to-20-minute-headways-beginning-march-24 |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Streetcar Service Will Reduce to 20-Minute Headways Beginning March 24 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar]] |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325063529/https://portlandstreetcar.org/news/2020/03/streetcar-service-will-reduce-to-20-minute-headways-beginning-march-24 |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy March 2, the [[Port of Portland (Oregon)|Port of Portland]] had increased the rate of cleanings at the [[Portland International Airport]] and at marine centers. The [[port authority]] focus on information and pay stations, shuttle buses, and valet booths, following recommendations issued by the county and CDC, and made hand sanitizer available for people using ground transportation.<ref name=Prevent/> The [[taxicab]] company Radio Cab also improved cleaning procedures.<ref name=Prevent/>\n\n==Impact on religion==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\n[[File:Aletheia Bible Fellowship Web Sermons Only during Coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|Sign of a Portland church live streaming sermons]]\n\nSeveral Portland area churches, mosques, synagogues, and other places of worship canceled or elected to live stream services, including [[Congregation Neveh Shalom]] and the [[First Unitarian Church of Portland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/religious-and-faith-communities-continue-services-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Religious And Faith Communities Continue Services Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|first=Meerah|last=Powell|date=March 26, 2020|publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]]|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328200817/https://www.opb.org/news/article/religious-and-faith-communities-continue-services-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/if-you-are-worshipping-this-weekend-you-might-want-to-check-ahead.html|title=Coronavirus and church: If you are worshipping this weekend, you might want to check ahead|date=March 14, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324031632/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/if-you-are-worshipping-this-weekend-you-might-want-to-check-ahead.html|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Portland's Bridgetown Church began offering services online via [[Zoom Video Communications]]. The city's largest mosque, [[Masjid As-Saber]], suspended [[Friday prayer]]s and asked worshippers to stay at home.<ref name=Open/>\n\nArchbishop [[Alexander King Sample]] of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Portland in Oregon|Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Portland]] encouraged priests to \"be creative\" with regard to accessibility,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/14/world/churches-mosques-temples-coronavirus-spread/index.html|title=What churches, mosques and temples are doing to fight the spread of coronavirus|first=Daniel|last=Burke|date=March 14, 2020|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314232611/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/14/world/churches-mosques-temples-coronavirus-spread/index.html|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"issued directives for parishes to cancel any event over 250 people and encouraged those aged over 60 or with underlying medical issues to consider not attending Mass and dispensed them of the obligation\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.statesmanjournal.com/story/news/2020/03/13/oregon-coronavirus-school-closures-salem-keizer-public-schools/5040931002/|title=Coronavirus: Oregon schools close, doctors demand state action, warming shelter closed|first1=Whitney|last1=Woodworth|first2=Virginia|last2=Barreda|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=[[Statesman Journal]]|location=Salem, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Masses were canceled until April 14, which included Holy Week and Easter. Archbishop Sample said the announcement was \"by far one of the most difficult communications [he has] ever written\".<ref>{{cite news |title=PUBLIC MASSES HALTED TO SLOW VIRUS |url=https://catholicsentinel.org/Content/News/Local/Article/PUBLIC-MASSES-HALTED-TO-SLOW-VIRUS/2/35/39515 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Catholic Sentinel]] |publisher=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Portland in Oregon]] |date=March 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325010853/https://catholicsentinel.org/Content/News/Local/Article/PUBLIC-MASSES-HALTED-TO-SLOW-VIRUS/2/35/39515 |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[The Grotto]] has suspended Mass until March 31, but visitors are welcome to visit the outdoor sanctuary and Upper Gardens.<ref name=Stein/>\n\n==Crime==\nOn March 23, the [[Multnomah County Sheriff's Office]] said the crime rate for the month to date was lower than the rate for March 2019. The same office had announced that they're not booking misdemeanor arrests and giving out citations instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/20/ppb-will-not-take-misdemeanor-arrests-to-jail-during-covid-19-outbreak-to-avoid-overcrowding/|title=Portland Police Will Not Take Misdemeanor Arrests to Jail During the COVID-19 Outbreak, to Avoid Overcrowding|last=Riski|first=Tess|last2=|first2=|date=March 20, 2020|website=Willamette Week|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14|last3=|first3=|last4=|first4=|last5=|first5=|last6=}}</ref> The agency also reported lower jail bookings and moved some inmates at the Inverness Jail in northeast Portland into temporary dormitory-style housing to follow social distancing measures.<ref name=\"Crime\">{{cite news |last1=Heye |first1=Bob |title=Coronavirus and Crime: Jail releases, a rash of break-ins and one encouraging trend |url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/coronavirus-and-crime-jail-releases-a-rash-of-break-ins-and-one-encouraging-trend |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=KATU |agency=Sinclair Broadcast Group |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325010138/https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/coronavirus-and-crime-jail-releases-a-rash-of-break-ins-and-one-encouraging-trend |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[KATU]] reported on a string of business break-ins in the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]].<ref name=Crime/> The crisis group Call to Safety, which supports people experiencing [[domestic violence]], began receiving twice as many calls and more requests for shelter and other resources once stay-at-home orders were enforced.<ref name=\"domeshelter\">{{cite news |last1=Crombie |first1=Noelle |title=Calls to Oregon's domestic violence crisis lines spike amid coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/crime/2020/03/calls-to-oregons-domestic-violence-crisis-lines-spike-amid-coronavirus-crisis.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |publisher=Advance Local Media |date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325013354/https://www.oregonlive.com/crime/2020/03/calls-to-oregons-domestic-violence-crisis-lines-spike-amid-coronavirus-crisis.html |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Thousands of [[respirator]] masks valued at approximately $2,500 were stolen from the Rebuilding Center in north Portland in March. Some of the masks were recovered and donated to local hospitals.<ref name=Crime/><ref name=\"stealmask\">{{cite news |author1=Nexstar Media Wire |title=Thousands of stolen N95 masks recovered in Portland, donated |url=https://www.ksn.com/news/thousands-of-stolen-n95-masks-recovered-donated/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=KSN |date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325013354/https://www.ksn.com/news/thousands-of-stolen-n95-masks-recovered-donated/ |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In April, federal investigators seized 100 coronavirus test kits shipped from China to an apartment in Portland.<ref>https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/feds-intercept-100-coronavirus-test-kits-shipped-to-portland-apartment/283-7c78c97e-2267-46de-b2cd-7a49a11e70de</ref>\n\n== Healthcare industry ==\nThe local [[healthcare industry]] was significantly impacted by the pandemic. Governor Kate Brown has said non-emergency medical procedures can resume starting May 1.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/non-emergency-medical-procedures-can-resume-in-oregon-on-may-1-gov-kate-brown-says.html</ref> On March 27, Portland began nightly \"solidarity cheers\" to recognize health care and other frontline workers, similar to many other cities around the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-urges-nightly-solidarity-cheer-for-frontline-coronavirus-workers.html|title=Portland urges nightly solidarity cheer for frontline coronavirus workers|first=Everton|last=Bailey Jr|date=March 27, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328201448/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-urges-nightly-solidarity-cheer-for-frontline-coronavirus-workers.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Portland, Oregon}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.travelportland.com/about-us/covid-19/|title=COVID-19 and the Portland Community|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=Travel Portland}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Zielinski |first1=Alex |title=\"I hope everything I'm telling you isn't true\": A Portland Oncology Nurse On COVID-19 |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/21/28177144/i-hope-everything-im-telling-you-isnt-true-a-portland-oncology-nurse-on-covid-19 |work=Portland Mercury |date=March 21, 2020}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Oregon|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:2020 in Portland, Oregon|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Oregon]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Health in Oregon]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Portland, Oregon}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon\n| width =\n| image         = File:Coronavirus responses in Portland Oregon.jpeg\n| image_size    = \n| image_upright =\n| alt           =\n| caption       = Sign on a storefront in [[Portland, Oregon]], noting a temporary closure due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing coronavirus pandemic]]\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| map4 =\n| legend4 =\n| map5 =\n| legend5 =\n| disease = [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19)\n| virus_strain = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|Severe acute respiratory syndrome<br />coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2)\n| location = [[Portland, Oregon]]\n| first_case =\n| arrival_date = <!-- or | dates = -->\n| date = \n| origin =\n| type =\n| confirmed_cases =\n| active_cases =\n| suspected_cases =\n| severe_cases =\n| recovery_cases =\n| deaths =\n| territories =\n| total_ili =\n| website = {{URL|https://beta.portland.gov/novel-coronavirus-covid-19}}\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon''', is an ongoing viral pandemic of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). Efforts to prevent the virus spreading include event postponements and cancellations, and facility closures.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Coronavirus disease 2019|Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2}}\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oregon}}\n[[File:Ghost Hug chalk writing on Hawthorne during Coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|Chalk writing on a sidewalk in southeast Portland during the pandemic]]\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] is an ongoing [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The outbreak started in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]] province, [[China]], in December 2019. The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) declared the outbreak to be a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]] on 30 January 2020 and a pandemic on 11 March 2020.\n\nAs of {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date|editlink=|ref=no}}, more than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|conround|editlink=|ref=no}} cases of COVID-19 have been reported in more than 200 countries and territories, resulting in more than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|dround|editlink=|ref=no}} deaths.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}} More than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|recround|editlink=|ref=no}} people have recovered.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}}\n\nThe pandemic was first confirmed to have spread to the United States in January 2020. Cases have been confirmed in all fifty U.S. states, [[Washington, D.C.]], and all inhabited [[Territories of the United States|U.S. territories]] except [[American Samoa]].<ref name=\"mariana\">{{cite web|url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/28/saipan-confirms-two-covid-19-positive-cases/2932326001/|title=Saipan confirms two COVID-19 positive cases|date=March 28, 2020|website=samoanews.com|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330220357/https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/28/saipan-confirms-two-covid-19-positive-cases/2932326001/|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> {{As of|2020|03|31|df=US}}, the U.S. has the most confirmed active cases in the world and ranks third in the number of total deaths from the virus.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905173559/https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|archive-date=September 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The pandemic was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Oregon]] on February 28, 2020.\n\n==Cases==\nOregon's first presumptive case was announced in Portland on February 28, 2020. Governor [[Kate Brown]] spoke and the director of the [[Oregon Health Authority]] confirmed someone from [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]] who worked at Forest Hills Elementary School in [[Lake Oswego, Oregon|Lake Oswego]] was being treated at [[Hillsboro, Oregon|Hillsboro]]'s [[Kaiser Westside Medical Center]]. The [[Lake Oswego School District]] closed the school for cleaning.<ref name=\"first\">{{cite news |title=State officials announce first presumptive case of coronavirus in Oregon |url=https://www.kptv.com/news/state-officials-announce-first-presumptive-case-of-coronavirus-in-oregon/article_6ac26688-5a93-11ea-a0af-d346d4e06ef0.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[KPTV]] |date=February 28, 2020 |location=Portland, Oregon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304134326/https://www.kptv.com/news/state-officials-announce-first-presumptive-case-of-coronavirus-in-oregon/article_6ac26688-5a93-11ea-a0af-d346d4e06ef0.html |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"firstabc\">{{cite news |last1=Selsky |first1=Andrew |title=Oregon has 1st coronavirus case: elementary school employee |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/oregon-1st-coronavirus-case-elementary-school-employee-69298619 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |via=[[Associated Press]] |date=February 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229155313/https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/oregon-1st-coronavirus-case-elementary-school-employee-69298619 |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first case in [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] and fifteenth in Oregon was confirmed on March 10; the patient was treatment at the [[Veterans Affairs Medical Center (Oregon)|Veterans Affairs Medical Center]].<ref name=\"case15\">{{cite news |title=Oregon confirms 15th coronavirus case in state |url=https://www.registerguard.com/news/20200310/oregon-confirms-15th-coronavirus-case-in-state |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The Register-Guard]] |date=March 10, 2020 |location=Eugene, Oregon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320150843/https://www.registerguard.com/news/20200310/oregon-confirms-15th-coronavirus-case-in-state |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> An employee who worked at the [[Wells Fargo Center (Portland, Oregon)|Wells Fargo Center]] tested positive on March 14, prompting building tenant [[Davis Wright Tremaine]] to close offices in Portland.<ref name=\"skyscraper\">{{cite news |last1=Rogoway |first1=Mike |title=Coronavirus case linked to downtown Portland skyscraper |url=https://pamplinmedia.com/pt/9-news/456350-372216-coronavirus-case-linked-to-downtown-portland-skyscraper-pwoff |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316013205/https://pamplinmedia.com/pt/9-news/456350-372216-coronavirus-case-linked-to-downtown-portland-skyscraper-pwoff |archive-date=March 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> More than 30 people in the Portland metropolitan area tested positive by April 1.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/strong-evidence-seen-that-oregons-coronavirus-restrictions-are-working.html |title=\u2018Strong evidence\u2019 seen that Oregon\u2019s coronavirus restrictions are working |website=The Oregonian |date=April 1, 2020 |access-date=April 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401215612/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/strong-evidence-seen-that-oregons-coronavirus-restrictions-are-working.html |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Healthcare at Foster Creek nursing home in southeast Portland was Oregon's largest coronavirus death cluster, as of mid April, with 50 confirmed cases and 14 deaths. The [[Oregon Department of Human Services]] identified many safety violations.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/portland-nursing-home-reports-14-deaths-after-slew-of-coronavirus-violations.html</ref><ref>https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/oregon-coronavirus-nursing-home-14-deaths-safety-violations/283-b574e186-6a80-4430-80bc-fd45d1857319</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n{{Main|U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Multnomah County Library Northwest branch with closure notice during 2020 coronavirus epidemic.jpg|thumb|left|Closure notice posted at the [[Northwest Library]] on March 16, 2020]]\n\nOn March 13, the [[Portland Police Bureau]] announced a reduction of in-person responses to reduce virus transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kobi5.com/news/portland-police-reduce-in-person-responses-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-123900/|title=Portland police reduce in-person responses amid coronavirus outbreak|date=March 13, 2020|website=KOBI-TV NBC5 / KOTI-TV NBC2|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325013939/https://kobi5.com/news/portland-police-reduce-in-person-responses-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-123900/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/public-global-health/487984-police-nationwide-ask-criminals-to-halt-activity|title=Police nationwide ask criminals to halt activity during coronavirus outbreak|first=Justine|last=Coleman|date=March 17, 2020|website=TheHill|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325013923/https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/public-global-health/487984-police-nationwide-ask-criminals-to-halt-activity|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Multnomah County Library]] closed all branch libraries and [[Portland Parks and Recreation]] (PPR) closed arts and community centers, sports facilities, and swimming pools, based on recommendations issued by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], [[Multnomah County Health Department]], and the Oregon Health Authority. PPR canceled athletic programs and indoor activities at community centers, but did not close golf courses, natural areas, parks, playgrounds, or trails, or cancel outdoor events for less than 250 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/covid--closures-multnomah-county-libraries-some-portland-parks-rec/article_d56dbd54-659a-11ea-a9dc-637432f6280c.html|title=COVID-19 closures: Multnomah County libraries, some Portland Parks & Rec facilities shut down|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323150334/https://www.kptv.com/news/covid--closures-multnomah-county-libraries-some-portland-parks-rec/article_d56dbd54-659a-11ea-a9dc-637432f6280c.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Portland Police have received 469 reports of social distancing violation between March 25, and April 14, yet have issued zero citations. The police reasoned that it would overburden the criminal justice system and compared the enforcement to enforcing every traffic violation being reported<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/how-to-report-people-who-arent-social-distancing/283-a90abfa0-389c-4bd0-baee-4e3a171883dd|title='This really isn't social distancing': What to do if you come across social distance violators|last=|first=|date=April 15, 2020|website=KGW|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16|quote=in reporter's video. at 3m25s and in body}}</ref> In comparison, [[Manhattan Beach, California]] have issued 129 citations over a weekend in early April.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:Portland, Oregon during the coronavirus pandemic, March 2020 - 16.jpg|thumb|upright|COVID-19 sign on a  bus-stop shelter in [[Woodstock, Portland, Oregon|Woodstock]]]]\nOn March 17, Multnomah County Chair Deborah Kafoury announced plans to add as many as 400 beds for county residents affected by the pandemic requiring shelter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/multnomah-county-to-add-hundreds-of-homeless-shelter-beds-within-the-week-for-people-with-symptoms-of-coronavirus.html|title=Multnomah County to add hundreds of homeless shelter beds within the week to help with coronavirus|first=Molly|last=Harbarger|date=March 17, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323212540/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/multnomah-county-to-add-hundreds-of-homeless-shelter-beds-within-the-week-for-people-with-symptoms-of-coronavirus.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> 120 beds were made available at the PPR-owned [[Charles Jordan Community Center]] in north Portland on March 19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/first-coronavirus-related-emergency-homeless-shelter-to-open-in-north-portland.html|title=First coronavirus-related emergency homeless shelter to open in North Portland|first=Molly|last=Harbarger|date=March 19, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323212537/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/first-coronavirus-related-emergency-homeless-shelter-to-open-in-north-portland.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]]'s [[Oregon Convention Center]], unable to host events since March 12, was converted into a temporary shelter with 130\u2013140 beds. The Joint Office of Homeless Services, a collaboration between the City of Portland and Multnomah County, hoped to open additional beds for healthy individuals as overflow from existing shelters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/oregon-convention-center-shelter/283-3f46becb-f2fa-4865-9cc1-65b35c741085|title=Oregon Convention Center to become temporary coronavirus-related homeless shelter|publisher=[[KGW]]|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323212534/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/oregon-convention-center-shelter/283-3f46becb-f2fa-4865-9cc1-65b35c741085|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/homeless-will-find-refuge-at-oregon-convention-center/|title=Homeless will find refuge at Oregon Convention Center|date=March 20, 2020|publisher=[[KOIN (TV)|KOIN]]|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323222632/https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/homeless-will-find-refuge-at-oregon-convention-center/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Trucks normally used by Multnomah Country Library and for animal control were repurposed to assist with the convention center conversion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/tape-and-two-hours-to-transform-oregon-convention-center-into-coronavirus-homeless-shelter.html |title=Tape and 2 hours to transform Oregon Convention Center into coronavirus homeless shelter |first=Molly |last=Harbarger |date=March 21, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323221955/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/tape-and-two-hours-to-transform-oregon-convention-center-into-coronavirus-homeless-shelter.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nOn March 22, Mayor [[Ted Wheeler]] said he was prepared to issue a [[stay-at-home order]] for Portland residents if Governor Brown would not issue a similar order for Oregon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/wheeler-to-brown-issue-statewide-stay-at-home-order/|title=Wheeler to Brown: Issue statewide stay-at-home order|date=March 22, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134322/https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/wheeler-to-brown-issue-statewide-stay-at-home-order/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/mayor-wheeler-on-stay-at-home-order-im-ready-to-act-for-portland-tomorrow|title=Mayor Wheeler on stay-at-home order: 'I'm ready to act for Portland tomorrow'|date=March 22, 2020|publisher=[[KATU]]|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322235314/https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/mayor-wheeler-on-stay-at-home-order-im-ready-to-act-for-portland-tomorrow|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The governor was also pressured by 25 Portland-area mayors, Metro's council, multiple county chairs, and other elected and health officials. She issued an executive order on March 23 requiring home [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]] for Oregonians, with some exceptions, and to practice [[social distancing]]. Violators may be punished with 30 days in jail and fines as high as $1,250 as a class C [[misdemeanor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-stay-at-home-order-coronavirus-covid-19-kate-brown/|title=Gov. Kate Brown Issues Order Directing Oregonians To 'Stay Home'|first=Dirk|last=VanderHart|date=March 2, 2020|publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323202624/https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-stay-at-home-order-coronavirus-covid-19-kate-brown/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Portland Police Bureau confirmed criminal citations were a \"last resort measure\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/23/portland-police-can-now-issue-criminal-citations-to-those-who-violate-browns-stay-at-home-order/|title=Portland Police May Now Issue Criminal Citations to Anyone Who Violates Brown\u2019s Stay at Home Order|date=March 23, 2020|first1=Tess|last1=Riski|newspaper=Willamette Week|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324134348/https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/23/portland-police-can-now-issue-criminal-citations-to-those-who-violate-browns-stay-at-home-order/|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The police have issued a statement to the public to not call 911 to report violations of stay-at-home order, but to call the non-emergency line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-police-dont-call-911-to-report-people-violating-coronavirus-stay-home-order.html|title=Portland police: Don\u2019t call 911 to report people violating coronavirus stay-home order|last=Acker|first=Lizzy|date=2020-03-29|website=oregonlive|publisher=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nCity official extended the [[Portland Arts Tax]] deadline from April 15 to July 15, 2020.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-arts-tax-now-due-in-july-due-to-coronavirus-city-says.html</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n{{Main|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{See also|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Hand sanitizer and gloves sold out due to Coronavirus 10 57 26 366000.jpeg|thumb|right|Empty [[latex glove]] shelves at a [[Rite Aid]] store in [[downtown Portland]]]]\n\n[[Delta Air Lines]] reduced flights between Portland and Japan. United Airlines cut 4 of 20 flights from Portland as well as one from Eugene. [[Sun Country Airlines]] reduced flights between Portland and Honolulu, Las Vegas, and San Francisco.<ref name=Outlook>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-darkens-oregons-economic-outlook-but-impacts-are-muted-for-now.html |title=Coronavirus darkens Oregon's economic outlook, but impacts are muted -- for now |first=Mike |last=Rogoway |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312163905/https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-darkens-oregons-economic-outlook-but-impacts-are-muted-for-now.html |archive-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSchool closures and event cancellations prompted people to stock up on groceries. Long lines were seen at grocery stores and food pantries throughout the Portland metropolitan area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-grocery-stores-and-food-pantries-busy-as-covid-/article_67560a58-6656-11ea-b7d7-c3c87e0e2492.html|title=Portland grocery stores and food pantries busy as COVID-19 closures begin|first=John|last=Hendricks|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323145749/https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-grocery-stores-and-food-pantries-busy-as-covid-/article_67560a58-6656-11ea-b7d7-c3c87e0e2492.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Local [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] dispensaries saw an increased demand as customers stocked up in case stores were forced to close temporarily.<ref name=Open>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-portland-coronavirus-covid-19-whats-open/|title=Life In The Time Of Coronavirus: What's Still Open In Oregon?|first=Donald|last=Orr|date=March 19, 2020|publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324011921/https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-portland-coronavirus-covid-19-whats-open/|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Oregon Liquor Control Commission]] (OLCC) permitted stores to operate via curbside pick-up and home delivery temporarily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/weve-been-having-420-every-day-for-the-last-2-weeks-oregon-pot-shops-see-spike-in-business-with-new-curbside-delivery/283-163e563c-a5e4-4b2a-87e1-76578a607346|title=\u2018We\u2019ve been having 4/20 every day\u2019: Oregon pot shops see spike in business with new curbside delivery|website=KGW|access-date=2020-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327173032/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/weve-been-having-420-every-day-for-the-last-2-weeks-oregon-pot-shops-see-spike-in-business-with-new-curbside-delivery/283-163e563c-a5e4-4b2a-87e1-76578a607346|archive-date=2020-03-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/at-home-because-of-the-coronavirus-shutdown-heres-who-delivers-cannabis-products-in-portland.html|title=At home because of the coronavirus shutdown? Here's who delivers cannabis products in Portland|first=Lizzy|last=Acker|date=March 25, 2020|website=The Oregonian|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327173312/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/at-home-because-of-the-coronavirus-shutdown-heres-who-delivers-cannabis-products-in-portland.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186115/oregon-cannabis-dispensaries-now-allowed-to-offer-curbside-pickup|title=Oregon Cannabis Dispensaries Now Allowed to Offer Curbside Pickup|first1=Wm Steven|last1=Humphrey|date=March 23, 2020|work=Portland Mercury|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326153724/https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186115/oregon-cannabis-dispensaries-now-allowed-to-offer-curbside-pickup|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Beverage Container Redemption Center in Oregon .jpg|right|thumb|Long line of people queued up in front of the BottleDrop redemption center in East Portland in April 2020. ]]\n\nOLCC suspended the enforcement of the [[Oregon Bottle Bill]] on March 15 so that grocers can focus on restocking, sanitation and social distancing management. Grocers may elect to not accept bottle returns during this period. The Oregon Beverage Recycling Cooperative (OBRC) which operates Beverage container redemption centers throughout Oregon is keeping their centers open.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-grocers-close-bottle-drop-service-due-to-coronavirus-staffing-issues.html|title=Oregon grocers close bottle return service due to coronavirus staffing issues|last=Harbarger|first=Molly|date=March 18, 2020|website=oregonlive|publisher=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/olcc-extends-bottle-bill-reprieve-for-oregon-businesses-due-to-pandemic/article_39a30206-744c-11ea-b7b3-574ecfd6fa66.html|title=OLCC extends bottle bill reprieve for Oregon businesses due to pandemic|last=Staff|first=FOX 12|website=KPTV.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The enforcement suspension remains in effect until June 1, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/04/23/oregon-grocery-stores-dont-have-to-accept-returnable-cans-and-bottles-until-june-1/|title=Oregon Grocery Stores Don\u2019t Have to Accept Returnable Cans and Bottles Until June 1|last=Jaquiss|first=Nigel|date=April 23, 2020|website=Willamette Week|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> ''[[The Oregonian]]'' reported on April 23 that the City of Portland has been operating a bottle return site at an \"undisclosed site in North Portland\" based at one of the city's clinic that provides drug addicts with services such as clean syringes and opioid overdose antidote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/the-peoples-depot-is-portlands-semi-secret-bottle-return-program-to-help-those-impacted-by-state-bottle-bill-decision.html|title=The People\u2019s Depot is Portland\u2019s semi-secret bottle return program to help those impacted by state Bottle Bill decision|last=Harbarger|first=Molly|date=2020-04-23|website=oregonlive|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, Oregon temporarily lifted the prohibition on self-pump at gas stations at least until April 11 to ensure fuel is available during staffing issues related to the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/news/2020/03/oregon-temporarily-lifts-prohibition-on-self-service-gas-in-response-to-coronavirus.html|title=Oregon temporarily allows drivers to pump their own gas|last=Borrud|first=Hillary|date=2020-03-28|website=oregonlive|publisher=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n===Business closures and event cancellations===\n{{Main|List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Portland, Oregon during the coronavirus pandemic, March 2020 - 15.jpg|thumb|left|upright|People practicing social distancing while waiting to enter [[New Seasons Market]] in the [[Woodstock, Portland, Oregon|Woodstock]] neighborhood]]\n\n[[Adidas]] closed offices at Montgomery Park and Portland Village after two employees had close content with someone who tested positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/nba/adidas-closes-north-american-headquarters-amid-covid-19-pandemic|title=Adidas closes North American headquarters amid COVID-19 pandemic|date=March 12, 2020|website=NBC Sports Northwest|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151019/https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/nba/adidas-closes-north-american-headquarters-amid-covid-19-pandemic|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Powell's Books]] five stores closed,<ref name=Rogoway/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/local/powells-books-closes-as-coronavirus-spreads-in-portland-metro|title=Powell's Books closes as coronavirus spreads in Portland metro|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=KATU|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317193824/https://katu.com/news/local/powells-books-closes-as-coronavirus-spreads-in-portland-metro|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and laid off most staff members.<ref name=Open/> [[Portland Incubator Experiment]] canceled PIE Demo Day; the March 19 event scheduled to be held at [[Revolution Hall]] was held online.<ref name=Stein/> On March 25, [[Daimler Trucks North America]] shut down a plant on Swan Island until April 6.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/daimler-trucks-shutting-down-portland-plant-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Daimler Trucks shutting down Portland plant amid coronavirus outbreak|first=Mike|last=Rogoway|date=March 25, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327172243/https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/daimler-trucks-shutting-down-portland-plant-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Portland-based companies [[Puppet (company)|Puppet]] and [[Vacasa]] laid off employees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/silicon-forest/2020/03/portland-marketing-technology-startup-opal-lays-off-20-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Portland technology companies lay off dozens amid coronavirus outbreak|first=Mike|last=Rogoway|date=March 27, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328201124/https://www.oregonlive.com/silicon-forest/2020/03/portland-marketing-technology-startup-opal-lays-off-20-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In April, [[Evraz]] announced plans to lay off 230 employees at a Portland steel plant, and [[Precision Castparts Corp.]] confirmed plans to close its main Portland site.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/04/precision-castparts-will-shut-its-main-portland-site-coronavirus-latest-blow-to-oregons-economy.html</ref> \n\n[[Oaks Amusement Park]] and the [[Oaks Park Roller Skating Rink]], the [[Oregon Historical Society]], the [[Oregon Zoo]], [[Portland Children's Museum]],<ref name=Stein>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/event-cancellationspostponements-due-to-coronavirus-concerns.html|title=Events canceled in Oregon over the next months|first=Rosemarie|last=Stein|date=March 10, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323223733/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/event-cancellationspostponements-due-to-coronavirus-concerns.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Portland Japanese Garden]] closed as well.<ref name=Rogoway/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/list-portland-area-museums-attractions-closed-amid-coronavirus-response/|title=LIST: Portland area museums, attractions closed amid coronavirus response|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316131605/https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/list-portland-area-museums-attractions-closed-amid-coronavirus-response/|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of March 19, the [[Portland Art Museum]] and [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] are closed through March 31 and mid April, respectively.<ref name=Open/> The [[Crystal Ballroom (Portland, Oregon)|Crystal Ballroom]] and [[Hawthorne Theatre]] canceled or postponed planned shows through mid April.<ref name=Open/> The [[City Club of Portland]] canceled activities.<ref name=MCL>{{Cite news|last=Monahan|first=Rachel|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/city/2020/03/13/multnomah-county-library-closed-as-of-today-in-response-to-the-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Multnomah County Library Closed in Response to the Coronavirus Outbreak|date=March 13, 2020|work=[[Willamette Week]]|accessdate=April 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403220746/https://www.wweek.com/news/city/2020/03/13/multnomah-county-library-closed-as-of-today-in-response-to-the-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Portland Rose Festival]] has postponed annual events, including the [[Starlight Parade]], indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=https://www.wweek.com/arts/2020/03/19/the-portland-rose-festival-has-been-postponed-indefinitely/|title=The Portland Rose Festival Has Been Postponed Indefinitely|date=March 19, 2020|work=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323180902/https://www.wweek.com/arts/2020/03/19/the-portland-rose-festival-has-been-postponed-indefinitely/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/entertainment/2020/03/the-portland-rose-festival-has-been-postponed.html |title=The 2020 Portland Rose Festival has been postponed due to coronavirus crisis |first1=Rosemarie |last1=Stein |first2=Kjerstin |last2=Gabrielson |date=March 19, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323180907/https://www.oregonlive.com/entertainment/2020/03/the-portland-rose-festival-has-been-postponed.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Herbal Products Association]]'s Hemp-CBD Congress, scheduled for mid April at the [[Benson Hotel]], was canceled.<ref name=Stein/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/09/28113766/coronavirus-and-cannabis-how-pot-is-impacted-by-a-pandemic |title=Coronavirus and Cannabis: How Pot Is Impacted by a Pandemic |first1=Josh |last1=Jardine |date=March 9, 2020 |newspaper=[[Portland Mercury]] |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313032723/https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/09/28113766/coronavirus-and-cannabis-how-pot-is-impacted-by-a-pandemic |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Road Runners Club of America]]'s annual convention, slated to be held at the [[Hilton Portland Hotel]] during March 19\u201322, was also canceled.<ref name=Stein/> A conference on [[affordable housing]], climate, and community stability featuring [[Julian Castro]] during April 2\u20134 was canceled.<ref name=Stein/> [[TechfestNW]] was to be held at [[Portland State University]] during April 2\u20133, but was rescheduled for August 6\u20137. April 11's Cider Rite of Spring was rescheduled for November, and Design Week Festival was moved from the week starting April 18 to August 1\u20138. The arts and technology festival [[XOXO (festival)|XOXO]] scheduled for September has been canceled.<ref name=Stein/> [[Pride Northwest]]'s annual [[pride parade]] has been postponed, and the Portland Retro Gaming Expo has been canceled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186244/todays-coronavirus-news-roundup-brown-issues-stay-home-order-dems-slam-gop-stimulus-bill-and-trump-keeps-getting-in-the-way|title=Today's Coronavirus News Roundup: Brown Issues \"Stay Home\" Order, Dems Slam GOP Stimulus Bill, and Trump Keeps Getting in the Way|date=March 23, 2020|work=Portland Mercury|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324133621/https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186244/todays-coronavirus-news-roundup-brown-issues-stay-home-order-dems-slam-gop-stimulus-bill-and-trump-keeps-getting-in-the-way|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Waterfront Blues Festival]], slated for July 2\u20135, was canceled on March 25.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/waterfront-blues-festival-canceled-for-2020-will-return-in-2021.html|title=Waterfront Blues Festival canceled for 2020, will return in 2021|first=Samantha|last=Swindler|date=March 24, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325160751/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/waterfront-blues-festival-canceled-for-2020-will-return-in-2021.html|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=https://www.wweek.com/music/2020/03/24/the-waterfront-blues-festival-has-been-canceled-due-to-the-pandemic/|title=The Waterfront Blues Festival Has Been Canceled Due to the Pandemic|date=March 24, 2020|newspaper=Willamette Week|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325160755/https://www.wweek.com/music/2020/03/24/the-waterfront-blues-festival-has-been-canceled-due-to-the-pandemic/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/organizers-cancel-waterfront-blues-festival-over-coronavirus-concerns|title=Organizers cancel Waterfront Blues Festival over coronavirus concerns|author=KATU Staff|date=March 24, 2020|website=KATU|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325160751/https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/organizers-cancel-waterfront-blues-festival-over-coronavirus-concerns|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhile cheer and dance competitions were still being held at the Oregon Convention Center in early March,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/crowds-gather-at-convention-center-despite-virus-concerns/|title=Crowds gather at convention center despite virus concerns|date=March 7, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323224315/https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/crowds-gather-at-convention-center-despite-virus-concerns/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> many events planned to be hosted at the venue were canceled. On February 5, the Materials Show scheduled for February 12\u201313 was canceled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-trade-show-canceled-over-coronavirus-concerns/article_28d3fde8-4889-11ea-bcd6-8bb625985644.html|title=Portland trade show canceled over coronavirus concerns|date=February 5, 2020|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323223337/https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-trade-show-canceled-over-coronavirus-concerns/article_28d3fde8-4889-11ea-bcd6-8bb625985644.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://q13fox.com/2020/02/05/portland-convention-rescheduled-over-coronavirus-fears/|title=Portland convention rescheduled over coronavirus fears|date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206124911/https://q13fox.com/2020/02/05/portland-convention-rescheduled-over-coronavirus-fears/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Gem Faire and the Multnomah County Democrats' annual Celsi Celebration slated for the weekend of March 21 were also canceled.<ref name=Stein/> On March 6, organizers of the Go West Summit, an international travel conference for March 24\u201327 expecting approximately 800 people, was postponed.<ref name=Hotels>{{Cite news|last=Iboshi|first=Kyle|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/portland-hotels-see-significant-room-cancellations-travel-conference-postponed/283-6d3b08c3-7a8a-4b56-a65c-bac4919cd73d|title=Portland hotels see 'significant' room cancellations; travel conference postponed|date=March 6, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=April 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406020722/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/portland-hotels-see-significant-room-cancellations-travel-conference-postponed/283-6d3b08c3-7a8a-4b56-a65c-bac4919cd73d|archive-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Oregon Dental Association's annual Oregon Dental Conference for April 2\u20134 was canceled.<ref name=Stein/> On March 9, the Burning Cat event being organized by the company behind the card game [[Exploding Kittens]] for May was canceled.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/09/event-canceled-at-oregon-convention-center-amid.html|title=Event canceled at Oregon Convention Center|last=|first=|date=March 9, 2020|newspaper=Portland Business Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, the newspaper [[Portland Mercury]] announced it was suspending print publications until further notice due to the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/14/28141336/the-mercury-is-temporarily-switching-to-online-only|title=The Mercury Is Temporarily Switching to Online Only|website=Portland Mercury|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, restrictions prompted the closures of amusement parks, barber shops, bowling alleys, gyms, hair and nail salons, malls, spas, and theaters.<ref name=Lillard>{{Cite web|last=Nemec|first=Andrew|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/blazers/2020/03/damian-lillard-joins-nba-instagram-encourages-social-distancing-staying-home-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Damian Lillard joins NBA Instagram, encourages social distancing, staying home amid coronavirus outbreak|date=March 23, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323232851/https://www.oregonlive.com/blazers/2020/03/damian-lillard-joins-nba-instagram-encourages-social-distancing-staying-home-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Film industry and the performing arts====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n{{multiple image\n | width = 200\n | image1 = Bagdad Theater, Portland Oregon, during coronavirus closure.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | image2 = Businesses closed in Portland because of Coronavirus .jpeg\n | alt2 = \n | footer = [[Bagdad Theatre]] (left) and [[Laurelhurst Theater]] (right) with marquee messages acknowledging closures because of the pandemic  \n}}\n\nLocal movie theaters were forced to close temporarily. Among them were [[Cinema 21]] and [[Laurelhurst Theater]],<ref name=Venues/> which was unable to continue operating with capacity limits and social distancing measures, despite efforts.<ref name=Open/> On March 13, the [[Hollywood Theatre (Portland, Oregon)|Hollywood Theatre]] confirmed plans to close from March 14 to April 8; previously, the theater was limiting capacity to 250 people per Oregon's ban on events and other social gatherings.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=https://www.wweek.com/arts/movies/2020/03/13/portlands-hollywood-theatre-will-close-until-april-8/|title=Portland's Hollywood Theatre Will Close Until April 8|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323231117/https://www.wweek.com/arts/movies/2020/03/13/portlands-hollywood-theatre-will-close-until-april-8/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Movie Madness Video]], a [[video rental shop]] and [[history of film]] museum, closed and waived late fees on rentals.<ref name=Open/> Cinema 21 later allowed people to stream independent films at home.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Cook|first=Katherine|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/entertainment/local-theaters-let-customers-stream-independent-films-from-home/283-d3c31d70-3985-4ed4-8047-284195efcc54|title=Local theaters let customers stream independent films from home|date=March 30, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=Apr 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401211940/https://www.kgw.com/article/entertainment/local-theaters-let-customers-stream-independent-films-from-home/283-d3c31d70-3985-4ed4-8047-284195efcc54|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Arlene Schnitzer Concert Hall]] and Brunish Theatre at [[Antoinette Hatfield Hall]] closed,<ref name=Venues>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-response-public-venues-omsi-childrens-museum-ohs-close-for-2-weeks.html|title=Oregon closures: Libraries, recreation centers, museums, ski resorts, zoo, retailers|first=Rosemarie|last=Stein|date=March 13, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323150627/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-response-public-venues-omsi-childrens-museum-ohs-close-for-2-weeks.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> forcing the [[Oregon Symphony]] to cancel performances.<ref name=Rogoway/> Initially, the symphony canceled performances between March 13 and April 6.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/12/oregon-symphony-cancels-march-early-april-shows.html|title=Oregon Symphony cancels March, Early April shows|date=March 12, 2020|newspaper=Portland Business Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> 76 musicians, two conductors, and 19 staff members were laid off, and the organization's [[President (corporate title)|president]] and [[chief executive officer]] has submitted an appeal for funding to Governor Brown.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-symphony-lays-off-orchestra-conductors-and-staff-amid-coronavirus-crisis.html |title=Oregon Symphony lays off orchestra, conductors and staff amid coronavirus crisis |first=Nathan |last=Rizzo |date=March 20, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324045834/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-symphony-lays-off-orchestra-conductors-and-staff-amid-coronavirus-crisis.html |archive-date=March 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Portland Center Stage]] canceled productions for eight weeks (through April 8) and furloughed 78 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/radio/article/coronavirus-fears-affect-oregons-biggest-arts-organizations/|title=Coronavirus Closures Endanger Oregon's Most Prominent Arts Organizations|first1=Steven|last1=Tonthat|first2=Eric|last2=Slade|publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324045832/https://www.opb.org/radio/article/coronavirus-fears-affect-oregons-biggest-arts-organizations/|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Portland Opera]] canceled March 20\u201328 performances of ''[[Bajazet (opera)|Bajazet]]'' at Antoinette Hatfield Hall's Newmark Theatre.<ref name=Stein/> The arts center [[Disjecta]] canceled or postponed activities.<ref name=Stein/> The [[Northwest Film Center]] closed and the Portland International Film Festival was canceled.<ref name=Open/> [[The Old Church (Portland, Oregon)|The Old Church]] has postponed concerts through April 8, forcing [[Chamber Music Northwest]] to reschedule some performances.<ref name=Stein/>\n\n====Food service and restaurant industry====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry}}\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry in the United States}}\n[[File:Businesses closed in Portland because of Coronavirus16 13 59 290000.jpeg|thumb|left|Sign noting [[Screen Door (restaurant)|Screen Door]]'s closure]]\n\nThe city's restaurant industry was \"completely obliterated\" by the state's bar and restaurant ban.<ref name=Rogoway>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-brings-oregon-a-sudden-economic-catastrophe-the-worst-week-ever.html|title=Coronavirus brings Oregon a sudden economic catastrophe: 'The worst week ever'|first=Mike|last=Rogoway|date=March 22, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323094044/https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-brings-oregon-a-sudden-economic-catastrophe-the-worst-week-ever.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Governor Brown banned in-house consumption across Oregon, effective March 17. Some restaurants closed entirely, while others implemented [[food delivery]] and [[take-out]] operations.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/dining/2020/03/responding-to-coronavirus-pandemic-vegan-fine-dining-restaurant-farm-spirit-upscale-steakhouse-el-gaucho-will-close-temporarily.html |title=Portland restaurants close dining rooms; some offer delivery |first=Michael |last=Russell |date=March 13, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323150658/https://www.oregonlive.com/dining/2020/03/responding-to-coronavirus-pandemic-vegan-fine-dining-restaurant-farm-spirit-upscale-steakhouse-el-gaucho-will-close-temporarily.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Closures>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/13/21178995/covid-19-coronavirus-closures-portland|title=A Number of Restaurants Once Open for Takeout and Delivery Have Closed List Last Week|first=Brooke|last=Jackson-Glidden|date=March 13, 2020|website=[[Eater (website)|Eater Portland]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323144522/https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/13/21178995/covid-19-coronavirus-closures-portland|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Acadia: A New Orleans Bistro]], [[Doug Fir Lounge]], [[Ken's Artisan Pizza]], [[Le Bistro Montage]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/dining/2020/03/portland-restaurants-closed-due-to-coronavirus.html |title=Here are all the Portland restaurants to close or embrace takeout, delivery-only service |first=Michael |last=Russell |date=March 14, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323150704/https://www.oregonlive.com/dining/2020/03/portland-restaurants-closed-due-to-coronavirus.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Le Pigeon]], [[Nostrana (restaurant)|Nostrana]], [[Olympia Provisions]], [[Pok Pok]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/25/21194167/pok-pok-closed|title=The Pok Pok Empire Closes Indefinitely in Wake of Coronavirus Crisis|first=Alex|last=Frane|date=March 25, 2020|website=Eater Portland|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325210015/https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/25/21194167/pok-pok-closed|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/how-to-make-pok-poks-fish-sauce-wings-at-home.html|title=With Pok Pok restaurants closed, here's how to make those famous fish sauce wings at home|first=Michael|last=Russell|date=March 26, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327172445/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/how-to-make-pok-poks-fish-sauce-wings-at-home.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Screen Door (restaurant)|Screen Door]] all closed.<ref name=Closures/> [[Hot Lips Pizza]], [[Oven and Shaker]], and [[Sizzle Pie]] continued pizza pickup and delivery service, as of March 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/27/21194686/where-to-find-a-pizza-during-the-restaurant-shutdown|title=Where to Find a Pizza During the Restaurant Shutdown|first=Sam|last=Hill|date=March 27, 2020|website=Eater Portland|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327225926/https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/27/21194686/where-to-find-a-pizza-during-the-restaurant-shutdown|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Shine Distillery and Grill]] began producing [[hand sanitizer]] from alcohol for customers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2020/03/19/oregon-shine-distillery-making-hand-sanitizer-coronavirus-bts-ctn-vpx.cnn|title=Oregon distillery is making its own in-house hand sanitizer and giving it away|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323133625/https://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2020/03/19/oregon-shine-distillery-making-hand-sanitizer-coronavirus-bts-ctn-vpx.cnn|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Prewitt|first=Andi|url=https://www.wweek.com/bars/2020/03/10/a-portland-distillery-is-making-its-own-hand-cleaner-in-the-wake-of-coronavirus/|title=A Portland Distillery Is Making Its Own Hand Cleaner in the Wake of Coronavirus|date=March 10, 2020|work=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323043652/https://www.wweek.com/bars/2020/03/10/a-portland-distillery-is-making-its-own-hand-cleaner-in-the-wake-of-coronavirus/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-distillery-makes-hand-sanitizer-to-give-to-customers/article_c79023bc-6292-11ea-832b-e3a4b8d06435.html|title=Portland distillery makes hand sanitizer to give to customers|first=Audrey|last=Weil|publisher=KPTV|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318141255/https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-distillery-makes-hand-sanitizer-to-give-to-customers/article_c79023bc-6292-11ea-832b-e3a4b8d06435.html|archive-date=2020-03-18|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/11/21174997/shine-distillery-hand-cleaning-solution|title=North Portland's Shine Distillery Is Giving Away House-Made, 80-Percent-Alcohol Hand 'Cleaner'|first=Brooke|last=Jackson-Glidden|date=March 11, 2020|website=Eater Portland|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323043653/https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/11/21174997/shine-distillery-hand-cleaning-solution|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The website 'PDX2Go' was created to track businesses still accepting orders, and some food carts continued to operate.<ref name=Open/> The Liberty Glass, a bar and \"neighborhood institution\" in north Portland, closed permanently in mid April \"due to COVID-19-related financial concerns\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frane |first1=Alex |title=North Portland Bar Liberty Glass, a Neighborhood Institution, Will Permanently Close |url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/4/17/21225721/liberty-glass-closes-coronavirus |website=Eater Portland |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwelve of 27 laid off [[Crush Bar]] employees staged a protest and accused the owner of \"[breaking] the law by denying their use of accrued sick hours to cover lost wages\". The demonstration was supposed to last for 24 hours but was stopped by police after an hour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/17/21184325/crush-bar-sit-in-layoffs-covid-19|title=Crush Bar Employees Staged Sit-In After Mass Layoffs [Updated]|first=Alex|last=Frane|date=March 17, 2020|website=Eater Portland|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323144519/https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/17/21184325/crush-bar-sit-in-layoffs-covid-19|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[strip club]] Lucky Devil Lounge continued to offer a full menu with home delivery service by \"scantily clad strippers\" under the business operation Boober Eats.<ref name=Lucky>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-strip-club-forced-to-close-so-dancers-now-do-delivery.html|title=Portland strip club forced to close, so dancers now do delivery|first=Samantha|last=Swindler|date=March 22, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323190325/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-strip-club-forced-to-close-so-dancers-now-do-delivery.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wweek.com/bars/2020/03/17/a-portland-strip-club-has-started-a-meal-delivery-service-where-dancers-bring-food-directly-to-your-door-to-your-home/|title=A Portland Strip Club Has Started a Meal Delivery Service Where Dancers Bring Food Directly to Your Door|work=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323131431/https://www.wweek.com/bars/2020/03/17/a-portland-strip-club-has-started-a-meal-delivery-service-where-dancers-bring-food-directly-to-your-door-to-your-home/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/23/strippers-staff-boober-eats-delivery-service-during-coronavirus-lockdown/|title=Strippers staff 'Boober Eats' delivery service during coronavirus lockdown|first=Hannah|last=Sparks|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323204932/https://nypost.com/2020/03/23/strippers-staff-boober-eats-delivery-service-during-coronavirus-lockdown/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Approximately 25 strippers have participated; dancers are driven and protected by security guards, armed with gloves, masks, and hand sanitizer,<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/boober-eats-lucky-devil-lounge-strip-club-covid-19-coronavirus-quarantine-971544/|title=With Clubs Closed for COVID-19, Strippers in Portland, Oregon, Take to Topless Food Delivery|first1=E. J.|last1=Dickson|first2=E. J.|last2=Dickson|date=March 23, 2020|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323224406/https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/boober-eats-lucky-devil-lounge-strip-club-covid-19-coronavirus-quarantine-971544/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and touching by customers is not allowed.<ref name=Lucky/>\n\n====Hospitality industry====\nThe [[hospitality industry]] also experienced a wave of guest cancellations followed by a decline in bookings.<ref name=Hotels/> The [[Jupiter Hotel (Portland, Oregon)|Jupiter Hotel]] laid off half its staff by March 18 after daily occupancy rates fell to 7\u201320 percent.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-hotels-lay-off-workers-question-survival-after-wave-of-coronavirus-cancellations.html |title=Oregon hotels lay off workers, question futures after wave of coronavirus cancellations |first=Jamie |last=Goldberg |date=March 19, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323225544/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-hotels-lay-off-workers-question-survival-after-wave-of-coronavirus-cancellations.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Jupiter partnered with Multnomah County to use the hotel's 81 rooms as a temporary homeless shelter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pamplinmedia.com/go/42-news/459054-373887-portlands-jupiter-hotel-becomes-coronavirus-shelter-for-medically-fragile-homeless-people|title=Portland's Jupiter Hotel becomes coronavirus shelter for medically fragile homeless people|first=Molly|last=Harbarger|date=March 26, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327170944/https://pamplinmedia.com/go/42-news/459054-373887-portlands-jupiter-hotel-becomes-coronavirus-shelter-for-medically-fragile-homeless-people|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katu.com/news/local/portland-hotel-donates-rooms-to-help-homeless-with-coronavirus-symptoms-stay-in-quarantine|title=Portland hotel donates rooms to help homeless with coronavirus symptoms stay in quarantine|first=KATU|last=Staff|date=March 26, 2020|website=KATU|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327170950/https://katu.com/news/local/portland-hotel-donates-rooms-to-help-homeless-with-coronavirus-symptoms-stay-in-quarantine|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Hanson|first=Nate|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/homeless/jupiter-hotel-homeless-shelter-portland-coronavirus/283-370d4b13-f607-4460-98ed-6a6d5465d83d|title=Jupiter Hotel in Portland to become homeless shelter during coronavirus pandemic|date=March 26, 2020|publisher=KGW|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327170943/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/homeless/jupiter-hotel-homeless-shelter-portland-coronavirus/283-370d4b13-f607-4460-98ed-6a6d5465d83d|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[The Nines (hotel)|The Nines]] suspended hotel and restaurant operations on March 19, effective March 22.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-luxury-hotel-nines-suspends-services-due-to-covid/article_6b47548a-6a40-11ea-adb7-4f0a8a298283.html|title=Portland luxury hotel Nines suspends services due to COVID-19|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324141326/https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-luxury-hotel-nines-suspends-services-due-to-covid/article_6b47548a-6a40-11ea-adb7-4f0a8a298283.html|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Hyatt Regency Portland]], which opened in December 2019, also suspended operations in March.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/14/business/convention-hotels-municipal-bonds-coronavirus.html</ref> In early April, Travel Portland reported approximately 80 percent decreases in the demand for lodging, revenue, and occupancy rates in Portland compared to last year.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/hotel-demand-in-portland-down-roughly-80-percent-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html</ref> The president of Provenance Hotels, which owns or manages six hotels in Portland, left the company in mid April because of the pandemic.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/04/bashar-wali-to-leave-provenance-hotels-covid-19-convinced-him-to-change-course.html</ref>\n\n====Impact on professional sports====\n[[File:Providence Park box office notice - closed due to COVID-19 epidemic, 3-16-2020.jpg|thumb|Box office closure sign at [[Providence Park]], home of the [[Portland Timbers]] and [[Portland Thorns FC]], on March 16, 2020]]\n\nFollowing season suspensions by the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/local/mls-suspends-season-due-to-coronavirus-delaying-timbers-season|title=MLS suspends season due to coronavirus, delaying Timbers season|first=Evan|last=Schreiber|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=KATU|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324024859/https://katu.com/news/local/mls-suspends-season-due-to-coronavirus-delaying-timbers-season|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] and [[Portland Timbers]] canceled games.<ref name=Rogoway/> The Trail Blazers and Timbers games averaged approximately 19,000 and 25,000 people at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/service-industry-portland-coronavirus-nba-mls-moda-center/|title=Portland Service Industry Reeling And Uncertain With NBA, MLS On Hold|first1=Troy|last1=Brynelson|first2=Bradley W.|last2=Parks|date=March 16, 2020|publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323131406/https://www.opb.org/news/article/service-industry-portland-coronavirus-nba-mls-moda-center/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> MLS initially announced a 30-day suspension, when the Timbers were scheduled to play at [[Providence Park]] five times between March 12 and mid April.<ref name=NBC>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/portland-timbers/breaking-mls-suspends-season-due-coronavirus|title=BREAKING: MLS suspends season due to coronavirus|date=March 12, 2020|website=NBC Sports Northwest|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324024538/https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/portland-timbers/breaking-mls-suspends-season-due-coronavirus|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The soccer league extended the suspension to eight weeks on March 19.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Goldberg|first=Jamie|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/major-league-soccer-extends-season-postponement-for-another-month/283-d59a5f0d-0416-4929-893e-73399e61476f|title=Major League Soccer extends season postponement for another month|date=March 19, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324025836/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/major-league-soccer-extends-season-postponement-for-another-month/283-d59a5f0d-0416-4929-893e-73399e61476f|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Portland Thorns FC]]'s pre-season tournament slated for March 29 \u2013 April 4 was canceled on March 12, shortly before the [[National Women's Soccer League]] canceled pre-season games across the league.<ref name=Thorns>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/portland-thorns/2020/03/portland-thorns-cancel-preseason-tournament-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Thorns cancel preseason tournament amid coronavirus outbreak|first=Jamie|last=Goldberg|date=March 12, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324025317/https://www.oregonlive.com/portland-thorns/2020/03/portland-thorns-cancel-preseason-tournament-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Timbers and Thorns tickets will be valid for rescheduled matches, as of March 12.<ref name=Thorns/> On March 17, the Timbers and Thorns announced part-time workers would still receive compensation for canceled games, among other community initiatives.<ref>{{Cite news|author=KGW Staff|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/portland-timbers-thorns-to-pay-part-time-workers/283-ae77774b-161a-4b19-9699-266bd9ef8e26|title=Portland Timbers, Thorns to pay part-time workers for games missed during coronavirus outbreak|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324025854/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/portland-timbers-thorns-to-pay-part-time-workers/283-ae77774b-161a-4b19-9699-266bd9ef8e26|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Damian Lillard]] encouraged fans to remain at home and practice social distancing. He said on the NBA's [[Instagram]] account on March 23, \"I've been washing my hands, social distancing \u2014 keep your space. Don't join in crowds, stay in small groups. It'd be best to stay in the house. I hope everybody is stocked up on everything they need so they can stay safe. Do everything the way we've been asked to help this pass faster. Like I said, ya'll stay safe, ya'll be good, man.\"<ref name=Lillard/>\n\n==Impact on education==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education}}\n[[File:Portland, Oregon during the coronavirus pandemic, March 2020 - 05.jpg|thumb|Sign noting [[Reed College]]'s closure]]\n\nGovernor Brown initially closed schools all K\u201312 schools through March 31.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/portland-metro-school-district-tigard-tualatin-lake-oswego-coronavirus-board-meeting-emergency-covid-students/|title=Brown orders all K-12 schools closed through March|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323210338/https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/portland-metro-school-district-tigard-tualatin-lake-oswego-coronavirus-board-meeting-emergency-covid-students/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A four-week extension was added; students are scheduled to return on April 28. [[Portland Public Schools (Oregon)|Portland Public Schools]] designated 15 buildings as sites for student meal distributions, and has considered providing 45,000 devices to students for [[distance education]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-public-schools-begins-plans-for-6-week-closure.html|title=Portland Public Schools begins plans for 6-week closure|first=Eder|last=Campuzano|date=March 18, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323131440/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-public-schools-begins-plans-for-6-week-closure.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> High school and college graduation ceremonies were canceled.<ref name=Rogoway/> On April 8, Brown extended the school closures through to the end of the 2019\u20132020 school year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katu.com/news/local/oregon-gov-brown-addresses-education-issues-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Oregon Gov. Brown Addresses Education Issues Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|archive-date=April 8, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAll Multnomah County Library branches were closed on March 13.<ref name=MCL/> The library system waived late fees and continued to provide public [[Wi-Fi]].<ref name=Open/>\n\nStudents at [[Oregon Health & Science University]] and the University of Portland began offering childcare and errand services for local health care professionals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-area-healthcare-workers-can-request-free-childcare-other-support-from-local-medical-and-nursing-students.html|title=Portland-area healthcare workers can request free childcare, other support from local medical and nursing students|first=Amy|last=Wang|date=March 21, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323181637/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-area-healthcare-workers-can-request-free-childcare-other-support-from-local-medical-and-nursing-students.html|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Universities and collegiate sports===\n[[Portland State University]] canceled in-person final exams,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/schools/2020/03/12/portland-state-university-cancels-in-person-final-exams-moves-spring-classes-online/|title=Portland State University Cancels In-Person Final Exams, Moves Spring Classes Online|last=Mesh|first=Aaron|last2=|first2=|date=March 12, 2020|newspaper=Willamette Week|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313034235/https://www.wweek.com/news/schools/2020/03/12/portland-state-university-cancels-in-person-final-exams-moves-spring-classes-online/|archive-date=March 13, 2020|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=|first3=}}</ref> and eliminated in-person classes for the spring term, opting for distance learning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-state-university-will-not-resume-in-person-classes-this-spring.html|title=Portland State will not resume in-person classes this spring|last=Goldberg|first=Jamie|date=March 19, 2020|newspaper=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325150842/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-state-university-will-not-resume-in-person-classes-this-spring.html|archive-date=March 25, 2020|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The [[University of Portland]] moved to online instruction and canceled all sports games and practices for the spring term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/university-of-oregon-classes-remotely-coronavirus/283-b5b5abc3-463f-442a-abc6-964fb9036d54|title=UO, OSU, PSU, UP to cancel in-person classes amid coronavirus outbreak|publisher=KGW|access-date=2020-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313070840/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/university-of-oregon-classes-remotely-coronavirus/283-b5b5abc3-463f-442a-abc6-964fb9036d54|archive-date=2020-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/pilots/2020/03/university-of-portland-pilots-cancel-all-future-spring-sports-events-activities-due-to-coronavirus.html|title=University of Portland Pilots cancel all future spring sports events, activities due to coronavirus|last=Brown|first=Tim|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401233443/https://www.oregonlive.com/pilots/2020/03/university-of-portland-pilots-cancel-all-future-spring-sports-events-activities-due-to-coronavirus.html|archive-date=April 1, 2020|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> [[Lewis and Clark College]], [[Linfield College]], and [[Willamette University]] also implemented distance learning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/university-of-portland-willamette-cancel-in-person-classes-latest-colleges-to-shift-amid-coronavirus-concerns.html|title=University of Portland, Willamette, Lewis & Clark, Linfield cancel in-person classes amid coronavirus concerns|last=Davis|first=Rob|date=March 12, 2020|newspaper=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404102829/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/university-of-portland-willamette-cancel-in-person-classes-latest-colleges-to-shift-amid-coronavirus-concerns.html|archive-date=April 4, 2020|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on public transit==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on public transport}}\n[[File:Coronavirus physical-distancing sticker on door of a MAX light rail car.jpg|thumb|Sticker on the glass of a door of a TriMet MAX Light Rail car encouraging physical distancing on board]]\n[[File:TriMet bus with seats marked by \"Don't sit here\" signs during coronavirus pandemic, April 2020.jpg|thumb|Signs in a [[TriMet]] bus promoting physical distancing during a temporary 10-passenger limit imposed in April]]\n\nOn March 5, 2020, workers of the Portland area's regional transit agency, [[TriMet]], began nightly disinfections of the interior surfaces of its buses, [[MAX Light Rail]] and [[WES Commuter Rail]] trains, and LIFT [[paratransit]] vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/05/amid-coronavirus-fear-trimet-begins-nightly-wipedown-of-bus-and-train-doors/ |last=Mesh |first=Aaron |title=Amid Coronavirus Fear, TriMet Begins Nightly Wipedown of Bus and Train Doors |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |date=March 5, 2020 |access-date=March 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306232656/https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/05/amid-coronavirus-fear-trimet-begins-nightly-wipedown-of-bus-and-train-doors/ |archive-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Prevent>{{cite news |url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/what-pdx-trimet-and-others-are-doing-to-keep-customers-staff-safe-from-coronavirus/283-c1d5be93-c504-41f4-91a1-5468534eba33 |last=Cowley |first=Jared |title=What PDX, TriMet and others are doing to prevent the spread of coronavirus |publisher=[[KGW]] |date=March 11, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325030145/https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/what-pdx-trimet-and-others-are-doing-to-keep-customers-staff-safe-from-coronavirus/283-c1d5be93-c504-41f4-91a1-5468534eba33 |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later on March 19, TriMet reported a significant decrease in ridership; approximately 140,000 fewer people rode TriMet vehicles compared to the weekday average in February.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/commuting/2020/03/trimet-is-not-cutting-service-yet-but-everything-is-on-the-table-amid-coronavirus-fears.html |last=Theen |first=Andrew |title=TriMet is not cutting service yet, but 'everything is on the table' amid coronavirus fears |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323131256/https://www.oregonlive.com/commuting/2020/03/trimet-is-not-cutting-service-yet-but-everything-is-on-the-table-amid-coronavirus-fears.html |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/trimet-sees-decrease-in-ridership-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ |last1=Powell |first1=Meerah |last2=Vance |first2=Bryan M. |title=TriMet Sees Decrease In Ridership Amid Coronavirus Outbreak |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323163842/https://www.opb.org/news/article/trimet-sees-decrease-in-ridership-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 28, the agency announced reductions to its services.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://katu.com/news/local/trimet-to-adjust-schedules-because-of-steep-drop-in-ridership |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=TriMet to adjust schedules because of steep drop in ridership |publisher=[[KATU]] |date=March 28, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329055217/https://katu.com/news/local/trimet-to-adjust-schedules-because-of-steep-drop-in-ridership |archive-date=March 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Effective April 5, MAX trains began running every 15{{nbsp}}minutes while WES trains ran every 45{{nbsp}}minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/trimet-reduces-train-and-bus-service/ |last=Powell |first=Meerah |title=TriMet Reduces Train, Bus Service In Response To Decreased Ridership |publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting |date=March 28, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328210920/https://www.opb.org/news/article/trimet-reduces-train-and-bus-service/ |archive-date=March 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> 84 bus lines saw schedule changes and the 272\u2013PDX Night Bus route was suspended.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/alerts/reducedservice.htm |title=Reduced Service |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329202724/https://trimet.org/alerts/reducedservice.htm |archive-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ptld-trib-trimet-reductions\">{{cite news |last1=Redden |first1=Jim |title=TriMet: Service reductions take effect Sunday |url=https://pamplinmedia.com/pt/9-news/460992-374755-trimet-service-reductions-take-effect-sunday |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |work=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>  On its website,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/health/ |title=COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Updates |publisher=[[TriMet]] |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325062205/https://trimet.org/health/ |archive-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> TriMet requested the public to \"maintain six feet of distance from other riders and the operator.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/19/28168598/fewer-riders-more-cleaning-heightened-uncertainty-how-are-trimet-employees-managing-the-covid-19-outbreak |last=Stenvick |first=Blair |title=Fewer Riders, More Cleaning, Heightened Uncertainty: How Are TriMet Employees Managing the COVID-19 Outbreak? |newspaper=[[Portland Mercury]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130807/https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/19/28168598/fewer-riders-more-cleaning-heightened-uncertainty-how-are-trimet-employees-managing-the-covid-19-outbreak |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The agency also asked people to \"only take transit if necessary.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/23/trimet-please-only-take-transit-if-necessary.html |last=Danko |first=Pete |title=TriMet: 'Please only take transit if necessary' |newspaper=[[Portland Business Journal]] |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 26, TriMet temporarily stopped accepting cash payment of fares on buses, asking all riders to pay with the [[Hop Fastpass]] system, so as to minimize the time that boarding passengers spend near the driver.<ref name=\"WW-TriMet-No-Cash-Buses\">{{cite news |last1=Mesh |first1=Aaron |title=TriMet Will No Longer Accept Cash Fares on Buses |url=https://www.wweek.com/news/city/2020/03/26/trimet-will-not-longer-accept-cash-fares-on-buses/ |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |work=[[Willamette Week]] |date=March 26, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327205626/https://www.wweek.com/news/city/2020/03/26/trimet-will-not-longer-accept-cash-fares-on-buses/ |archivedate=March 27, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On April 9, the agency indefinitely imposed a temporary limit of 10 passengers per bus, or up to 15 if including family members traveling together, and began installing signs on bus seats to enforce this physical distancing.<ref name=\"don't sit here signs\">{{cite news |last1=Theen |first1=Andrew |title=TriMet placing \u2018don\u2019t sit here\u2019 signs on bus seats, limiting passengers to 15 per bus |work=The Oregonian |date=April 2, 2020<!--(print edition of April 3, p. A10)--> |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/commuting/2020/04/coronavirus-in-oregon-trimet-to-place-dont-sit-here-signs-on-bus-seats-no-more-than-15-passengers-allowed.html |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther transit agencies across the region have adopted similar measures, as well as measures to assist community members in need. On March 19, [[South Metro Area Regional Transit]] (SMART) buses in [[Wilsonville, Oregon|Wilsonville]] began temporarily operating fare-free in support of transit-dependent commuters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ridesmart.com/transit/page/temporary-free-rides-all-smart-routes |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Temporary FREE RIDES on all SMART Routes |publisher=[[South Metro Area Regional Transit]] |date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325065703/https://www.ridesmart.com/transit/page/temporary-free-rides-all-smart-routes |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2020|3|24|df=us}}, SMART services continue to operate without any schedule reductions.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ridesmart.com/transit/page/transit-covid-19-coronavirus-updates |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=TRANSIT COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Updates |publisher=South Metro Area Regional Transit |date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325065621/https://www.ridesmart.com/transit/page/transit-covid-19-coronavirus-updates |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 23, the [[Portland Streetcar]] reduced its regular weekday schedule from every 15{{nbsp}}minutes to every 20{{nbsp}}minutes in response to the statewide stay-at-home order.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/news/2020/03/streetcar-service-will-reduce-to-20-minute-headways-beginning-march-24 |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Streetcar Service Will Reduce to 20-Minute Headways Beginning March 24 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar]] |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325063529/https://portlandstreetcar.org/news/2020/03/streetcar-service-will-reduce-to-20-minute-headways-beginning-march-24 |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy March 2, the [[Port of Portland (Oregon)|Port of Portland]] had increased the rate of cleanings at the [[Portland International Airport]] and at marine centers. The [[port authority]] focus on information and pay stations, shuttle buses, and valet booths, following recommendations issued by the county and CDC, and made hand sanitizer available for people using ground transportation.<ref name=Prevent/> The [[taxicab]] company Radio Cab also improved cleaning procedures.<ref name=Prevent/>\n\n==Impact on religion==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\n[[File:Aletheia Bible Fellowship Web Sermons Only during Coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|Sign of a Portland church live streaming sermons]]\n\nSeveral Portland area churches, mosques, synagogues, and other places of worship canceled or elected to live stream services, including [[Congregation Neveh Shalom]] and the [[First Unitarian Church of Portland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/religious-and-faith-communities-continue-services-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Religious And Faith Communities Continue Services Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|first=Meerah|last=Powell|date=March 26, 2020|publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]]|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328200817/https://www.opb.org/news/article/religious-and-faith-communities-continue-services-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/if-you-are-worshipping-this-weekend-you-might-want-to-check-ahead.html|title=Coronavirus and church: If you are worshipping this weekend, you might want to check ahead|date=March 14, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324031632/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/if-you-are-worshipping-this-weekend-you-might-want-to-check-ahead.html|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Portland's Bridgetown Church began offering services online via [[Zoom Video Communications]]. The city's largest mosque, [[Masjid As-Saber]], suspended [[Friday prayer]]s and asked worshippers to stay at home.<ref name=Open/>\n\nArchbishop [[Alexander King Sample]] of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Portland in Oregon|Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Portland]] encouraged priests to \"be creative\" with regard to accessibility,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/14/world/churches-mosques-temples-coronavirus-spread/index.html|title=What churches, mosques and temples are doing to fight the spread of coronavirus|first=Daniel|last=Burke|date=March 14, 2020|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314232611/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/14/world/churches-mosques-temples-coronavirus-spread/index.html|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"issued directives for parishes to cancel any event over 250 people and encouraged those aged over 60 or with underlying medical issues to consider not attending Mass and dispensed them of the obligation\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.statesmanjournal.com/story/news/2020/03/13/oregon-coronavirus-school-closures-salem-keizer-public-schools/5040931002/|title=Coronavirus: Oregon schools close, doctors demand state action, warming shelter closed|first1=Whitney|last1=Woodworth|first2=Virginia|last2=Barreda|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=[[Statesman Journal]]|location=Salem, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Masses were canceled until April 14, which included Holy Week and Easter. Archbishop Sample said the announcement was \"by far one of the most difficult communications [he has] ever written\".<ref>{{cite news |title=PUBLIC MASSES HALTED TO SLOW VIRUS |url=https://catholicsentinel.org/Content/News/Local/Article/PUBLIC-MASSES-HALTED-TO-SLOW-VIRUS/2/35/39515 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Catholic Sentinel]] |publisher=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Portland in Oregon]] |date=March 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325010853/https://catholicsentinel.org/Content/News/Local/Article/PUBLIC-MASSES-HALTED-TO-SLOW-VIRUS/2/35/39515 |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[The Grotto]] has suspended Mass until March 31, but visitors are welcome to visit the outdoor sanctuary and Upper Gardens.<ref name=Stein/>\n\n==Crime==\nOn March 23, the [[Multnomah County Sheriff's Office]] said the crime rate for the month to date was lower than the rate for March 2019. The same office had announced that they're not booking misdemeanor arrests and giving out citations instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/20/ppb-will-not-take-misdemeanor-arrests-to-jail-during-covid-19-outbreak-to-avoid-overcrowding/|title=Portland Police Will Not Take Misdemeanor Arrests to Jail During the COVID-19 Outbreak, to Avoid Overcrowding|last=Riski|first=Tess|last2=|first2=|date=March 20, 2020|website=Willamette Week|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14|last3=|first3=|last4=|first4=|last5=|first5=|last6=}}</ref> The agency also reported lower jail bookings and moved some inmates at the Inverness Jail in northeast Portland into temporary dormitory-style housing to follow social distancing measures.<ref name=\"Crime\">{{cite news |last1=Heye |first1=Bob |title=Coronavirus and Crime: Jail releases, a rash of break-ins and one encouraging trend |url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/coronavirus-and-crime-jail-releases-a-rash-of-break-ins-and-one-encouraging-trend |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=KATU |agency=Sinclair Broadcast Group |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325010138/https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/coronavirus-and-crime-jail-releases-a-rash-of-break-ins-and-one-encouraging-trend |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[KATU]] reported on a string of business break-ins in the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]].<ref name=Crime/> The crisis group Call to Safety, which supports people experiencing [[domestic violence]], began receiving twice as many calls and more requests for shelter and other resources once stay-at-home orders were enforced.<ref name=\"domeshelter\">{{cite news |last1=Crombie |first1=Noelle |title=Calls to Oregon's domestic violence crisis lines spike amid coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/crime/2020/03/calls-to-oregons-domestic-violence-crisis-lines-spike-amid-coronavirus-crisis.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |publisher=Advance Local Media |date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325013354/https://www.oregonlive.com/crime/2020/03/calls-to-oregons-domestic-violence-crisis-lines-spike-amid-coronavirus-crisis.html |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Thousands of [[respirator]] masks valued at approximately $2,500 were stolen from the Rebuilding Center in north Portland in March. Some of the masks were recovered and donated to local hospitals.<ref name=Crime/><ref name=\"stealmask\">{{cite news |author1=Nexstar Media Wire |title=Thousands of stolen N95 masks recovered in Portland, donated |url=https://www.ksn.com/news/thousands-of-stolen-n95-masks-recovered-donated/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=KSN |date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325013354/https://www.ksn.com/news/thousands-of-stolen-n95-masks-recovered-donated/ |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In April, federal investigators seized 100 coronavirus test kits shipped from China to an apartment in Portland.<ref>https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/feds-intercept-100-coronavirus-test-kits-shipped-to-portland-apartment/283-7c78c97e-2267-46de-b2cd-7a49a11e70de</ref>\n\n== Healthcare industry ==\nThe local [[healthcare industry]] was significantly impacted by the pandemic. Governor Kate Brown has said non-emergency medical procedures can resume starting May 1.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/non-emergency-medical-procedures-can-resume-in-oregon-on-may-1-gov-kate-brown-says.html</ref> On March 27, Portland began nightly \"solidarity cheers\" to recognize health care and other frontline workers, similar to many other cities around the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-urges-nightly-solidarity-cheer-for-frontline-coronavirus-workers.html|title=Portland urges nightly solidarity cheer for frontline coronavirus workers|first=Everton|last=Bailey Jr|date=March 27, 2020|work=The Oregonian|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328201448/https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-urges-nightly-solidarity-cheer-for-frontline-coronavirus-workers.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Portland, Oregon}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.travelportland.com/about-us/covid-19/|title=COVID-19 and the Portland Community|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=Travel Portland}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Zielinski |first1=Alex |title=\"I hope everything I'm telling you isn't true\": A Portland Oncology Nurse On COVID-19 |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/21/28177144/i-hope-everything-im-telling-you-isnt-true-a-portland-oncology-nurse-on-covid-19 |work=Portland Mercury |date=March 21, 2020}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Oregon|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:2020 in Portland, Oregon|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Oregon]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Health in Oregon]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Truflip99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eImpact on public transit:logical quotation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Portland,_Oregon"}
{"title_page": "Charles Booker (American politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Charles Booker\n| image               = Charles solar panels (cropped).jpg\n| state_house         = Kentucky\n| district            = 43rd\n| term_start          = January 1, 2019\n| predecessor         = [[Darryl Owens]]\n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth year and age|1984|10}}\n| birth_place         = [[Louisville, Kentucky]]\n| spouse              = Tanesha\n| children            = 2\n| alma_mater          = [[University of Louisville]] {{Small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n| website             = www.BookerforKentucky.com\n}}\n'''Charles Booker''' (born 1984) is an American politician from the [[Commonwealth (U.S. state)|commonwealth]] of [[Kentucky]]. He serves in the [[Kentucky House of Representatives]] for the 43rd district, and is currently Kentucky's youngest black state lawmaker.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kentucky\u2019s Youngest Black State Lawmaker Wants To Challenge Mitch McConnell|author=Travis Waldron|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/charles-booker-mitch-mcconnell-kentucky-senate_n_5dc95c22e4b02bf579437897|publisher=[[Huffington Post]]|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Booker is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], and is running for the Democratic nomination for Mitch McConnell's [[2020 United States Senate election in Kentucky|Kentucky Senate Seat in the 2020 election]].<ref name=CourierJournal>{{cite news |last1=Bailey |first1=Phillip M. |title=Democrat Charles Booker is running for US Senate in 2020 |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/2020/01/05/democrat-charles-booker-decides-2020-us-senate-bid/2794647001/ |accessdate=January 12, 2020 |publisher=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBooker graduated from [[Louisville Male High School]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]], and earned his [[bachelor's degree]] and [[Juris Doctor]] from the [[University of Louisville]].<ref name=forwardky/> \n\n== Career ==\nBooker worked for the [[Legislative Research Commission]] until 2014, when he was fired for appearing in a campaign video of [[Alison Lundergan Grimes]], a candidate in the [[2014 United States Senate election in Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web|work=The Courier-Journal|url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/local/2014/02/17/legislative-employee-fired-for-appearing-in-grimes-campaign-video/5564469/ |title=LRC employee fired for appearing in Grimes video |date=February 18, 2014 |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> He then worked for the [[Kentucky Department of Fish and Wildlife Resources]] and West Louisville FoodPort.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brammer|first1=Jack|url=https://www.kentucky.com/news/politics-government/election/article44486238.html|title=Legislative aide who was fired after appearing in Grimes video lands better-paying state job|date=April 23, 2014|accessdate=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]}}</ref> In 2016, he ran against [[Gerald Neal]] in the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] [[primary election]] for the 33rd district of the [[Kentucky Senate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/01/26/sen-gerald-neal-draws-2-primary-challengers/79359994/ |title=Sen. Gerald Neal draws 2 primary challengers |publisher=Courier-journal.com |date= |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> Booker finished in third place with 20 percent of the vote, behind Neal, who received 48 percent, and Joan Stringer, who received 32 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wdrb.com/news/gerald-neal-wins-democratic-nomination-in-district-kentucky-senate-race/article_2e8f5bdc-eb92-59e5-9ce1-8bdf0daf46e1.html |title=Gerald Neal wins Democratic nomination in District 33 Kentucky Senate race &#124; News |publisher=wdrb.com |date=May 17, 2016 |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[Darryl Owens]]' retirement from representing the 43rd district in the [[Kentucky House of Representatives]] in 2018, Booker ran to succeed him. In a field of seven candidates, Booker won the Democratic nomination with 29.5 percent of the vote,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wdrb.com/news/longtime-state-rep-horlander-ousted-in-democratic-primary/article_d779683b-a78e-5ecc-93b5-94d12e8f625e.html |title=Longtime state Rep. Horlander ousted in Democratic primary &#124; News |publisher=wdrb.com |date=May 22, 2018 |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> and defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Everett Corley in the general election by 56 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wdrb.com/news/two-louisville-gop-representatives-lose-re-election-bids/article_1bb7cfa9-5629-548c-a67b-209363dba943.html |title=Two Louisville GOP representatives lose re-election bids &#124; News |publisher=wdrb.com |date=November 6, 2018 |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn January 5, 2020, Booker formally entered the [[2020 United States Senate election in Kentucky|2020 Kentucky Senate race]].<ref name=\"CourierJournal\" /> A [[Progressivism|progressive]] Democrat, Booker supported the [[Bernie Sanders 2020 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/6c2f2730f15534f8d5169726b553da40|title=Senate hopeful Booker endorses Sanders for president|date=2020-03-03|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Booker had advocated for [[universal health care]], a [[green new deal]] to tackle climate change, and [[universal basic income]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2020/03/12/not-time-half-measures-progressives-demand-far-reaching-economic-and-public-health|title='Not the Time for Half-Measures': Progressives Demand Far-Reaching Economic and Public Health Assistance as Coronavirus Spreads|website=Common Dreams|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cheddar.com/media/mcconnell-s-challenger-in-kentucky-wants-ubi-medicare-for-all|title=McConnell\u2019s Challenger in Kentucky Wants UBI, Medicare for All|website=Cheddar|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nBooker and his wife, Tanesha, have two daughters, and live in [[Russell, Louisville]].<ref name=forwardky>{{cite web|author=Berry Craig |url=https://forwardky.com/charles-booker-part-of-a-bluegrass-wave-coming-to-frankfort/ |title=Charles Booker part of a \"Bluegrass wave\" coming to Frankfort |publisher=Forwardky.com |date=August 30, 2018 |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongLinks|votesmart=167536}}\n\n{{Kentucky House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Booker, Charles}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the Kentucky House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:University of Louisville School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Charles Booker\n| image               = Charles solar panels (cropped).jpg\n| state_house         = Kentucky\n| district            = 43rd\n| term_start          = January 1, 2019\n| predecessor         = [[Darryl Owens]]\n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth year and age|1984|10}}\n| birth_place         = [[Louisville, Kentucky]]\n| spouse              = Tanesha\n| children            = 2\n| alma_mater          = [[University of Louisville]] {{Small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n| website             = www.BookerforKentucky.com\n}}\n'''Charles Booker''' (born 1984) is an American politician from the [[Commonwealth (U.S. state)|commonwealth]] of [[Kentucky]]. He serves in the [[Kentucky House of Representatives]] for the 43rd district, and is currently Kentucky's youngest black state lawmaker.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kentucky\u2019s Youngest Black State Lawmaker Wants To Challenge Mitch McConnell|author=Travis Waldron|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/charles-booker-mitch-mcconnell-kentucky-senate_n_5dc95c22e4b02bf579437897|publisher=[[Huffington Post]]|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Booker is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], and is running for the Democratic nomination for Mitch McConnell's [[2020 United States Senate election in Kentucky|Kentucky Senate Seat in the 2020 election]].<ref name=CourierJournal>{{cite news |last1=Bailey |first1=Phillip M. |title=Democrat Charles Booker is running for US Senate in 2020 |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/2020/01/05/democrat-charles-booker-decides-2020-us-senate-bid/2794647001/ |accessdate=January 12, 2020 |publisher=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBooker graduated from [[Louisville Male High School]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]], and earned his [[bachelor's degree]] and [[Juris Doctor]] from the [[University of Louisville]].<ref name=forwardky/> \n\n== Career ==\nBooker worked for the [[Legislative Research Commission]] until 2014, when he was fired for appearing in a campaign video of [[Alison Lundergan Grimes]], a candidate in the [[2014 United States Senate election in Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web|work=The Courier-Journal|url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/local/2014/02/17/legislative-employee-fired-for-appearing-in-grimes-campaign-video/5564469/ |title=LRC employee fired for appearing in Grimes video |date=February 18, 2014 |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> He then worked for the [[Kentucky Department of Fish and Wildlife Resources]] and West Louisville FoodPort.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brammer|first1=Jack|url=https://www.kentucky.com/news/politics-government/election/article44486238.html|title=Legislative aide who was fired after appearing in Grimes video lands better-paying state job|date=April 23, 2014|accessdate=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]}}</ref> In 2016, he ran against [[Gerald Neal]] in the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] [[primary election]] for the 33rd district of the [[Kentucky Senate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/01/26/sen-gerald-neal-draws-2-primary-challengers/79359994/ |title=Sen. Gerald Neal draws 2 primary challengers |publisher=Courier-journal.com |date= |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> Booker finished in third place with 20 percent of the vote, behind Neal, who received 48 percent, and Joan Stringer, who received 32 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wdrb.com/news/gerald-neal-wins-democratic-nomination-in-district-kentucky-senate-race/article_2e8f5bdc-eb92-59e5-9ce1-8bdf0daf46e1.html |title=Gerald Neal wins Democratic nomination in District 33 Kentucky Senate race &#124; News |publisher=wdrb.com |date=May 17, 2016 |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[Darryl Owens]]' retirement from representing the 43rd district in the [[Kentucky House of Representatives]] in 2018, Booker ran to succeed him. In a field of seven candidates, Booker won the Democratic nomination with 29.5 percent of the vote,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wdrb.com/news/longtime-state-rep-horlander-ousted-in-democratic-primary/article_d779683b-a78e-5ecc-93b5-94d12e8f625e.html |title=Longtime state Rep. Horlander ousted in Democratic primary &#124; News |publisher=wdrb.com |date=May 22, 2018 |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> and defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Everett Corley in the general election by 56 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wdrb.com/news/two-louisville-gop-representatives-lose-re-election-bids/article_1bb7cfa9-5629-548c-a67b-209363dba943.html |title=Two Louisville GOP representatives lose re-election bids &#124; News |publisher=wdrb.com |date=November 6, 2018 |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn January 5, 2020, Booker formally entered the [[2020 United States Senate election in Kentucky|2020 Kentucky Senate race]].<ref name=\"CourierJournal\" /> A [[Progressivism|progressive]] Democrat, Booker supported the [[Bernie Sanders 2020 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/6c2f2730f15534f8d5169726b553da40|title=Senate hopeful Booker endorses Sanders for president|date=2020-03-03|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Booker had advocated for [[universal health care]], and a [[universal basic income]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2020/03/12/not-time-half-measures-progressives-demand-far-reaching-economic-and-public-health|title='Not the Time for Half-Measures': Progressives Demand Far-Reaching Economic and Public Health Assistance as Coronavirus Spreads|website=Common Dreams|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cheddar.com/media/mcconnell-s-challenger-in-kentucky-wants-ubi-medicare-for-all|title=McConnell\u2019s Challenger in Kentucky Wants UBI, Medicare for All|website=Cheddar|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nBooker and his wife, Tanesha, have two daughters, and live in [[Russell, Louisville]].<ref name=forwardky>{{cite web|author=Berry Craig |url=https://forwardky.com/charles-booker-part-of-a-bluegrass-wave-coming-to-frankfort/ |title=Charles Booker part of a \"Bluegrass wave\" coming to Frankfort |publisher=Forwardky.com |date=August 30, 2018 |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongLinks|votesmart=167536}}\n\n{{Kentucky House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Booker, Charles}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the Kentucky House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:University of Louisville School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Starklinson", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Booker_(American_politician)"}
